{"title_page": "Melissa Broder", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               =  Melissa Broder\n| image              =  Is Technology Enriching Language - b - Melissa Broder 2017.jpg\n| image_upright =\n| image_size = <!-- DISCOURAGED per WP:IMGSIZE. Use image_upright. -->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = 2017\n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         =  <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         =  <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = \n| monuments          = \n| residence          = Los Angeles\n| nationality        = \n| citizenship        = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Tufts University]] (BA), [[City College of New York]] (MFA)\n| occupation         = Poet, essayist\n| agent              =  \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = ''So Sad Today'', ''The Pisces'', ''Last Sext''\n| style              = \n| home_town          = [[Bryn Mawr, Pennsylvania]]\n| movement           = \n| spouse             =  <!-- Use article title or common name -->\n| partner            =  <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = \n| parents            =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n| mother             =  <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| father             =  <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| awards             = [[Pushcart Prize]]\n| website            =  {{URL|melissabroder.com}}\n}}\n'''Melissa Broder''' is a poet and writer. Her work includes the novel ''The Pisces'' ([[Penguin Random House]] 2018),<ref name=\":nyt\">{{cite news|last1=Syme|first1=Rachel|title=In 'The Pisces,' a Woman and a Merman Fall in Love. Aquatic Erotica Ensues.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/26/books/the-pisces-melissa-broder.html|accessdate=May 14, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref> the poetry collection ''Last Sext'' ([[Tin House]] 2016)<ref>{{cite news|title=Fiction Book Review: Last Sext by Melissa Broder|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-941040-33-1|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=Publishers Weekly|date=April 18, 2016}}</ref> and essay collection ''So Sad Today'' ([[Grand Central Publishing|Grand Central]] 2016),<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|last1=Joiner|first1=Whitney|title=Why Is Melissa Broder So Sad Today?|url=http://www.elle.com/culture/books/a34613/melissa-broder-so-sad-today/|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=Elle|issue=April 2016|date=March 14, 2016}}</ref> as well as a popular Twitter feed also titled So Sad Today, on which the book is based.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lovitt|first1=Bryn|title=So Sad Today Author Melissa Broder on Twitter Anonymity and Internet Addiction|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2016/03/so-sad-today-twitter-melissa-broder|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=Vanity Fair|date=March 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBroder grew up in [[Bryn Mawr, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She attended the [[Baldwin School]] and became interested in poetry early, writing her first collection in third grade.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBroder developed an anxiety disorder at age 12.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nShe then attended [[Tufts University]] where she studied English and edited the literary magazine ''Queen's Head and Artichoke''. After graduating, she moved to San Francisco, then to New York where she worked as a publicist for [[Penguin Books]] and attended night classes at [[City College of New York]], earning an MFA in poetry.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBroder has been clean and sober since age 25.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Career==\n===Poetry===\n\nBroder has published four collections of poetry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/literature/20160315_Melissa_Broder_happy_to_bring__So_Sad_Today__back_home.html|title=Melissa Broder happy to bring 'So Sad Today' back home|last=Volpe|first=Allie|date=March 14, 2016|work=Philadelphia Inquirer|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, Broder won a Pushcart Prize for her poem \"Forgotten Sound\",<ref>{{cite book |oclc=961956305 |title=Pushcart prize XLI, 2017: best of the small presses |last=Henderson |first=Bill |last2=Pushcart Press |date=January 1, 2017 |issn=0149-7863 |language=English}}</ref> included in her collection ''Last Sext.''\n\n===Twitter===\nBroder began her So Sad Today Twitter account, initially anonymously, in 2012.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|last1=Mlotek|first1=Haley|title=The Hidden Vulnerabilities of @SoSadToday|url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-hidden-vulnerabilities-of-sosadtoday|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=The New Yorker|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref> She revealed herself as the account's author in an ''Rolling Stone'' interview in May 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vozick-Levinson|first1=Simon|title=SoSadToday Reveals Her Identity and Existential Beach Read|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/sosadtoday-reveals-herself-and-her-existential-beach-read-20150519|accessdate=May 15, 2017|work=Rolling Stone|date=May 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs of February 2018, the So Sad Today Twitter account had more than 600,000 followers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://twitter.com/sosadtoday/followers|title=@SoSadToday Twitter Account Followers Page|date=February 26, 2018|work=Twitter}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''So Sad Today''===\nIn 2016, Broder published a collection of personal essays, ''So Sad Today'', based on her Twitter account.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/books/2016/05/melissa_broder_s_book_so_sad_today_reviewed.html|title=The Ocean of Sadness|last=Coakley|first=Alexandra|date=May 4, 2016|work=Slate|access-date=May 15, 2017|issn=1091-2339}}</ref> The collection includes some essays initially published at [[Vice (magazine)|''Vice'']] under her So Sad Today pen name.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===''The Pisces''===\nIn 2018, Broder published the novel ''The Pisces'',<ref name=\":nyt\" /> which garnered praise from The New York Times, The New Yorker, Vogue, and The Washington Post.\n\n===Other projects===\nBroder is adapting ''The Pisces'' for [[Lionsgate Films]].<ref name=\":nyt\" /> Broder writes the So Sad Today column for ''[[Vice Media]]'', the [[horoscope]]s for [[Lena Dunham]]'s newsletter ''[[Lenny Letter]]'' and the Beauty and Death column for Elle. She has a television pilot in development.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nBroder is married and lives in Los Angeles.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last1=Bromwich|first1=Kathryn|title=So Sad Today's Melissa Broder: \u2018I just want to rip that chapter out\u2019|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/may/08/so-sad-today-melissa-broder-poet-twitter-book-mental-health|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=The Guardian|date=May 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n=== Poetry ===\n* ''When You Say One Thing But Mean Your Mother'' (Ampersand Books, 2010)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bombmagazine.org/article/4487/melissa-broder-when-you-say-one-thing-but-mean-your-mother|title=Melissa Broder, When You Say One Thing But Mean Your Mother|last=Moysaenko|first=Peter|date=March 19, 2010|work=BOMB Magazine|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Meat Heart'' ([[Publishing Genius]], 2012)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://therumpus.net/2012/04/i-have-a-jaw-that-seeks-chunks/|title=I Have a Jaw That Seeks Chunks|last=Zingg|first=Matthew|date=April 14, 2012|work=The Rumpus|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-9831706-6-2|title=Fiction Book Review: Meat Heart by Melissa Broder|date=March 1, 2012|work=Publishers Weekly|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bombmagazine.org/article/6722/|title=Melissa's Meat Heart|last=Moysaenko|first=Peter|date=July 27, 2012|work=BOMB Magazine|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Scarecrone'' (Publishing Genius, 2014)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://flavorwire.com/442242/melissa-broder-is-twitters-most-fascinating-poet|title=Melissa Broder Is Twitter's Most Fascinating Poet|last=Diamond|first=Jason|date=February 25, 2014|work=Flavorwire|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-9887503-7-1|title=Fiction Book Review: Scarecrone by Melissa Broder|date=February 24, 2014|work=Publishers Weekly|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Last Sext'' (Tin House 2016)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://therumpus.net/2017/04/last-sext-by-melissa-broder/|title=The Teenage Girl in All of Us: Last Sext by Melissa Broder|last=Derby|first=Edward|date=April 21, 2017|work=The Rumpus|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bkmag.com/2016/06/13/melissa-broder-last-sext/|title=What Is Melissa Broder's Last Sext?: Talking Poetry, God, and LA with the Darkly Brilliant Writer|last=Delaney|first=Kellylouise|date=June 13, 2016|work=Brooklyn Magazine|access-date=May 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Essay collection ===\n* ''So Sad Today'' (Grand Central, 2016)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nymag.com/thecut/2016/03/melissa-broder-so-sad-today-interview.html|title=Ask Polly and So Sad Today Talk About Feelings|last=Havrilesky|first=Heather|date=March 15, 2016|department=The Cut|access-date=May 15, 2017|work=New York}}</ref>\n\n=== Novel ===\n* ''The Pisces'' (Penguin Random House, May 2018)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/557707/the-pisces-by-melissa-broder/|title=The Pisces by Melissa Broder {{!}} PenguinRandomHouse.com}}</ref>\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.melissabroder.com/ Official website]\n* [https://twitter.com/sosadtoday @sosadtoday] on Twitter\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Broder, Melissa}}\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American women essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:City College of New York alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Bryn Mawr, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Poets from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               =  Melissa Broder\n| image              =  Is Technology Enriching Language - b - Melissa Broder 2017.jpg\n| image_upright =\n| image_size = <!-- DISCOURAGED per WP:IMGSIZE. Use image_upright. -->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = 2017\n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         =  <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         =  <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = \n| monuments          = \n| residence          = Los Angeles\n| nationality        = \n| citizenship        = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Tufts University]] (BA), [[City College of New York]] (MFA)\n| occupation         = Poet, essayist\n| agent              =  \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = ''So Sad Today'', ''The Pisces'', ''Last Sext''\n| style              = \n| home_town          = [[Bryn Mawr, Pennsylvania]]\n| movement           = \n| spouse             =  <!-- Use article title or common name -->\n| partner            =  <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = \n| parents            =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n| mother             =  <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| father             =  <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| awards             = [[Pushcart Prize]]\n| website            =  {{URL|melissabroder.com}}\n}}\n'''Melissa Broder''' is a poet and writer. Her work includes the novel ''The Pisces'' ([[Penguin Random House]] 2018),<ref name=\":nyt\">{{cite news|last1=Syme|first1=Rachel|title=In 'The Pisces,' a Woman and a Merman Fall in Love. Aquatic Erotica Ensues.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/26/books/the-pisces-melissa-broder.html|accessdate=May 14, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref> the poetry collection ''Last Sext'' ([[Tin House]] 2016)<ref>{{cite news|title=Fiction Book Review: Last Sext by Melissa Broder|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-941040-33-1|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=Publishers Weekly|date=April 18, 2016}}</ref> and essay collection ''So Sad Today'' ([[Grand Central Publishing|Grand Central]] 2016),<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|last1=Joiner|first1=Whitney|title=Why Is Melissa Broder So Sad Today?|url=http://www.elle.com/culture/books/a34613/melissa-broder-so-sad-today/|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=Elle|issue=April 2016|date=March 14, 2016}}</ref> as well as a popular Twitter feed also titled So Sad Today, on which the book is based.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lovitt|first1=Bryn|title=So Sad Today Author Melissa Broder on Twitter Anonymity and Internet Addiction|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2016/03/so-sad-today-twitter-melissa-broder|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=Vanity Fair|date=March 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBroder grew up in [[Bryn Mawr, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She attended the [[Baldwin School]] and became interested in poetry early, writing her first collection in third grade.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBroder developed an anxiety disorder at age 12.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nShe then attended [[Tufts University]] where she studied English and edited the literary magazine ''Queen's Head and Artichoke''. After graduating, she moved to San Francisco, then to New York where she worked as a publicist for [[Penguin Books]] and attended night classes at [[City College of New York]], earning an MFA in poetry.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBroder has been clean and sober since age 25.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Career==\n===Poetry===\n\nBroder has published four collections of poetry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/literature/20160315_Melissa_Broder_happy_to_bring__So_Sad_Today__back_home.html|title=Melissa Broder happy to bring 'So Sad Today' back home|last=Volpe|first=Allie|date=March 14, 2016|work=Philadelphia Inquirer|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, Broder won a Pushcart Prize for her poem \"Forgotten Sound\",<ref>{{cite book |oclc=961956305 |title=Pushcart prize XLI, 2017: best of the small presses |last=Henderson |first=Bill |last2=Pushcart Press |date=January 1, 2017 |issn=0149-7863 |language=English}}</ref> included in her collection ''Last Sext.''\n\n===Twitter===\nBroder began her So Sad Today Twitter account, initially anonymously, in 2012.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|last1=Mlotek|first1=Haley|title=The Hidden Vulnerabilities of @SoSadToday|url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-hidden-vulnerabilities-of-sosadtoday|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=The New Yorker|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref> She revealed herself as the account's author in an ''Rolling Stone'' interview in May 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vozick-Levinson|first1=Simon|title=SoSadToday Reveals Her Identity and Existential Beach Read|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/sosadtoday-reveals-herself-and-her-existential-beach-read-20150519|accessdate=May 15, 2017|work=Rolling Stone|date=May 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs of February 2018, the So Sad Today Twitter account had more than 600,000 followers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://twitter.com/sosadtoday/followers|title=@SoSadToday Twitter Account Followers Page|date=February 26, 2018|work=Twitter}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''So Sad Today''===\nIn 2016, Broder published a collection of personal essays, ''So Sad Today'', based on her Twitter account.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/books/2016/05/melissa_broder_s_book_so_sad_today_reviewed.html|title=The Ocean of Sadness|last=Coakley|first=Alexandra|date=May 4, 2016|work=Slate|access-date=May 15, 2017|issn=1091-2339}}</ref> The collection includes some essays initially published at [[Vice (magazine)|''Vice'']] under her So Sad Today pen name.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===''The Pisces''===\nIn 2018, Broder published the novel ''The Pisces'',<ref name=\":nyt\" /> which garnered praise from The New York Times, The New Yorker, Vogue, and The Washington Post.\n\n===Other projects===\nBroder is adapting ''The Pisces'' for [[Lionsgate Films]].<ref name=\":nyt\" /> Broder writes the So Sad Today column for ''[[Vice Media]]'', the [[horoscope]]s for [[Lena Dunham]]'s newsletter ''[[Lenny Letter]]'' and the Beauty and Death column for Elle. She has a television pilot in development.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nBroder is married and lives in Los Angeles.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last1=Bromwich|first1=Kathryn|title=So Sad Today's Melissa Broder: \u2018I just want to rip that chapter out\u2019|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/may/08/so-sad-today-melissa-broder-poet-twitter-book-mental-health|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=The Guardian|date=May 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n=== Poetry ===\n* ''When You Say One Thing But Mean Your Mother'' (Ampersand Books, 2010)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bombmagazine.org/article/4487/melissa-broder-when-you-say-one-thing-but-mean-your-mother|title=Melissa Broder, When You Say One Thing But Mean Your Mother|last=Moysaenko|first=Peter|date=March 19, 2010|work=BOMB Magazine|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Meat Heart'' ([[Publishing Genius]], 2012)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://therumpus.net/2012/04/i-have-a-jaw-that-seeks-chunks/|title=I Have a Jaw That Seeks Chunks|last=Zingg|first=Matthew|date=April 14, 2012|work=The Rumpus|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-9831706-6-2|title=Fiction Book Review: Meat Heart by Melissa Broder|date=March 1, 2012|work=Publishers Weekly|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bombmagazine.org/article/6722/|title=Melissa's Meat Heart|last=Moysaenko|first=Peter|date=July 27, 2012|work=BOMB Magazine|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Scarecrone'' (Publishing Genius, 2014)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://flavorwire.com/442242/melissa-broder-is-twitters-most-fascinating-poet|title=Melissa Broder Is Twitter's Most Fascinating Poet|last=Diamond|first=Jason|date=February 25, 2014|work=Flavorwire|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-9887503-7-1|title=Fiction Book Review: Scarecrone by Melissa Broder|date=February 24, 2014|work=Publishers Weekly|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Last Sext'' (Tin House 2016)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://therumpus.net/2017/04/last-sext-by-melissa-broder/|title=The Teenage Girl in All of Us: Last Sext by Melissa Broder|last=Derby|first=Edward|date=April 21, 2017|work=The Rumpus|access-date=May 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bkmag.com/2016/06/13/melissa-broder-last-sext/|title=What Is Melissa Broder's Last Sext?: Talking Poetry, God, and LA with the Darkly Brilliant Writer|last=Delaney|first=Kellylouise|date=June 13, 2016|work=Brooklyn Magazine|access-date=May 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Essay collection ===\n* ''So Sad Today'' (Grand Central, 2016)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nymag.com/thecut/2016/03/melissa-broder-so-sad-today-interview.html|title=Ask Polly and So Sad Today Talk About Feelings|last=Havrilesky|first=Heather|date=March 15, 2016|department=The Cut|access-date=May 15, 2017|work=New York}}</ref>\n\n=== Novel ===\n* ''The Pisces'' (Penguin Random House, May 2018)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/557707/the-pisces-by-melissa-broder/|title=The Pisces by Melissa Broder {{!}} PenguinRandomHouse.com}}</ref>\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.melissabroder.com/ Official website]\n* [https://twitter.com/sosadtoday @sosadtoday] on Twitter\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Broder, Melissa}}\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American women essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:City College of New York alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Bryn Mawr, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Poets from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alt-lit]]\n", "name_user": "BrownHairedGirl", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing fromCategory:Alt-lit.   @User:Theghostofcaptmoore: PerWP:REDNOT, please use only categories which actually exist usingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melissa_Broder"}
{"title_page": "Scott McClanahan", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Scott McClanahan\n| image        = [[File:Scott McClanahan, writer, March 2013.jpg|200px|center|alt=Scott McClanahan with thug tattoos]]\n| caption = McClanahan in March 2013\n| birth_date  = June 24, 1978\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Writer, filmmaker\n| genre       = [[Literary Fiction]]\n| movement    = \n| nationality = American\n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| website     = {{URL|http://hollerpresents.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Scott McClanahan''' (born June 24, 1978) is an [[American writer]],  economist, explorer, and martial artist.<ref>Spilker, Josh, ''Impose Magazine'', April 22, 2011, [http://www.imposemagazine.com/bytes/quick-questions-w-scott-mcclanahan-of-emstories-vem \"Quick Questions:  Scott McClanahan of Stories V!\"].  Retrieved June 1, 2011.</ref> He lives in [[Beckley, West Virginia]] and is the author of eight books. His most recent book, ''The Sarah Book'', was featured in Rolling Stone, Village Voice, and Playboy.<ref>Carroll, Tobias, ''Rolling Stone'', June 22, 2017, [https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/scott-mcclanahan-appalachian-literary-outsider-w489229 \"Scott McClanahan, Appalachian Literary Outsider, on His Harrowing Divorce Book\"].</ref><ref>McNamara, Nate, ''Village Voice'', June 27, 2017, [https://www.villagevoice.com/2017/06/27/separating-fact-from-fiction-in-scott-mcclanahans-hillbilly-elegies/ \"Separating Fact From Fiction In Scott McClanahan\u2019s Hillbilly Elegies\"]</ref><ref>Woods, Bryan, ''Playboy'', July 7, 2017, [http://www.playboy.com/articles/scott-mcclanahan-the-sarah-book-interview \"Scott McClanahan's 'The Sarah Book' Is a Painfully Funny Look at Life in a Wal-Mart Parking Lot\"].</ref> NPR called the book \"brave, triumphant and beautiful \u2014 it reads like a fever dream, and it feels like a miracle.\"<ref>Schaub, Michael, NPR, June 21, 2017, [https://www.npr.org/2017/06/21/532975930/the-sarah-book-is-an-unsparing-primal-scream-of-a-book \"Book Review: 'The Sarah Book' Is An Unsparing Primal Scream Of A Book\"].</ref> McClanahan is also a co-founder of Holler Presents, a West Virginia-based production and small press company.<ref>Hoenigman, David F., ''Word Riot'', February 16, 2010, [http://www.wordriot.org/template_3.php?ID=2053 \"An Interview With Scott McClanahan\"].  Retrieved June 1, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2010, McClanahan made [[Dzanc Books]]' list of \"20 Writers Worth Watching,\" which was a response to the ''New Yorker'''s earlier \"20 Under 40\" list.<ref>Kirch, Claire, ''Publishers Weekly'', June 25, 2010, [http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/authors/profiles/article/43644-dzanc-books-responds-to-new-yorker-s-20-under-40-.html \"Dzanc Books Responds to 'New Yorker''s '20 Under 40'\"].  Retrieved April 18, 2012.</ref> He is burly and built like a \"smallish linebacker.\"<ref>Spilker, Josh, ''Vol. 1 Brooklyn'', October 21, 2013, [http://www.vol1brooklyn.com/2013/10/21/scott-mcclanahan-has-a-cold/ \"Scott McClanahan Has a Cold\"]. Retrieved January 18, 2014.</ref>\n\n''Pittsburgh City Paper'''s Bill O'Driscoll wrote McClanahan's stories read \"like a modern Gogol gone small-town U.S.A.\"<ref>O'Driscoll, Bill, ''Pittsburgh City Paper'', June 30, 2011, [http://www.pghcitypaper.com/gyrobase/scott-mcclanahans-stories-v-and-angele-elliss-spared/Content?oid=1397609 \"Scott McClanahan's Stories V! and Angele Ellis's Spared\"].  Retrieved August 10, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2012, Lazy Fascist Press published ''The Collected Works of Scott McClanahan'', reissuing the first two ''Stories'' collections.<ref>Pierce, Cameron, LazyFascistPress.com, March 7, 2012,[http://lazyfascistpress.com/2012/03/07/the-collected-works-of-scott-mcclanahan-vol-1/ \"The Collected Works of Scott McClanahan\"].  Retrieved April 13, 2012.</ref>\n\nTwo more books, ''Crapalachia'' and ''Hill William'', were published by Two Dollar Radio and [[Tyrant Books]], respectively, in 2013.<ref>Deahl, Rachel, ''Publishers Weekly'', February 13, 2012, [http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/book-news/deals/article/50600-deals-week-of-february-13-2012.html \"Deals: Week of February 13, 2012\"].  Retrieved April 13, 2012.</ref><ref>Gumbiner, Daniel, ''The Rumpus'', May 31, 2011, [http://therumpus.net/2011/05/the-rumpus-interview-with-scott-mcclanahan/ \"The Rumpus Interview With Scott McClanahan\"].  Retrieved June 1, 2011.</ref>\n\nA two volume compilation of McClanahan's interviews entitled ''SM: The Collected Interviews Volumes 1 and 2'' is forthcoming.\n\nMcClanahan won Philadelphia's third [[Literary Death Match]] on May 23, 2012.<ref>Lopez, Teresa, ''Drexel Publishing Group'', May 25, 2012, [http://drexelpublishing.org/2012/05/25/philadelphia-literary-death-match/ \"Philadelphia Literary Death Match (WoW)\"].  Retrieved May 30, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2014, McClanahan and his Holler Presents partner, Chris Oxley, released a limited edition vinyl single by their band, Holler Boys, on Fat Possum Records.<ref>Butler, Blake, VICE, March 13, 2014, [https://www.vice.com/read/hill-william-sings-ghost-country \"Hill William Sings Ghost Country\"].  Retrieved July 14, 2014.</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, McClanahan married writer [[Juliet Escoria]].\n\n==Critical response==\nMcClanahan's work has garnered generally favorable reviews.  In his review of ''Stories V!'' for ''The Huffington Post'', Declan Tan wrote, \"it doesn't have any of the staid and academically 'meta' tropes that often go with it; you can tell McClanahan feels something when he writes and when he lives. He wants you to feel something too. And he wants you to see the possibilities of the writer-reader interaction.\"<ref>Tan, Declan, ''The Huffington Post'', December 18, 2011, [http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/declan-tan/stories-v-scott-mcclanahan_b_1156414.html \"Stories V! by Scott McClanahan (REVIEW)\"].  Retrieved February 22, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn their review of ''Crapalachia'', ''The Paris Review'' said, \"his voice is wholly unaffected, and his account manages to be both comic and unpretentiously sentimental,\"<ref>Rudick, Nicole, ''The Paris Review'', February 22, 2013, [http://www.theparisreview.org/blog/2013/02/22/what-were-loving-crapalachia-welty-animalia/ \"What We\u2019re Loving: Crapalachia, Welty, Animalia\"]. Retrieved February 22, 2013.</ref> while ''Paste'' magazine called his writing \"stark, beautiful\" and that it \"cannot be confined by genre.\"<ref>Sypolt, Natalie, ''Paste'', February 5, 2013, [http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2013/02/crapalachia-a-biography-of-a-place-by-scott-mcclan.html \"Crapalachia:  A Biography Of Place by Scott McClanahan \u2013 Truth and Memory\"].  Retrieved February 22, 2013.</ref>\n\nAlison Glock of ''The New York Times'' said of ''Crapalachia'', \"McClanahan's prose is miasmic, dizzying, repetitive.  A rushing river of words that reflects the chaos and humanity of the place from which he hails. He writes in an elliptical fever dream so contagious that slowing down is not an option.  It would be like putting a doorstop in front of a speeding train.  This is not a book you savor. It is one you inhale.\"<ref>Glock, Alison, ''The New York Times'', May 31, 2013, [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/02/books/review/crapalachia-by-scott-mcclanahan.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 \"Country Living \u2013 \u2018Crapalachia,\u2019 by Scott McClanahan]. Retrieved August 15, 2013.</ref> Steve Donoghue, writing for ''The Washington Post'', called ''Crapalachia'' \"the genuine article: intelligent, atmospheric, raucously funny and utterly wrenching.\"<ref>Donoghue, Steve, ''The Washington Post'', April 23, 2013, [https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2013-04-23/entertainment/38760090_1_odisha-joint-entrance-examination-angel-stories \"\u2018Crapalachia,\u2019 by Scott McClanahan\"].  Retrieved August 15, 2013.</ref> In the ''New York Daily News'', Michael Abolafia reviewed ''Hill William'' positively, saying that it \"invites us to look into the heart of easily forgotten, off-the-beaten-path landscapes and the strangeness that permeates them, and we are better off for his words.\"<ref>Abolafia, Michael, ''New York Daily News'', March 26, 2013, [http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/pageviews/scott-mcclanahan-hill-william-gritty-soulful-tribute-lost-appalachian-childhood-blog-entry-1.1735272 ''Review of Hill William by Scott McClanahan'']. Retrieved September 30, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Stories'' (2008, Six Gallery Press)\n*''Stories II'' (2009, Six Gallery Press)\n*''Stories V!'' (2011, Holler Presents)\n*''The Collected Works of Scott McClanahan Vol. 1'' (2012, Lazy Fascist Press)\n*''Crapalachia'' (2013, Two Dollar Radio)\n*''Hill William'' (2013, [[Tyrant Books]])\n*''The Incantations of Daniel Johnston'' (2016, Two Dollar Radio)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Incantations-Daniel-Johnston-Scott-McClanahan/dp/1937512452/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1461539436&sr=8-2&keywords=scott%20mcclanahan|title=The Incantations of Daniel Johnston|first1=Scott|last1=McClanahan|first2=Ricardo|last2=Cavolo|date=July 19, 2016|publisher=Two Dollar Radio|accessdate=September 10, 2016|via=Amazon}}</ref>\n*''The Sarah Book'' (2017, [[Tyrant Books]])\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Artist\n! style=\"width:22em;\"| Single\n! Label\n|-\n| 2014\n| Holler Boys\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Holy Holy Prayer\"/\"The Nah Nah Song\"\n| align=\"left\"| Fat Possum Records\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using  tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://hollerpresents.com/scottstories.html|title=Holler Presents The Official Scott McClanahan Site|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://hollerpresents.com|title=Holler Presents Official Site|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://therumpus.net/2011/05/the-rumpus-interview-with-scott-mcclanahan/|title=The Rumpus Interview with Scott McClanahan|date=May 31, 2011|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.thelmagazine.com/TheMeasure/archives/2011/10/11/an-unforgettable-reading-at-franklin-park-last-night|title=An Unforgettable Reading at Franklin Park Last Night - The L Magazine|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*[http://electricliterature.com/blog/2011/10/08/preaching-the-gospel-of-scott-mcclanahan/ ''Electric Literature'''s \"Preaching The Gospel of Scott McClanahan\"]\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/declan-tan/stories-v-scott-mcclanahan_b_1156414.html|title=Stories V! by Scott McClanahan (REVIEW) - Huffington Post|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/friday-tyrant-scott-mcclanahan-hick-christ|title=Friday Tyrant - Scott McClanahan, Hick Christ - VICE - United States|date=April 1, 2011|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://bombsite.com/issues/1000/articles/6727|title=BOMB Magazine \u2014 Scott McClanahan by Royal Young|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121127051049/http://www.oxfordamerican.org/articles/2012/oct/09/author-interview-scott-mcclanahan/ ''Oxford American'' interview]\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.theparisreview.org/blog/2013/02/22/what-were-loving-crapalachia-welty-animalia/|title=What We\u2019re Loving: Crapalachia, Welty, Animalia|first=The Paris|last=Review|date=February 22, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://harvardreview.fas.harvard.edu/?q=features/book-review/crapalachia|title=Crapalachia - Harvard Review Online|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2013/02/crapalachia-a-biography-of-a-place-by-scott-mcclan.html|title=Crapalachia: A Biography of a Place by Scott McClanahan|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-937512-03-3|title=Fiction Book Review: Crapalachia: A Biography of a Place by Scott McClanahan|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/authors/interviews/article/56364-level-the-mountain-pw-talks-with-scott-mcclanahan.html|title=Level the Mountain: PW Talks With Scott McClanahan|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/authors/profiles/article/58028-scott-mcclanahan-on-the-rise.html|title=Scott McClanahan On the Rise|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/culture/scott-mcclanahan-crapalachia|title=Scott McClanahan Tells It from the Mountains|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://hollerpresents.com/nylon.html|title=Holler Presents The Official Scott McClanahan Site|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.myajc.com/news/entertainment/crapalachia-a-biography-of-a-place-captures-hardsc/nW6WZ/|title=A hardscrabble life in rural W.V.|first=By Gina Webb - For the|last=AJC|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/crapalachia-by-scott-mcclanahan/2013/04/23/7f77e670-a5eb-11e2-8302-3c7e0ea97057_story.html|title=\u2018Crapalachia,\u2019 by Scott McClanahan|first=Steve|last=Donoghue|date=April 23, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016|via=washingtonpost.com}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/02/books/review/crapalachia-by-scott-mcclanahan.html|title=Country Living|date=June 2, 2013|work=The New York Times|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/scott-mcclanahans-animal-magnetism|title=Scott McClanahan\u2019s Animal Magnetism - VICE - United States|date=March 20, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/hill-william-sings-ghost-country|title=Hill William Sings Ghost Country - VICE - United States|date=March 13, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://hollerpresents.com/1.html|title=Holler Presents 1|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://hollerpresents.com/2.html|title=Holler Presents 2|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://hollerpresents.com/3.html|title=Holler Presents 3|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://hollerpresents.com/4.html|title=Holler Presents 4|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*[http://logger.believermag.com/post/65527007456/wouldnt-you-want-to-party-with-a-baby Scott McClanahan in Conversation with Stacy Kranitz for ''The Believer'']\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/Crapa|title=[Crapalachia]|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/18116/1/the-best-indie-books-of-2013|title=The best indie books of 2013|first=|last=Dazed|date=December 11, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/17603/1/the-da-zed-guide-to-alt-lit|title=The dA-Zed guide to Alt Lit|first=|last=Dazed|date=November 11, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/19621/1/literary-rebels-you-need-to-know|title=Literary rebels you need to know|first=|last=Dazed|date=April 22, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://flavorwire.com/429323/the-10-best-nonfiction-books-of-2013/view-all/|title=The 10 Best Nonfiction Books of 2013|date=December 12, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://flavorwire.com/422919/10-must-read-books-for-november/|title=10 Must-Read Books for November|date=October 31, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/review/robert-rea-on-hill-william-scott-mcclanahan-and-the-digital-south|title=Down and Out in the Digital South: Scott McClanahan's \"Hill William\" - Los Angeles Review of Books|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.brooklynrail.org/2013/11/books/two-by-scott-McClanahan|title=Two by Scott McClanahan|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://brooklynbased.com/blog/2014/02/06/books-of-the-week/|title=Ride Out Winter With These Two Book Picks - Brooklyn Based|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McClanahan, Scott}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male short story writers]]\n[[Category:People from Beckley, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Scott McClanahan\n| image        = [[File:Scott McClanahan, writer, March 2013.jpg|200px|center|alt=Scott McClanahan with thug tattoos]]\n| caption = McClanahan in March 2013\n| birth_date  = June 24, 1978\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Writer, filmmaker\n| genre       = [[Literary Fiction]]\n| movement    = \n| nationality = American\n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| website     = {{URL|http://hollerpresents.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Scott McClanahan''' (born June 24, 1978) is an [[American writer]],  economist, explorer, and martial artist.<ref>Spilker, Josh, ''Impose Magazine'', April 22, 2011, [http://www.imposemagazine.com/bytes/quick-questions-w-scott-mcclanahan-of-emstories-vem \"Quick Questions:  Scott McClanahan of Stories V!\"].  Retrieved June 1, 2011.</ref> He lives in [[Beckley, West Virginia]] and is the author of eight books. His most recent book, ''The Sarah Book'', was featured in Rolling Stone, Village Voice, and Playboy.<ref>Carroll, Tobias, ''Rolling Stone'', June 22, 2017, [https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/scott-mcclanahan-appalachian-literary-outsider-w489229 \"Scott McClanahan, Appalachian Literary Outsider, on His Harrowing Divorce Book\"].</ref><ref>McNamara, Nate, ''Village Voice'', June 27, 2017, [https://www.villagevoice.com/2017/06/27/separating-fact-from-fiction-in-scott-mcclanahans-hillbilly-elegies/ \"Separating Fact From Fiction In Scott McClanahan\u2019s Hillbilly Elegies\"]</ref><ref>Woods, Bryan, ''Playboy'', July 7, 2017, [http://www.playboy.com/articles/scott-mcclanahan-the-sarah-book-interview \"Scott McClanahan's 'The Sarah Book' Is a Painfully Funny Look at Life in a Wal-Mart Parking Lot\"].</ref> NPR called the book \"brave, triumphant and beautiful \u2014 it reads like a fever dream, and it feels like a miracle.\"<ref>Schaub, Michael, NPR, June 21, 2017, [https://www.npr.org/2017/06/21/532975930/the-sarah-book-is-an-unsparing-primal-scream-of-a-book \"Book Review: 'The Sarah Book' Is An Unsparing Primal Scream Of A Book\"].</ref> McClanahan is also a co-founder of Holler Presents, a West Virginia-based production and small press company.<ref>Hoenigman, David F., ''Word Riot'', February 16, 2010, [http://www.wordriot.org/template_3.php?ID=2053 \"An Interview With Scott McClanahan\"].  Retrieved June 1, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2010, McClanahan made [[Dzanc Books]]' list of \"20 Writers Worth Watching,\" which was a response to the ''New Yorker'''s earlier \"20 Under 40\" list.<ref>Kirch, Claire, ''Publishers Weekly'', June 25, 2010, [http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/authors/profiles/article/43644-dzanc-books-responds-to-new-yorker-s-20-under-40-.html \"Dzanc Books Responds to 'New Yorker''s '20 Under 40'\"].  Retrieved April 18, 2012.</ref> He is burly and built like a \"smallish linebacker.\"<ref>Spilker, Josh, ''Vol. 1 Brooklyn'', October 21, 2013, [http://www.vol1brooklyn.com/2013/10/21/scott-mcclanahan-has-a-cold/ \"Scott McClanahan Has a Cold\"]. Retrieved January 18, 2014.</ref>\n\n''Pittsburgh City Paper'''s Bill O'Driscoll wrote McClanahan's stories read \"like a modern Gogol gone small-town U.S.A.\"<ref>O'Driscoll, Bill, ''Pittsburgh City Paper'', June 30, 2011, [http://www.pghcitypaper.com/gyrobase/scott-mcclanahans-stories-v-and-angele-elliss-spared/Content?oid=1397609 \"Scott McClanahan's Stories V! and Angele Ellis's Spared\"].  Retrieved August 10, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2012, Lazy Fascist Press published ''The Collected Works of Scott McClanahan'', reissuing the first two ''Stories'' collections.<ref>Pierce, Cameron, LazyFascistPress.com, March 7, 2012,[http://lazyfascistpress.com/2012/03/07/the-collected-works-of-scott-mcclanahan-vol-1/ \"The Collected Works of Scott McClanahan\"].  Retrieved April 13, 2012.</ref>\n\nTwo more books, ''Crapalachia'' and ''Hill William'', were published by Two Dollar Radio and [[Tyrant Books]], respectively, in 2013.<ref>Deahl, Rachel, ''Publishers Weekly'', February 13, 2012, [http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/book-news/deals/article/50600-deals-week-of-february-13-2012.html \"Deals: Week of February 13, 2012\"].  Retrieved April 13, 2012.</ref><ref>Gumbiner, Daniel, ''The Rumpus'', May 31, 2011, [http://therumpus.net/2011/05/the-rumpus-interview-with-scott-mcclanahan/ \"The Rumpus Interview With Scott McClanahan\"].  Retrieved June 1, 2011.</ref>\n\nA two volume compilation of McClanahan's interviews entitled ''SM: The Collected Interviews Volumes 1 and 2'' is forthcoming.\n\nMcClanahan won Philadelphia's third [[Literary Death Match]] on May 23, 2012.<ref>Lopez, Teresa, ''Drexel Publishing Group'', May 25, 2012, [http://drexelpublishing.org/2012/05/25/philadelphia-literary-death-match/ \"Philadelphia Literary Death Match (WoW)\"].  Retrieved May 30, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2014, McClanahan and his Holler Presents partner, Chris Oxley, released a limited edition vinyl single by their band, Holler Boys, on Fat Possum Records.<ref>Butler, Blake, VICE, March 13, 2014, [https://www.vice.com/read/hill-william-sings-ghost-country \"Hill William Sings Ghost Country\"].  Retrieved July 14, 2014.</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, McClanahan married writer [[Juliet Escoria]].\n\n==Critical response==\nMcClanahan's work has garnered generally favorable reviews.  In his review of ''Stories V!'' for ''The Huffington Post'', Declan Tan wrote, \"it doesn't have any of the staid and academically 'meta' tropes that often go with it; you can tell McClanahan feels something when he writes and when he lives. He wants you to feel something too. And he wants you to see the possibilities of the writer-reader interaction.\"<ref>Tan, Declan, ''The Huffington Post'', December 18, 2011, [http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/declan-tan/stories-v-scott-mcclanahan_b_1156414.html \"Stories V! by Scott McClanahan (REVIEW)\"].  Retrieved February 22, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn their review of ''Crapalachia'', ''The Paris Review'' said, \"his voice is wholly unaffected, and his account manages to be both comic and unpretentiously sentimental,\"<ref>Rudick, Nicole, ''The Paris Review'', February 22, 2013, [http://www.theparisreview.org/blog/2013/02/22/what-were-loving-crapalachia-welty-animalia/ \"What We\u2019re Loving: Crapalachia, Welty, Animalia\"]. Retrieved February 22, 2013.</ref> while ''Paste'' magazine called his writing \"stark, beautiful\" and that it \"cannot be confined by genre.\"<ref>Sypolt, Natalie, ''Paste'', February 5, 2013, [http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2013/02/crapalachia-a-biography-of-a-place-by-scott-mcclan.html \"Crapalachia:  A Biography Of Place by Scott McClanahan \u2013 Truth and Memory\"].  Retrieved February 22, 2013.</ref>\n\nAlison Glock of ''The New York Times'' said of ''Crapalachia'', \"McClanahan's prose is miasmic, dizzying, repetitive.  A rushing river of words that reflects the chaos and humanity of the place from which he hails. He writes in an elliptical fever dream so contagious that slowing down is not an option.  It would be like putting a doorstop in front of a speeding train.  This is not a book you savor. It is one you inhale.\"<ref>Glock, Alison, ''The New York Times'', May 31, 2013, [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/02/books/review/crapalachia-by-scott-mcclanahan.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 \"Country Living \u2013 \u2018Crapalachia,\u2019 by Scott McClanahan]. Retrieved August 15, 2013.</ref> Steve Donoghue, writing for ''The Washington Post'', called ''Crapalachia'' \"the genuine article: intelligent, atmospheric, raucously funny and utterly wrenching.\"<ref>Donoghue, Steve, ''The Washington Post'', April 23, 2013, [https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2013-04-23/entertainment/38760090_1_odisha-joint-entrance-examination-angel-stories \"\u2018Crapalachia,\u2019 by Scott McClanahan\"].  Retrieved August 15, 2013.</ref> In the ''New York Daily News'', Michael Abolafia reviewed ''Hill William'' positively, saying that it \"invites us to look into the heart of easily forgotten, off-the-beaten-path landscapes and the strangeness that permeates them, and we are better off for his words.\"<ref>Abolafia, Michael, ''New York Daily News'', March 26, 2013, [http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/pageviews/scott-mcclanahan-hill-william-gritty-soulful-tribute-lost-appalachian-childhood-blog-entry-1.1735272 ''Review of Hill William by Scott McClanahan'']. Retrieved September 30, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Stories'' (2008, Six Gallery Press)\n*''Stories II'' (2009, Six Gallery Press)\n*''Stories V!'' (2011, Holler Presents)\n*''The Collected Works of Scott McClanahan Vol. 1'' (2012, Lazy Fascist Press)\n*''Crapalachia'' (2013, Two Dollar Radio)\n*''Hill William'' (2013, [[Tyrant Books]])\n*''The Incantations of Daniel Johnston'' (2016, Two Dollar Radio)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Incantations-Daniel-Johnston-Scott-McClanahan/dp/1937512452/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1461539436&sr=8-2&keywords=scott%20mcclanahan|title=The Incantations of Daniel Johnston|first1=Scott|last1=McClanahan|first2=Ricardo|last2=Cavolo|date=July 19, 2016|publisher=Two Dollar Radio|accessdate=September 10, 2016|via=Amazon}}</ref>\n*''The Sarah Book'' (2017, [[Tyrant Books]])\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Artist\n! style=\"width:22em;\"| Single\n! Label\n|-\n| 2014\n| Holler Boys\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Holy Holy Prayer\"/\"The Nah Nah Song\"\n| align=\"left\"| Fat Possum Records\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using  tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://hollerpresents.com/scottstories.html|title=Holler Presents The Official Scott McClanahan Site|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://hollerpresents.com|title=Holler Presents Official Site|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://therumpus.net/2011/05/the-rumpus-interview-with-scott-mcclanahan/|title=The Rumpus Interview with Scott McClanahan|date=May 31, 2011|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.thelmagazine.com/TheMeasure/archives/2011/10/11/an-unforgettable-reading-at-franklin-park-last-night|title=An Unforgettable Reading at Franklin Park Last Night - The L Magazine|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2016}}\n*[http://electricliterature.com/blog/2011/10/08/preaching-the-gospel-of-scott-mcclanahan/ ''Electric Literature'''s \"Preaching The Gospel of Scott McClanahan\"]\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/declan-tan/stories-v-scott-mcclanahan_b_1156414.html|title=Stories V! by Scott McClanahan (REVIEW) - Huffington Post|publisher=|accessdate=September 10,