{"title_page": "Ben Brooks (novelist)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name = Ben Brooks\n|birth_date = 1992\n|birth_place = [[Gloucestershire]], England \n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|occupation = Writer\n|nationality = British\n|notableworks = ''[[Grow Up (book)]]'' (2011)}}\n\n'''Ben Brooks''' (born 1992 in [[Gloucestershire]]) is the author of seven novels: ''[[Grow Up (book)|Grow Up]]'',<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/grow-up/oclc/721920396&referer=brief_results WorldCat]</ref>  ''Fences'',<ref name=\"Review2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.fuguestatepress.com/fences.html | title=FENCES by Ben Brooks | publisher=Fugue State Press | date=15 January 2010 | accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref> ''An Island of Fifty'', ''The Kasahara School of Nihilism,'' ''Upward Coast and Sadie'', ''Lolito,'' and most recently ''Hurra.''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141105142912/http://www.sweetparanoia.com/2014/09/lolito-de-ben-brooks.html Rese\u00f1a de Lolito de Ben Brooks] en Sweet Paranoia. Publicada en Septiembre 2014.\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brooks, Ben}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:English male writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gloucestershire]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name = Ben Brooks\n|birth_date = 1992\n|birth_place = [[Gloucestershire]], England \n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|occupation = Writer\n|nationality = British\n|notableworks = ''[[Grow Up (book)]]'' (2011)}}\n\n'''Ben Brooks''' (born 1992 in [[Gloucestershire]]) is the author of seven novels: ''[[Grow Up (book)|Grow Up]]'',<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/grow-up/oclc/721920396&referer=brief_results WorldCat]</ref>  ''Fences'',<ref name=\"Review2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.fuguestatepress.com/fences.html | title=FENCES by Ben Brooks | publisher=Fugue State Press | date=15 January 2010 | accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref> ''An Island of Fifty'', ''The Kasahara School of Nihilism,'' ''Upward Coast and Sadie'', ''Lolito,'' and most recently ''Hurra.''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141105142912/http://www.sweetparanoia.com/2014/09/lolito-de-ben-brooks.html Rese\u00f1a de Lolito de Ben Brooks] en Sweet Paranoia. Publicada en Septiembre 2014.\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brooks, Ben}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:English male writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gloucestershire]]\n[[Category:Alt-lit]]\n", "name_user": "BrownHairedGirl", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing fromCategory:Alt-lit.   @User:Theghostofcaptmoore: PerWP:REDNOT, please use only categories which actually exist usingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Brooks_(novelist)"}
{"title_page": "Spencer Madsen", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Spencer Madsen\n| image         = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software  -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people - supply only the year unless the exact date is already widely published, as per WP:DOB. For people that have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = \n| residence     = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], US\n| nationality   = American\n| occupation    = Poet, founding editor of [[Sorry House]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Spencer Madsen''' is a contemporary [[American poet]] and [[small press]] publisher. He is a Brooklyn-based contemporary writer as well as the founding editor of [[Sorry House]], an independent publishing press in [[New York City]]. Madsen is part of a genre of independent poetry that is unique in its association with the [[New Sincerity]]  movement as well as its use of social media platforms  as its main source of publicity. He is described by ''[[The Fader]]'' magazine as \"a writer who will, with equal enthusiasm, tweet a selfie of his butt and write the sincerest, saddest line of poetry you've ever read.\"<ref>{{cite web |title = Interview: Spencer Madsen Writes Real-Life Poetry for Real-Life Attention Spans |first = Alex |last = Frank |url = http://www.thefader.com/2014/03/07/interview-spencer-madsen-writes-real-life-poetry-for-real-life-attention-spans/ |website = [[The Fader]] |date = March 7, 2014 |access-date = December 10, 2015 |archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6deyZuToc |archive-date = December 10, 2015 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==Poetry==\nThe notice of Madsen's poetry began with him posting a photo someone had taken of his 2010 self-published book ''A Million Bears'' on [[Tumblr]], which reached over 10,000 notes in the first 24-hour period. After reaching 300,000 notes ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' featured the excerpted poem online, dubbing it the \"Sad Cat Poem\".<ref>{{cite web|last=McGlynn|first=Katla|title=Sad Cat Poem Will Make You Laugh And Cry Simultaneously|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/31/sad-cat-poem-_n_2590608.html|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> In an interview with [[Adam Humphreys]] at ''Thought Catalog'', Madsen said that ''A Million Bears'' was out of print at the time of this spike in Tumblr publicity,<ref>{{cite web| last=Adam| first=Humphreys| url=http://thoughtcatalog.com/adam-humphreys/2013/09/my-poem-went-really-viral-an-interview-with-spencer-madsen/| title=My Poem Went Really Viral: An Interview With Spencer Madsen| publisher=Thought Catalog| accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> but he later issued a second edition with a new cover.<ref>{{cite web| last=Madsen| first=Spencer| title=A Million Bears Second Edition| url=http://sorryhouse.tumblr.com/post/67575262930/the-second-edition-of-a-million-bears-by-spencer| publisher=Sorry House}}</ref>\n\nA second book of poetry from Spencer Madsen entitled ''You Can Make Anything Sad'' was published by [[Publishing Genius]] on April 29, 2014. It received advanced praise from [[Dennis Cooper]].<ref>{{cite web |title = You Can Make Anything Sad by Spencer Madsen |url = http://www.publishinggenius.com/product/you-can-make-anything-sad-by-spencer-madsen/ |publisher = [[Publishing Genius]] |access-date = December 10, 2015 |archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6dez9G0rn\n|archive-date = December 10, 2015 |url-status = live }}</ref> In a review at ''[[Dazed]]'', Lauren Oyler said \"There's a disconnect between the narcissism Madsen and his alt-lit contemporaries have been accused of and the truly original insights you find yourself reading.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Oyler|first=Lauren|title=Can Spencer Madsen make anything sad?|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/19585/1/can-spencer-madsen-make-anything-sad|work=[[Dazed]]|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref> At ''[[Vice (magazine)|\nVice]]'', Madsen interviewed New York Tyrant publisher Giancarlo DiTrapano about his experience reading Madsen's book.<ref>{{cite web|last=DiTrapano|first=Giancarlo|title=Who Cares What You Think About the Book You Wrote|url=https://www.vice.com/read/who-cares-what-you-think-about-the-book-you-wrote|publisher=Vice Magazine|accessdate=29 May 2014}}</ref> ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper Magazine]]'' named ''You Can Make Anything Sad'' one of five \"Indie Poetry Books That Even Non-Lit People Will Love.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bess|first1=Gabby|title=5 Indie Poetry Books That Even Non-Lit People Will Love|url=http://www.papermag.com/2014/04/5_indie_poetry_books_for_non_lit_people.php|website=Papermag.com|publisher=Paper Magazine|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Publishing==\nIn early 2013, Madsen founded [[Sorry House]], an independent, [[small press]] [[publishing company]].<ref>{{cite web |title = I Made the Mistake of Starting a Small Press and So Can You |first = Spencer |last = Madsen |url = http://the-toast.net/2014/03/12/guide-to-starting-a-small-press/ |website = The Toast |date = March 12, 2014 |access-date = December 10, 2015 |archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6df00VfGR |archive-date = December 10, 2015 |url-status = live }}</ref> Sorry House's debut publication was ''I will never be beautiful enough to make us beautiful together'' by [[Mira Gonzalez]], released on January 31, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/books/sorry-house-book-release-housing-works-bookstore-cafe-january-31-2013|title=Sorry House Book Release|date=22 January 2013|accessdate=27 March 2014|newspaper=Time Out New York}}</ref> In February 2013, the company published ''Joke Book'' by [[Victor Vazquez (musician)|Victor Vazquez]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Cooke|first=Sam|title=But To Answer Ur Question, No: An Interview With Kool A.D.|url=http://thoughtcatalog.com/sam-cooke/2013/04/but-to-answer-ur-question-no-an-interview-with-kool-a-d/|publisher=Thought Catalog|accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref> Sorry House \"transformed into a legitimate business\" in early 2014 by becoming a [[limited liability company]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sorryhouse.com/sorry-house-transforms-into-a-legitimate-business|title=Sorry house transforms into a legitimate business|publisher=Sorry House|date=March 19, 2014|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Monkeybicycle]], Madsen cited [[Dalkey Archive Press|Dalkey Archive]], [[Melville House Publishing]], [[Grove Press]], [[Muumuu House]], and others as publishing influences.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cotrone|first=David|title=Small Press Interview: Sorry House|url=http://monkeybicycle.net/blog/small-press-interview-sorry-house/|publisher=Monkey Bicycle|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> On March 12, 2014, Madsen published an article called \"I Made the Mistake of Starting a Small Press and So Can You\" that guides others to create their own small press.<ref>{{cite web|last=Malone|first=Tess|url=http://www.themillions.com/2014/03/better-looking-than-a-breakfast-burrito.html|title=Better Looking than a Breakfast Burrito|publisher=The Millions|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSpencer Madsen (along with his brother Tyler Madsen) were conceived through [[in vitro fertilization]] (IVF).<ref>{{cite news |title = Birds and bees for \u2018test-tube\u2019 kids |first = Jacqueline |last = Stenson |url = http://www.nbcnews.com/id/3076785/ns/health-special_reports/t/birds-bees-test-tube-kids/ |work = [[NBC News]] |publisher = [[NBC]] |date = July 23, 2003 |access-date = December 10, 2015 |archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6deyq8t3W |archive-date = December 10, 2015 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Madsen, Spencer}}\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Spencer Madsen\n| image         = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software  -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people - supply only the year unless the exact date is already widely published, as per WP:DOB. For people that have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = \n| residence     = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], US\n| nationality   = American\n| occupation    = Poet, founding editor of [[Sorry House]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Spencer Madsen''' is a contemporary [[American poet]] and [[small press]] publisher. He is a Brooklyn-based contemporary writer as well as the founding editor of [[Sorry House]], an independent publishing press in [[New York City]]. Madsen is part of a genre of independent poetry that is unique in its association with the [[New Sincerity]]  movement as well as its use of social media platforms  as its main source of publicity. He is described by ''[[The Fader]]'' magazine as \"a writer who will, with equal enthusiasm, tweet a selfie of his butt and write the sincerest, saddest line of poetry you've ever read.\"<ref>{{cite web |title = Interview: Spencer Madsen Writes Real-Life Poetry for Real-Life Attention Spans |first = Alex |last = Frank |url = http://www.thefader.com/2014/03/07/interview-spencer-madsen-writes-real-life-poetry-for-real-life-attention-spans/ |website = [[The Fader]] |date = March 7, 2014 |access-date = December 10, 2015 |archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6deyZuToc |archive-date = December 10, 2015 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==Poetry==\nThe notice of Madsen's poetry began with him posting a photo someone had taken of his 2010 self-published book ''A Million Bears'' on [[Tumblr]], which reached over 10,000 notes in the first 24-hour period. After reaching 300,000 notes ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' featured the excerpted poem online, dubbing it the \"Sad Cat Poem\".<ref>{{cite web|last=McGlynn|first=Katla|title=Sad Cat Poem Will Make You Laugh And Cry Simultaneously|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/31/sad-cat-poem-_n_2590608.html|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> In an interview with [[Adam Humphreys]] at ''Thought Catalog'', Madsen said that ''A Million Bears'' was out of print at the time of this spike in Tumblr publicity,<ref>{{cite web| last=Adam| first=Humphreys| url=http://thoughtcatalog.com/adam-humphreys/2013/09/my-poem-went-really-viral-an-interview-with-spencer-madsen/| title=My Poem Went Really Viral: An Interview With Spencer Madsen| publisher=Thought Catalog| accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> but he later issued a second edition with a new cover.<ref>{{cite web| last=Madsen| first=Spencer| title=A Million Bears Second Edition| url=http://sorryhouse.tumblr.com/post/67575262930/the-second-edition-of-a-million-bears-by-spencer| publisher=Sorry House}}</ref>\n\nA second book of poetry from Spencer Madsen entitled ''You Can Make Anything Sad'' was published by [[Publishing Genius]] on April 29, 2014. It received advanced praise from [[Dennis Cooper]].<ref>{{cite web |title = You Can Make Anything Sad by Spencer Madsen |url = http://www.publishinggenius.com/product/you-can-make-anything-sad-by-spencer-madsen/ |publisher = [[Publishing Genius]] |access-date = December 10, 2015 |archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6dez9G0rn\n|archive-date = December 10, 2015 |url-status = live }}</ref> In a review at ''[[Dazed]]'', Lauren Oyler said \"There's a disconnect between the narcissism Madsen and his alt-lit contemporaries have been accused of and the truly original insights you find yourself reading.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Oyler|first=Lauren|title=Can Spencer Madsen make anything sad?|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/19585/1/can-spencer-madsen-make-anything-sad|work=[[Dazed]]|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref> At ''[[Vice (magazine)|\nVice]]'', Madsen interviewed New York Tyrant publisher Giancarlo DiTrapano about his experience reading Madsen's book.<ref>{{cite web|last=DiTrapano|first=Giancarlo|title=Who Cares What You Think About the Book You Wrote|url=https://www.vice.com/read/who-cares-what-you-think-about-the-book-you-wrote|publisher=Vice Magazine|accessdate=29 May 2014}}</ref> ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper Magazine]]'' named ''You Can Make Anything Sad'' one of five \"Indie Poetry Books That Even Non-Lit People Will Love.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bess|first1=Gabby|title=5 Indie Poetry Books That Even Non-Lit People Will Love|url=http://www.papermag.com/2014/04/5_indie_poetry_books_for_non_lit_people.php|website=Papermag.com|publisher=Paper Magazine|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Publishing==\nIn early 2013, Madsen founded [[Sorry House]], an independent, [[small press]] [[publishing company]].<ref>{{cite web |title = I Made the Mistake of Starting a Small Press and So Can You |first = Spencer |last = Madsen |url = http://the-toast.net/2014/03/12/guide-to-starting-a-small-press/ |website = The Toast |date = March 12, 2014 |access-date = December 10, 2015 |archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6df00VfGR |archive-date = December 10, 2015 |url-status = live }}</ref> Sorry House's debut publication was ''I will never be beautiful enough to make us beautiful together'' by [[Mira Gonzalez]], released on January 31, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/books/sorry-house-book-release-housing-works-bookstore-cafe-january-31-2013|title=Sorry House Book Release|date=22 January 2013|accessdate=27 March 2014|newspaper=Time Out New York}}</ref> In February 2013, the company published ''Joke Book'' by [[Victor Vazquez (musician)|Victor Vazquez]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Cooke|first=Sam|title=But To Answer Ur Question, No: An Interview With Kool A.D.|url=http://thoughtcatalog.com/sam-cooke/2013/04/but-to-answer-ur-question-no-an-interview-with-kool-a-d/|publisher=Thought Catalog|accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref> Sorry House \"transformed into a legitimate business\" in early 2014 by becoming a [[limited liability company]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sorryhouse.com/sorry-house-transforms-into-a-legitimate-business|title=Sorry house transforms into a legitimate business|publisher=Sorry House|date=March 19, 2014|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Monkeybicycle]], Madsen cited [[Dalkey Archive Press|Dalkey Archive]], [[Melville House Publishing]], [[Grove Press]], [[Muumuu House]], and others as publishing influences.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cotrone|first=David|title=Small Press Interview: Sorry House|url=http://monkeybicycle.net/blog/small-press-interview-sorry-house/|publisher=Monkey Bicycle|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> On March 12, 2014, Madsen published an article called \"I Made the Mistake of Starting a Small Press and So Can You\" that guides others to create their own small press.<ref>{{cite web|last=Malone|first=Tess|url=http://www.themillions.com/2014/03/better-looking-than-a-breakfast-burrito.html|title=Better Looking than a Breakfast Burrito|publisher=The Millions|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSpencer Madsen (along with his brother Tyler Madsen) were conceived through [[in vitro fertilization]] (IVF).<ref>{{cite news |title = Birds and bees for \u2018test-tube\u2019 kids |first = Jacqueline |last = Stenson |url = http://www.nbcnews.com/id/3076785/ns/health-special_reports/t/birds-bees-test-tube-kids/ |work = [[NBC News]] |publisher = [[NBC]] |date = July 23, 2003 |access-date = December 10, 2015 |archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6deyq8t3W |archive-date = December 10, 2015 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Madsen, Spencer}}\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Alt-lit]]\n", "name_user": "BrownHairedGirl", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing fromCategory:Alt-lit.   @User:Theghostofcaptmoore: PerWP:REDNOT, please use only categories which actually exist usingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spencer_Madsen"}
{"title_page": "Zachary German", "text_new": "{{Notability|Biographies|date=May 2010}}\n'''Zachary German''' (born December 17, 1988) is an [[American novelist]] and [[poet]]. His first novel, ''Eat When You Feel Sad,'' was published by [[Melville House Publishing|Melville House]] in 2010.<ref name=\"mhpbooks1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mhpbooks.com/book.php?id=312 |title=Eat When You Feel Sad |publisher=Melville House Publishing : Zachary German |date= |accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref>\n\nGerman's poems and prose have been published in [[Dennis Cooper]]'s ''Userland'' anthology,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/1933354151 |title=Userlands: New Fiction Writers from the Blogging Underground (Little House on the Bowery) : Dennis Cooper (Editor) |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref> [[3:AM Magazine]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.3ammagazine.com/3am/a-poem-about-new-york-citys-organic-vegan-restaurants/ |title=a poem about new york city\u2019s organic vegan restaurants : Zachary Graham |publisher=3:AM Magazine |date=2008-04-01 |accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref> Bear Parade,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bearparade.com/eatwhenyoufeelsad/ |title=Eat When You Feel Sad by Zachary German |publisher=Bearparade |date= |accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref> and Small Distribution Press.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spdbooks.org/Pages/Item/442/zachary-german-the-nike-swoosh-is-beautiful.aspx |title=Zachary German : The Nike Swoosh Is Beautiful |publisher=Small Press Distribution |date= |accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref>\n\n==''Eat When You Feel Sad''==\n\n''Eat When You Feel Sad'' was published by [[Melville House Publishing|Melville House]] in February 2010.<ref name=\"mhpbooks1\"/> It is about a character named Robert in an unnamed city.\n\nOnline and print response to ''Eat When You Feel Sad'' was mixed. It has been reviewed in [[Bookslut]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookslut.com/fiction/2010_04_015921.php|title=EAT WHEN YOU FEEL SAD BY ZACHARY GERMAN|publisher=Bookslut|accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref> [[The Rumpus]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://therumpus.net/2010/03/twenty-and-bored-and-alive/|title=TWENTY AND BORED AND ALIVE|publisher=The Rumpus|accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref> [[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out Chicago]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timeoutchicago.com/arts-culture/books/74852/eat-when-you-feel-sad|title=Eat When You Feel Sad|publisher=Time Out Chicago|accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref> [[Publishers Weekly]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-933633-85-5|title=Eat When You Feel Sad|publisher=Publishers Weekly|accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref> [[Philadelphia City Paper]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.citypaper.net/articles/2010/02/04/mo-regrets|title=Mo' Regrets|publisher=Philadelphia City Paper|accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref> and [[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zacharygerman.com/2005/01/news.html |title=every time a police officer gets shot i throw a party |publisher=Zachary German |date=2005-01-23 |accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref>\n\n[[Dennis Cooper]] has said of the book: \u201cZachary German\u2019s nimble, catwalking, archeological, surface dwelling, emotionally unpaved prose is a thing of total wonder and my favorite drug, language-based or otherwise. ''Eat When You Feel Sad'' is so bright and pleasurable and full of excellence, it\u2019s positively serene.\u201d<ref name=\"mhpbooks1\"/>\n\n[[Tao Lin]] has said of the book: \"Moving, funny, emotional, and\u2014in a revolutionary way\u2014both highly readable and avant-garde, ''Eat When You Feel Sad'' excites me very much in terms of literature and also life itself.\u201d<ref name=\"mhpbooks1\"/>\n\n==''Shitty Youth''==\n\nIn 2010, German started the internet radio show ''Shitty Youth'' after the death of his previous internet radio show ''Every Time A Police Officer Gets Shot I Throw a Party Radio''. ''Shitty Youth'' generally broadcasts on Sundays.\n\nIn November 2012, director [[Adam Humphreys]] released a documentary about German, also titled [http://vimeo.com/41526122 ''Shitty Youth''].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/who-is-zachary-german|title=WHO IS ZACHARY GERMAN?|publisher=Vice Magazine|date=2013-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Zachary German, website http://www.zacharygerman.com/\n* Eat When You Feel Sad at Melville House http://www.mhpbooks.com/book.php?id=312\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:German, Zachary}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Notability|Biographies|date=May 2010}}\n'''Zachary German''' (born December 17, 1988) is an [[American novelist]] and [[poet]]. His first novel, ''Eat When You Feel Sad,'' was published by [[Melville House Publishing|Melville House]] in 2010.<ref name=\"mhpbooks1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mhpbooks.com/book.php?id=312 |title=Eat When You Feel Sad |publisher=Melville House Publishing : Zachary German |date= |accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref>\n\nGerman's poems and prose have been published in [[Dennis Cooper]]'s ''Userland'' anthology,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/1933354151 |title=Userlands: New Fiction Writers from the Blogging Underground (Little House on the Bowery) : Dennis Cooper (Editor) |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref> [[3:AM Magazine]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.3ammagazine.com/3am/a-poem-about-new-york-citys-organic-vegan-restaurants/ |title=a poem about new york city\u2019s organic vegan restaurants : Zachary Graham |publisher=3:AM Magazine |date=2008-04-01 |accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref> Bear Parade,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bearparade.com/eatwhenyoufeelsad/ |title=Eat When You Feel Sad by Zachary German |publisher=Bearparade |date= |accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref> and Small Distribution Press.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spdbooks.org/Pages/Item/442/zachary-german-the-nike-swoosh-is-beautiful.aspx |title=Zachary German : The Nike Swoosh Is Beautiful |publisher=Small Press Distribution |date= |accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref>\n\n==''Eat When You Feel Sad''==\n\n''Eat When You Feel Sad'' was published by [[Melville House Publishing|Melville House]] in February 2010.<ref name=\"mhpbooks1\"/> It is about a character named Robert in an unnamed city.\n\nOnline and print response to ''Eat When You Feel Sad'' was mixed. It has been reviewed in [[Bookslut]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookslut.com/fiction/2010_04_015921.php|title=EAT WHEN YOU FEEL SAD BY ZACHARY GERMAN|publisher=Bookslut|accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref> [[The Rumpus]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://therumpus.net/2010/03/twenty-and-bored-and-alive/|title=TWENTY AND BORED AND ALIVE|publisher=The Rumpus|accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref> [[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out Chicago]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timeoutchicago.com/arts-culture/books/74852/eat-when-you-feel-sad|title=Eat When You Feel Sad|publisher=Time Out Chicago|accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref> [[Publishers Weekly]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-933633-85-5|title=Eat When You Feel Sad|publisher=Publishers Weekly|accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref> [[Philadelphia City Paper]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.citypaper.net/articles/2010/02/04/mo-regrets|title=Mo' Regrets|publisher=Philadelphia City Paper|accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref> and [[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zacharygerman.com/2005/01/news.html |title=every time a police officer gets shot i throw a party |publisher=Zachary German |date=2005-01-23 |accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref>\n\n[[Dennis Cooper]] has said of the book: \u201cZachary German\u2019s nimble, catwalking, archeological, surface dwelling, emotionally unpaved prose is a thing of total wonder and my favorite drug, language-based or otherwise. ''Eat When You Feel Sad'' is so bright and pleasurable and full of excellence, it\u2019s positively serene.\u201d<ref name=\"mhpbooks1\"/>\n\n[[Tao Lin]] has said of the book: \"Moving, funny, emotional, and\u2014in a revolutionary way\u2014both highly readable and avant-garde, ''Eat When You Feel Sad'' excites me very much in terms of literature and also life itself.\u201d<ref name=\"mhpbooks1\"/>\n\n==''Shitty Youth''==\n\nIn 2010, German started the internet radio show ''Shitty Youth'' after the death of his previous internet radio show ''Every Time A Police Officer Gets Shot I Throw a Party Radio''. ''Shitty Youth'' generally broadcasts on Sundays.\n\nIn November 2012, director [[Adam Humphreys]] released a documentary about German, also titled [http://vimeo.com/41526122 ''Shitty Youth''].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/who-is-zachary-german|title=WHO IS ZACHARY GERMAN?|publisher=Vice Magazine|date=2013-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Zachary German, website http://www.zacharygerman.com/\n* Eat When You Feel Sad at Melville House http://www.mhpbooks.com/book.php?id=312\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:German, Zachary}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Alt-lit]]\n", "name_user": "BrownHairedGirl", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing fromCategory:Alt-lit.   @User:Theghostofcaptmoore: PerWP:REDNOT, please use only categories which actually exist usingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zachary_German"}
{"title_page": "Brendan Connell", "text_new": "{{short description|American author and translator|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Brendan Connell''' (born 1970) is an American author and translator. Though his work often falls into the horror and fantasy genres, it has also often been called unclassifiable and avant-garde.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fright.com/edge/LifeOPolycrates.htm|title=THE LIFE OF POLYCRATES by Brendan Connell--Fright.com review|website=www.fright.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fright.com/edge/MissHomicide.htm|title=MISS HOMICIDE PLAYS THE FLUTE by BRENDAN CONNELL--Fright.com review|website=www.fright.com}}</ref> His style has been compared to that of [[J.K. Huysmans]]<ref>Metrophilias, introduction by Daniel Corrick</ref> and [[Angela Carter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infinityplus.co.uk/nonfiction/intjvm2.htm|title=Jeff VanderMeer interviewed - infinity plus non-fiction|website=www.infinityplus.co.uk}}</ref> Some of his shorter fiction, such as that contained in his collection ''Metrophilias'', has been referred to as prose poetry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-943813-07-0|title=Fiction Book Review: Metrophilias  by Brendan Connell. Snuggly,   $12.50 ISBN 978-1-943813-07-0|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nInfluences he has cited, include [[Balzac]] and [[Ponson du Terrail]].<ref name=\"risingshadow.net\">{{cite web|url=https://www.risingshadow.net/articles/334-an-interview-with-brendan-connell|title=An interview with Brendan Connell|website=www.risingshadow.net}}</ref> He has also written many lyrics for the Serbian band Kodagain.<ref name=\"risingshadow.net\"/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n=== Novels ===\n*''The Translation of Father Torturo'', Prime Books, 2005\n*''The Architect'', PS Publishing, 2012\n*''Miss Homicide Plays the Flute'', Eibonvale Press, 2013\n*''The Cutest Girl in Class'', Snuggly Books, 2013\n*''The Galaxy Club'', Chomu Press, 2014\n*''Cannibals of West Papua'', Zagava, 2015\n*''Clark'', Snuggly Books, 2016\n*''The Heel'', Snuggly Books, 2017\n\n=== Collections ===\n*''Metrophilias'', Better Non Sequitur, 2010\n*''Unpleasant Tales'', Eibonvale Press, 2010\n*''The Life of Polycrates and Other Stories for Antiquated Children'', Chomu Press, 2011\n*''Lives of Notorious Cooks'', Chomu Press, 2012\n*''The Metanatural Adventures of Dr. Black'', PS Publishing, 2014\n*''Jottings from a Far Away Place'', Snuggly Books, 2015\n*''Pleasant Tales'', Eibonvale Press, 2017\n\n=== Translations ===\n*''Requiems and Nightmares'', by Guido Gozzano, Hieroglyphic Press, 2012 (translated together with Anna Fonti Connell)\n\n=== Interviews ===\n* [https://weirdfictionreview.com/2012/09/interview-the-weird-and-brendan-and-anna-connell/ Brendan Connell Interview] (Weird Fiction Review, September 2012)\n* [https://www.risingshadow.net/articles/334-an-interview-with-brendan-connell Brendan Connell Interview] (Rising Shadow, March 2014)\n* [https://culturedvultures.com/interview-brendan-connell-author-jottings-far-away-place/ Brendan Connell Interview] (Cultured Vultures, February 2016)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n\n* {{isfdb name|id=Brendan_Connell|name= Brendan Connell}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Connell, Brendan}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American horror writers]]\n[[Category:American speculative fiction critics]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:Postmodern writers]]\n[[Category:American short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American author and translator|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Brendan Connell''' (born 1970) is an American author and translator. Though his work often falls into the horror and fantasy genres, it has also often been called unclassifiable and avant-garde.<ref>{{cite web|url=ht