{"title_page": "Marie Calloway", "text_new": "{{short description|American author|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox writer \n| name          = Marie Calloway\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = 1990\n| birth_place   = Japan, Oregon, \n| nationality   = American\n| alma_mater    = \n| genre         = literary fiction\n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| website       = \n}}\n'''Marie Calloway''' (born 1990) is an [[United States|American]] [[author]]. Her first book, ''what purpose did i serve in your life?'' was published by [[Tyrant Books]] and generated controversy.<ref>http://flavorwire.com/399421/it-doesnt-matter-if-you-think-its-good-in-defense-of-marie-calloway/</ref><ref>http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/publisher-news/article/55516-citing-content-issue-printer-refuses-to-print-marie-calloway-s-tyrant-books-debut.html</ref><ref>https://huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/22/marie-calloway-what-purpose_n_3307240.html</ref><ref>http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/books/2013/06/marie_calloway_what_purpose_did_i_serve_in_your_life_is_a_titillating_frustrating.html</ref>  A portion of the volume recounts the author's romantic relationship with a married journalist, Adrien Brody, and is reportedly based on an actual relationship with a prominent American writer.<ref>Orange, Michelle.  Men Respond to Marie:  The titillating, frustrating debut by online lit\u2019s enfant terrible.  Slate, http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/books/2013/06/marie_calloway_what_purpose_did_i_serve_in_your_life_is_a_titillating_frustrating.html</ref>  Daniel D'Addario of Salon said the article upon which the book was based \"sent shockwaves through the publishing industry.\"<ref>D'Addario, Daniel. Memoirist Marie Calloway: \u201cI don\u2019t like the privileging of other topics over sex,\u201d Salon, June 12, 2013. http://www.salon.com/2013/06/12/memoirist_marie_calloway_i_dont_like_the_privileging_of_other_topics_over_sex</ref>\n\nHer writing has been championed by literary provocateur [[Tao Lin]] and is considered a staple of [[alternative literature]].<ref>Stoeffel, Kat. Meet Marie Calloway: The New Model for Literary Seductress is Part Feminist, Part \u2018Famewhore\u2019 and All Pseudonymous, The New York Observer, December 20, 2011. http://observer.com/2011/12/meet-marie-calloway</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nA writer in ''Esquire'' described Calloway as belonging to an \"'Asperger's style' of literature, the mode of a small New York-based coterie of writers who specialize in disaffection and disconnection.\"<ref>Marche, Stephen.  Esquire, June 10, 2013.http://www.esquire.com/blogs/culture/marie-calloway-tao-lin></ref> [[Jacob M. Appel]] at ''Quarterly Conversation'' compared Calloway to [[Jane Austen]]'s [[Marianne Dashwood]] and [[George Eliot]]'s [[Dorothea Brooke]].<ref>Appel, JM. QC.  Sept 2, 2013.  http://quarterlyconversation.com/what-purpose-did-i-serve-in-your-life-by-marie-calloway</ref> A writer in \"Bookforum\" described the controversy that greeted Calloway's debut, writing, \"The initial publication of \"adrien brody\" on novelist Tao Lin's website Muumuu House heralded Calloway's arrival in the New York literary scene\u2014as an author, but also as a phenomenon. Brody was recognizable to insiders, and the ethics of Calloway's exposure were questioned, often within broader attacks on her sexual morality and provincial assessments of her craft.\"<ref>Fateman, Johanna. Bookforum.  Sept, 2013.  http://www.bookforum.com/inprint/020_03/12182</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''what purpose did i serve in your life'', 2013. [[Tyrant Books]] {{OCLC|812258823}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calloway, Maria}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American author|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox writer \n| name          = Marie Calloway\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = 1990\n| birth_place   = Japan, Oregon, \n| nationality   = American\n| alma_mater    = \n| genre         = literary fiction\n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| website       = \n}}\n'''Marie Calloway''' (born 1990) is an [[United States|American]] [[author]]. Her first book, ''what purpose did i serve in your life?'' was published by [[Tyrant Books]] and generated controversy.<ref>http://flavorwire.com/399421/it-doesnt-matter-if-you-think-its-good-in-defense-of-marie-calloway/</ref><ref>http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/publisher-news/article/55516-citing-content-issue-printer-refuses-to-print-marie-calloway-s-tyrant-books-debut.html</ref><ref>https://huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/22/marie-calloway-what-purpose_n_3307240.html</ref><ref>http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/books/2013/06/marie_calloway_what_purpose_did_i_serve_in_your_life_is_a_titillating_frustrating.html</ref>  A portion of the volume recounts the author's romantic relationship with a married journalist, Adrien Brody, and is reportedly based on an actual relationship with a prominent American writer.<ref>Orange, Michelle.  Men Respond to Marie:  The titillating, frustrating debut by online lit\u2019s enfant terrible.  Slate, http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/books/2013/06/marie_calloway_what_purpose_did_i_serve_in_your_life_is_a_titillating_frustrating.html</ref>  Daniel D'Addario of Salon said the article upon which the book was based \"sent shockwaves through the publishing industry.\"<ref>D'Addario, Daniel. Memoirist Marie Calloway: \u201cI don\u2019t like the privileging of other topics over sex,\u201d Salon, June 12, 2013. http://www.salon.com/2013/06/12/memoirist_marie_calloway_i_dont_like_the_privileging_of_other_topics_over_sex</ref>\n\nHer writing has been championed by literary provocateur [[Tao Lin]] and is considered a staple of [[alternative literature]].<ref>Stoeffel, Kat. Meet Marie Calloway: The New Model for Literary Seductress is Part Feminist, Part \u2018Famewhore\u2019 and All Pseudonymous, The New York Observer, December 20, 2011. http://observer.com/2011/12/meet-marie-calloway</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nA writer in ''Esquire'' described Calloway as belonging to an \"'Asperger's style' of literature, the mode of a small New York-based coterie of writers who specialize in disaffection and disconnection.\"<ref>Marche, Stephen.  Esquire, June 10, 2013.http://www.esquire.com/blogs/culture/marie-calloway-tao-lin></ref> [[Jacob M. Appel]] at ''Quarterly Conversation'' compared Calloway to [[Jane Austen]]'s [[Marianne Dashwood]] and [[George Eliot]]'s [[Dorothea Brooke]].<ref>Appel, JM. QC.  Sept 2, 2013.  http://quarterlyconversation.com/what-purpose-did-i-serve-in-your-life-by-marie-calloway</ref> A writer in \"Bookforum\" described the controversy that greeted Calloway's debut, writing, \"The initial publication of \"adrien brody\" on novelist Tao Lin's website Muumuu House heralded Calloway's arrival in the New York literary scene\u2014as an author, but also as a phenomenon. Brody was recognizable to insiders, and the ethics of Calloway's exposure were questioned, often within broader attacks on her sexual morality and provincial assessments of her craft.\"<ref>Fateman, Johanna. Bookforum.  Sept, 2013.  http://www.bookforum.com/inprint/020_03/12182</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''what purpose did i serve in your life'', 2013. [[Tyrant Books]] {{OCLC|812258823}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calloway, Maria}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Alt-lit]]\n", "name_user": "BrownHairedGirl", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing fromCategory:Alt-lit.   @User:Theghostofcaptmoore: PerWP:REDNOT, please use only categories which actually exist usingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marie_Calloway"}
{"title_page": "Caroline Grassari", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               =  Caroline Grassari \n| image              = Grassari by Vigneron.jpg\n| image_upright =\n| birth_name        = Marie-Caroline-Josephine G\u00e9rard\n| birth_date    = \n| baptised      = 15 June 1795\n| birth_place   = [[Tongeren]], Belgium \n| death_date    = after 1832\n| death_place    = \n| occupation    = Opera singer ([[soprano]])\n}}\n'''Caroline Grassari''', born '''Marie-Caroline-Josephine G\u00e9rard''' (baptised 15 June 1795 \u2013 after 1832) was a French opera singer active at the [[Paris Op\u00e9ra]] from 1816 to 1828 where she sang leading [[soprano]] roles. Amongst the many roles she created were Almazie in [[Nicol\u00f2 Isouard|Isouard]]'s ''Aladin ou La lampe merveilleuse'' and Aurora in Carafa's ''[[La belle au bois dormant (Carafa)|La belle au bois dormant]]''.\n\n==Life and career==\nGrassari was born Marie-Caroline-Josephine G\u00e9rard in [[Tongeren]], Belgium, where she was baptised on 15 June 1795. Her father was {{ill|Fran\u00e7ois Joseph G\u00e9rard |fr}}, a highly decorated French general. Her mother,  Anne-Christine Tournay, was the daughter of Tongeren's [[Burgomaster]]. Her parents divorced in her childhood and she initially lived with her mother in Belgium, where she began her musical studies. In 1814, she was sent to Paris under the care of her father and finished her studies at the [[Conservatoire de Paris]].<ref name=\"Gregoire\" /><ref name=\"Cancan\" /><ref name = Fetis />\n\nShe made her stage debut under the name \"Mademoiselle Grassari\" at the [[Paris Op\u00e9ra]] on 13 February 1816 singing Antigone in Sacchini's ''[[\u0152dipe \u00e0 Colone]]''. She was then given a permanent position at the Op\u00e9ra as ''premier remplacement'', singing the roles of the primadonnas when they were unavailable as well as secondary roles. However, she soon rose to the first rank of singers and went on to create numerous leading roles for the company, including Aurora in Carafa's ''[[La belle au bois dormant (Carafa)|La belle au bois dormant]]'' and Elzire in Liszt's ''[[Don Sanche]]''. In April 1819 she also sang in the Op\u00e9ra's first and only performance of [[Maximilian Stadler]]'s oratorio ''La D\u00e9livrance de J\u00e9rusalem''.{{efn|The other soloists in the performance of ''La D\u00e9livrance de J\u00e9rusalem'' were the tenor Jean-Baptiste Lecomte and the bass [[Nicolas Levasseur]].<ref name=\"Buguet\" />}} Grassari was described in contemporary accounts as uniting a beautiful voice with compelling acting and a charming stage presence. She was particularly admired for her performances as Amazily in Spontini's ''[[Fernand Cortez]]'' and the title role in M\u00e9hul's ''[[Stratonice (opera)|Stratonice]]''.<ref name = Alhoy /><ref name=\"ICC\" /><ref name = Fetis />\n\nOne of Grassari's last performances at the Op\u00e9ra was in May 1827 as Pamina in ''Les myst\u00e8res d'Isis'', a [[Pasticcio|pastiche opera]] by [[Ludwig Wenzel Lachnith]] based on the story of Mozart's ''[[Die Zauberfl\u00f6te]]''. Faced with enormous deficits in 1828, \u00c9mile Lubbert, the new director of the Op\u00e9ra, gave notice to [[Henri-\u00c9tienne D\u00e9rivis]] that his contract would not be renewed and asked Grassari to retire early. She was paid 30,000 francs to cancel her contract. According to her father's death certificate, she was still alive when he died in September 1832. Earlier that year articles had appeared in ''Gazette des Tribunaux'' and ''Giornale del Regno delle Due Sicilie'' describing a lawsuit which she brought against her former protector and lover, Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Levrat,{{efn|Prior to his relationship with Grassari, Levrat had been the protector of Jos\u00e9phine Rolandeau (1774\u20131809), a singer at the [[Op\u00e9ra-Comique]].<ref name=\"SClub\" /> For more on the role of \"protector\" in the theatrical life in 19th-century France, see White, Kimberly (2018). ''Female Singers on the French Stage, 1830\u20131848'', pp. 175\u2013178. Cambridge University Press. ISBN 1108643191 and Dickinson, Linzy (2000). ''Theatre in Balzac's La Com\u00e9die Humaine'', pp. 130\u2013168. Rodopi. ISBN 9042005491.}} whom she accused of using her pension from the Op\u00e9ra to pay off his creditors.{{efn|In his testimony Levrat claimed that he had met Grassari when she was still a student at the Paris conservatory and living in a [[garret]] in extreme poverty. In Levrat's telling, he set her up in a luxurious house replete with [[Aubusson, Creuse#Tapestry|Aubusson]] carpets and crystal chandeliers, satisfied all of her \"whims\" which were both \"expensive and continuous\", invited her mother and siblings to move in with her, and also paid all their expenses. According to Levrat, once he found himself in financial difficulty twelve years later, Grassari was no longer happy to \"lavish him with her caresses\" as she had in the past and became simply a \"greedy woman\". The Commerce Tribunal ultimately dismissed the case on the grounds that it was an interpersonal dispute rather than commercial one and not within the court's purview. Grassari was ordered to pay Levrat's legal costs.<ref name=\"GdT1\" /><ref name=\"GdRdDS1\" />}} Apart from those articles, news of her disappeared completely from the French press after her retirement. [[Arthur Pougin]] wrote in 1906 that despite an extensive search, he was unable to find any publication of the date of her death, a fact which he found remarkable given her considerable fame during the twelve years she was on the stage.<ref name = AA /><ref name = White /><ref name=\"Death1\" /><ref name=\"GdT1\" /><ref name=\"GdRdDS1\" /><ref name=\"ICC\" />\n\n==Roles created==\nGrassari's performances in world premieres at the [[Paris Op\u00e9ra]] included:\n[[File:Grassari as Almazie in Aladin ou La lampe merveilleuse.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|Grassari as Almasie in ''Aladin ou La lampe merveilleuse'']]\n*Parth\u00e9nope in ''Les dieux rivaux ou Les f\u00eates de Cyth\u00e8re'' ([[opera-ballet]] in 1 act) jointly composed by [[Henri-Montan Berton|Berton]], [[Rodolphe Kreutzer|Kreutzer]], [[Louis-Luc Loiseau de Persuis|Loiseau de Persuis]] and [[Gaspare Spontini|Spontini]]; 21 June 1816 (marking the marriage of the [[Charles Ferdinand, Duke of Berry|Duke of Berry]])<ref name = AA />\n*Alexis in ''Nathalie ou La famille russe'' (opera in 3 acts) composed by [[Antoine Reicha|Reicha]]; 30 July 1816<ref name=\"Laugier\" />\n*Aspasie in ''Aspasie et P\u00e9ricl\u00e8s'' (opera in 1 act) composed by [[Joseph Daussoigne-M\u00e9hul|Daussoigne-M\u00e9hul]]; 17 July 1820<ref name=\"Laugier\" />\n*Almasie in  ''Aladin ou La lampe merveilleuse'' (opera in 5 acts) composed by [[Nicolas Isouard|Isouard]]; 6 February 1822<ref name = AA />\n*Virginie in ''Virginie ou Les D\u00e9cemvirs'' (opera in 3 acts) composed by Berton; 11 June 1823\n*Lasth\u00e9nie in ''Lasth\u00e9nie'' (opera in 1 act) composed by [[Ferdinand H\u00e9rold|H\u00e9rold]]; 8 September 1823<ref name=\"Laugier\" />\n*La Reine in ''Vend\u00f4me en Espagne'' (opera in 1 act) jointly composed by [[Daniel-Fran\u00e7ois-Esprit Auber|Auber]] and H\u00e9rold; 5 December 1823 (marking the return of the  [[Charles X of France|Duke of Angoul\u00eame]] from Spain)<ref name = AA />\n*Z\u00e9naire in ''Ipsibo\u00e9'' (opera in 4 acts) composed by Kreutzer; 31 March 1824<ref name=\"Laugier\" />\n*Zul\u00e9ma in ''Les deux Salem'' (opera in 1 act) composed by Daussoigne-M\u00e9hul; 12 July 1824<ref name=\"Laugier\" />\n*Aurora in ''[[La belle au bois dormant (Carafa)|La belle au bois dormant]]'' (opera in 3 acts) composed by [[Michele Carafa|Carafa]]; 2 March 1825<ref name = AA />\n*Ph\u00e9dora in ''Pharamond'' (opera in 3 acts) jointly composed by [[Fran\u00e7ois Adrien Boieldieu|Boieldieu]], Berton, and Kreutzer; 10 June 1825 (marking the coronation of [[Charles X of France|Charles X]])<ref name = AA />\n*Elzire in ''[[Don Sanche|Don Sanche, ou Le ch\u00e2teau de l'amour]]'' (opera in 1 act) composed by [[Franz Liszt|Liszt]]; 17 October 1825<ref name=\"ICC\" />\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name = White>White, Kimberly (2018). [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BqxcDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA151 ''Female Singers on the French Stage, 1830\u20131848''], p. 151. Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|1108643191}}</ref>\n\n<ref name = Fetis>F\u00e9tis, Fran\u00e7ois-Joseph and Pougin, Arthur (1881). [https://archive.org/details/biographiemusyork01ftuoft/page/416 \"Grassari (Mademoiselle Gerard)\"]. ''Biographie universelle des musiciens (Suppl\u00e9ment et Compl\u00e9ment)'', Vol. 1, p. 416. Firmin Didot {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n<ref name = Alhoy>Alhoy, Philadelphe Maurice (1824). [https://archive.org/details/grandebiographie00alho/page/168 \"Grassari\"] ''Grande biographie dramatique'', p. 168. Chez les marchands de nouveaut\u00e9s {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n<ref name = AA>Casaglia, Gherardo (2005). [http://almanac-gherardo-casaglia.com/index.php?Start=0&Giorno=&Mese=&Anno=&Giornata=&Testo=Grassari&Parola=Stringa \"Grassari\"]. ''Almanacco Amadeus''. Retrieved 9 November 2019 {{in lang|it}}.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gregoire\">Gregoire, \u00c9douard Georges Jacques (1885). ''Les artistes-musiciens belges au XVIIIme et au XIXme si\u00e8cle'', p. 211. Schott Fr\u00e8res</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ICC\">Pougin, Arthur (30 October 1906). [https://archive.org/details/lintermdiaired54pariuoft/page/308 \"Madame Grassari, cantatrice\"]. ''[[L'Interm\u00e9diaire des chercheurs et curieux]]'', columns 629\u2013633. Retrieved 9 November 2019 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Death1\">Grande Chancellerie de la L\u00e9gion d'honneur (14 August 1833). [https://en.geneanet.org/archives/actes/actesenligne/2215395 \"D\u00e9c\u00e8s: G\u00e9rard, Fran\u00e7ois Joseph, 18 Septembre 1832\"]. Retrieved 9 November 2019 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Laugier\">Laugier, Adolphe (1826). [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=b_X1mxsc8XkC&pg=PA19 ''Galerie biographique des artistes dramatiques des th\u00e9\u00e2tres royaux''], pp. 19\u201322. Ponthieux {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GdT1\">[[s.n.]] (24 February 1832). [http://data.decalog.net/enap1/Liens/Gazette/ENAP_GAZETTE_TRIBUNAUX_18320224.pdf \"Trbunal de Commerce de Paris\"]. ''Gazette des Tribunaux'', p. 1. Retrieved 13 November 2019 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GdRdDS1\">G. di C. (2 June 1832). [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NNtN_tOiUhMC&pg=PA536 \"Francia: Marsiglia 1 maggio\"]. ''Giornale del Regno delle Due Sicilie'', p. 536 {{in lang|it}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Cancan\">Tamvaco, Jean-Louis and Guest, Ivor Forbes (eds). (2000). ''Les cancans de l'Op\u00e9ra'', p. 422. [[CNRS]]. {{ISBN|2271057426}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Buguet\">Buguet, Henry (1875). [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yB2I94MQm-QC&pg=PA263 ''Foyers et coulisses: Op\u00e9ra'']. p. 263. Tresse {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SClub\">Doyon, A. and Du Parc, Y. (October 1974) . \"De Bonaparte a Stendhal: Jos\u00e9phine Rolandeau\". ''Stendhal Club'', pp. 55, 65. \u00c9ditions du Grand-Ch\u00eane</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grassari, Caroline}}\n[[Category:1795 births]]\n[[Category:19th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:Belgian operatic sopranos]]\n[[Category:People from Tongeren]]\n[[Category:Conservatoire de Paris alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               =  Caroline Grassari \n| image              = Grassari by Vigneron.jpg\n| image_upright =\n| birth_name        = Marie-Caroline-Josephine G\u00e9rard\n| birth_date    = \n| baptised      = 15 June 1795\n| birth_place   = [[Tongeren]], Belgium \n| death_date    = after 1832\n| death_place    = \n| occupation    = Opera singer ([[soprano]])\n}}\n'''Caroline Grassari''', born '''Marie-Caroline-Josephine G\u00e9rard''' (baptised 15 June 1795 \u2013 after 1832) was a French opera singer active at the [[Paris Op\u00e9ra]] from 1816 to 1828 where she sang leading [[soprano]] roles. Amongst the many roles she created were Almazie in [[Nicol\u00f2 Isouard|Isouard]]'s ''Aladin ou La lampe merveilleuse'' and Aurora in Carafa's ''[[La belle au bois dormant (Carafa)|La belle au bois dormant]]''.\n==Life and career== \nGrassari was born Marie-Caroline-Josephine G\u00e9rard in [[Tongeren]], Belgium, where she was baptised on 15 June 1795. Her father was {{ill|Fran\u00e7ois Joseph G\u00e9rard |fr}}, a highly decorated French general. Her mother,  Anne-Christine Tournay, was the daughter of Tongeren's [[Burgomaster]]. Her parents divorced in her childhood and she initially lived with her mother in Belgium, where she began her musical studies. In 1814, she was sent to Paris under the care of her father and finished her studies at the [[Conservatoire de Paris]].<ref name=\"Gregoire\" /><ref name=\"Cancan\" /><ref name = Fetis /> \n\nShe made her stage debut under the name \"Mademoiselle Grassari\" at the [[Paris Op\u00e9ra]] on 13 February 1816 singing Antigone in Sacchini's ''[[\u0152dipe \u00e0 Colone]]''. She was then given a permanent position at the Op\u00e9ra as ''premier remplacement'', singing the roles of the primadonnas when they were unavailable as well as secondary roles. However, she soon rose to the first rank of singers and went on to create numerous leading roles for the company, including Aurora in Carafa's ''[[La belle au bois dormant (Carafa)|La belle au bois dormant]]'' and Elzire in Liszt's ''[[Don Sanche]]''. In April 1819 she also sang in the Op\u00e9ra's first and only performance of [[Maximilian Stadler]]'s oratorio ''La D\u00e9livrance de J\u00e9rusalem''.{{efn|The other soloists in the performance of ''La D\u00e9livrance de J\u00e9rusalem'' were the tenor Jean-Baptiste Lecomte and the bass [[Nicolas Levasseur]].<ref name=\"Buguet\" />}} Grassari was described in contemporary accounts as uniting a beautiful voice with compelling acting and a charming stage presence. She was particularly admired for her performances as Amazily in Spontini's ''[[Fernand Cortez]]'' and the title role in M\u00e9hul's ''[[Stratonice (opera)|Stratonice]]''.<ref name = Alhoy /><ref name=\"ICC\" /><ref name = Fetis />  \n\nOne of Grassari's last performances at the Op\u00e9ra was in May 1827 as Pamina in ''Les myst\u00e8res d'Isis'', a [[Pasticcio|pastiche opera]] by [[Ludwig Wenzel Lachnith]] based on the story of Mozart's ''[[Die Zauberfl\u00f6te]]''. Faced with enormous deficits in 1828, \u00c9mile Lubbert, the new director of the Op\u00e9ra, gave notice to [[Henri-\u00c9tienne D\u00e9rivis]] that his contract would not be renewed and asked Grassari to retire early. She was paid 30,000 francs to cancel her contract. According to her father's death certificate, she was still alive when he died in September 1832. Earlier that year articles had appeared in ''Gazette des Tribunaux'' and ''Giornale del Regno delle Due Sicilie'' describing a lawsuit which she brought against her former protector and lover, Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Levrat,{{efn|Prior to his relationship with Grassari, Levrat had been the protector of Jos\u00e9phine Rolandeau (1774\u20131809), a singer at the [[Op\u00e9ra-Comique]].<ref name=\"SClub\" /> For more on the role of \"protector\" in the theatrical life in 19th-century France, see White, Kimberly (2018). ''Female Singers on the French Stage, 1830\u20131848'', pp. 175\u2013178. Cambridge University Press. ISBN 1108643191 and Dickinson, Linzy (2000). ''Theatre in Balzac's La Com\u00e9die Humaine'', pp. 130\u2013168. Rodopi. ISBN 9042005491.}} whom she accused of using her pension from the Op\u00e9ra to pay off his creditors.{{efn|In his testimony Levrat claimed that he had met Grassari when she was still a student at the Paris conservatory and living in a [[garret]] in extreme poverty. In Levrat's telling, he set her up in a luxurious house replete with [[Aubusson, Creuse#Tapestry|Aubusson]] carpets and crystal chandeliers, satisfied all of her \"whims\" which were both \"expensive and continuous\", invited her mother and siblings to move in with her, and also paid all their expenses. According to Levrat, once he found himself in financial difficulty twelve years later, Grassari was no longer happy to \"lavish him with her caresses\" as she had in the past and became simply a \"greedy woman\". The Commerce Tribunal ultimately dismissed the case on the grounds that it was an interpersonal dispute rather than commercial one and not within the court's purview. Grassari was ordered to pay Levrat's legal costs.<ref name=\"GdT1\" /><ref name=\"GdRdDS1\" />}} Apart from those articles, news of her disappeared completely from the French press after her retirement. [[Arthur Pougin]] wrote in 1906 that despite an extensive search, he was unable to find any publication of the date of her death, a fact which he found remarkable given her considerable fame during the twelve years she was on the stage.<ref name = AA /><ref name = White /><ref name=\"Death1\" /><ref name=\"GdT1\" /><ref name=\"GdRdDS1\" /><ref name=\"ICC\" />\n\n==Roles created==\nGrassari's performances in world premieres at the [[Paris Op\u00e9ra]] included:\n[[File:Grassari as Almazie in Aladin ou La lampe merveilleuse.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|Grassari as Almasie in  ''Aladin ou La lampe merveilleuse'']]\n*Parth\u00e9nope in ''Les dieux rivaux ou Les f\u00eates de Cyth\u00e8re'' ([[opera-ballet]] in 1 act) jointly composed by [[Henri-Montan Berton|Berton]], [[Rodolphe Kreutzer|Kreutzer]], [[Louis-Luc Loiseau de Persuis|Loiseau de Persuis]] and [[Gaspare Spontini|Spontini]]; 21 June 1816 (marking the marriage of the [[Charles Ferdinand, Duke of Berry|Duke of Berry]])<ref name = AA />\n*Alexis in ''Nathalie ou La famille russe'' (opera in 3 acts) composed by [[Antoine Reicha|Reicha]]; 30 July 1816<ref name=\"Laugier\" />\n*Aspasie in ''Aspasie et P\u00e9ricl\u00e8s'' (opera in 1 act) composed by [[Joseph Daussoigne-M\u00e9hul|Daussoigne-M\u00e9hul]]; 17 July 1820<ref name=\"Laugier\" />\n*Almasie in  ''Aladin ou La lampe merveilleuse'' (opera in 5 acts) composed by [[Nicolas Isouard|Isouard]]; 6 February 1822<ref name = AA />\n*Virginie in ''Virginie ou Les D\u00e9cemvirs'' (opera in 3 acts) composed by Berton; 11 June 1823\n*Lasth\u00e9nie in ''Lasth\u00e9nie'' (opera in 1 act) composed by [[Ferdinand H\u00e9rold|H\u00e9rold]]; 8 September 1823<ref name=\"Laugier\" />\n*La Reine in ''Vend\u00f4me en Espagne'' (opera in 1 act) jointly composed by [[Daniel-Fran\u00e7ois-Esprit Auber|Auber]] and H\u00e9rold; 5 December 1823 (marking the return of the  [[Charles X of France|Duke of Angoul\u00eame]] from Spain)<ref name = AA />\n*Z\u00e9naire in ''Ipsibo\u00e9'' (opera in 4 acts) composed by Kreutzer; 31 March 1824<ref name=\"Laugier\" />\n*Zul\u00e9ma in ''Les deux Salem'' (opera in 1 act) composed by Daussoigne-M\u00e9hul; 12 July 1824<ref name=\"Laugier\" />\n*Aurora in ''[[La belle au bois dormant (Carafa)|La belle au bois dormant]]'' (opera in 3 acts) composed by [[Michele Carafa|Carafa]]; 2 March 1825<ref name = AA />\n*Ph\u00e9dora in ''Pharamond'' (opera in 3 acts) jointly composed by [[Fran\u00e7ois Adrien Boieldieu|Boieldieu]], Berton, and Kreutzer; 10 June 1825 (marking the coronation of [[Charles X of France|Charles X]])<ref name = AA />\n*Elzire in ''[[Don Sanche|Don Sanche, ou Le ch\u00e2teau de l'amour]]'' (opera in 1 act) composed by [[Franz Liszt|Liszt]]; 17 October 1825<ref name=\"ICC\" />\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name = White>White, Kimberly (2018). [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BqxcDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA151 ''Female Singers on the French Stage, 1830\u20131848''], p. 151. Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|1108643191}}</ref>\n\n<ref name = Fetis>F\u00e9tis, Fran\u00e7ois-Joseph and Pougin, Arthur (1881). [https://archive.org/details/biographiemusyork01ftuoft/page/416 \"Grassari (Mademoiselle Gerard)\"]. ''Biographie universelle des musiciens (Suppl\u00e9ment et Compl\u00e9ment)'', Vol. 1, p. 416. Firmin Did