 football]] games that ABC carries during the fall may subject ''Weekend Adventure'' programs normally aired on Saturdays in the 11:00&nbsp;a.m. hour, as well as the syndicated ''[[Teen Kids News]]'', to be deferred to Sundays to fulfill [[Children's Television Act|educational programming]] obligations.) Channel 5 may preempt some ABC programs to provide long-form breaking news or severe weather coverage when necessary, or air specials produced by the station's news department (such as its ''KOCO 5 Chronicle'' series or weather and sports specials). The preempted programs may either be [[broadcast delay|rebroadcast]] over KOCO in place of regularly scheduled overnight programs or diverted to KOCO-DT2 on a live-to-air basis in place of MeTV programming, although station personnel also gives viewers\u2014particularly, subscribers of [[AT&T U-verse]], [[DirecTV]], [[Dish Network]] and some smaller cable systems within the Oklahoma City DMA that do not carry KOCO-DT2\u2014the option of watching them on ABC's website and [[mobile app]], [[Hulu]], or its cable/satellite [[video-on-demand]] service the day after their initial airing.\n\n[[Broadcast syndication|Syndicated]] programs broadcast by KOCO-TV {{as of|September 2019|lc=y}} include ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'', ''[[The Dr. Oz Show]]'', ''[[Tamron Hall (talk show)|Tamron Hall]]'', ''[[The Kelly Clarkson Show]]'', ''[[Access Hollywood]]'', ''[[Matter of Fact with Soledad O'Brien]]'' (distributed by parent company Hearst), ''[[The Real (talk show)|The Real]]'' and ''[[Wheel of Fortune (American game show)|Wheel of Fortune]]''. (Oklahoma City is one of a small number of U.S. television markets in which ''Jeopardy!'' and ''Wheel'' are carried on separate stations: ''Jeopardy!'' airs on NBC affiliate KFOR-TV, which has carried the program locally since January 2000 after CBS affiliate KWTV initially dropped the program in September 1999 when that station moved its 4:30&nbsp;p.m. newscast back to 4:00&nbsp;p.m. and expanded it to an hour, only to bring ''Jeopardy!'' back a few days later in an early-morning, 4:30&nbsp;a.m. timeslot. Both ''Wheel'' and ''Jeopardy!'' were seen on KWTV from their respective debuts in 1983 and 1984 until the former moved to KOCO in September 1992).<ref name=\"KOCO schedule\">{{cite web|title=TitanTV Programming Guide -- What's on TV, Movies, Reality Shows and Local News: KOCO-TV schedule|url=http://koco.titantv.com/apg/ttv.aspx?siteid=53470|website=Titan TV|publisher=Broadcast Interactive Media, LLC|accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Local Stations Trade Syndicated Programming|url=http://newsok.com/article/2404113|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=August 23, 1992|accessdate=July 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Viewers here won't see 'Jeopardy' until 2000|url=http://newsok.com/article/2666355|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=September 3, 1999|accessdate=July 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Jeopardy' back, very early|url=http://newsok.com/article/2666877|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=September 8, 1999|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Jeopardy' may air at a decent hour|url=http://newsok.com/article/2678063|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=December 9, 1999|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nChannel 5 served as the Oklahoma City affiliate of the ''[[Children's Miracle Network Hospitals|Children's Miracle Network Telethon]]'' from its inception in May 1983 until June 2016. Until 2004, KOCO typically aired the first hour of the telethon on tape delay after the Saturday edition of its late-evening newscast, depending on the telethon's airdate, on the last weekend of May or first weekend of June; the remainder of the telecast (including local segments hosted by KOCO on-air personalities) would then air through its conclusion the following Sunday afternoon.<ref>{{cite news|title=Children's Miracle Network Telethon Begins Saturday|url=http://newsok.com/article/2358153|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=May 26, 1991|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Telethon To Aid Research|url=http://newsok.com/article/2395125|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=May 20, 1992|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> It also served as the local broadcaster of the ''[[United Cerebral Palsy|United Cerebral Palsy Star-athon]]'', a telethon to raise money for the [[cerebral palsy]] research organization, from 1962 to 1996.<ref>{{cite news|title=Local, National Celebrities Join Lineup for Cerebral Palsy Telethon|url=http://newsok.com/article/2418631|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=January 17, 1993|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Local Faces to Join Telethon As Fund-Raiser Enters 33rd Year|url=http://newsok.com/article/2489635|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=January 15, 1995|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Past program preemptions and deferrals===\nHistorically, KOCO-TV has either preempted or given out-of-pattern clearances to certain ABC programs to air local, syndicated or special event programs. After it debuted a noon newscast in September 1978, the station aired ''[[All My Children]]'' (which ABC concurrently moved to the aforementioned slot with the [[soap opera]]'s expansion to a full hour) on a day-behind basis at 11:00&nbsp;a.m., which resulted in the preemption of ABC Daytime shows that normally occupied that hour in the [[Central Time Zone]] (such as the network version of ''[[Family Feud#1976\u201385|Family Feud]]'') until it was ceded to ABC's affiliates in September 1992; KOCO began carrying ''AMC'' live-to-air at noon on January 2, 2008, where the soap remained until it was replaced by ''[[The Chew]]'' on September 27, 2011. ''[[Loving (TV series)|Loving]]'' also aired mid-mornings on a one-day delay until September 1990, when the station replaced it with the hour-long version of ''[[Home (1988 TV program)|Home]]'' (which KOCO had aired in the talk show's optional half-hour abbreviated format since it debuted two years earlier);<ref name=\"oklahoman-koconewsteam\">{{cite web|title=KOCO News Team Listed|url=http://newsok.com/article/2327212|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=August 12, 1990|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> KOCO preempted ABC's half-hour soap operas (''Loving'', ''[[The City (1995 TV series)|The City]]'' and, until the station began clearing it in September 1998, ''[[Port Charles]]'') for most of the 1990s in favor of first-run syndicated shows and, after September 1994, an expanded midday newscast in its standard network slot. Until ABC discontinued the afternoon newsbriefs in 2012, the station also did not clear the ''ABC News Brief''\u2014which aired during [[ABC Daytime]] programming\u2014in order to run additional local advertising.\n\nBeginning with the [[News magazine#Television|newsmagazine]]'s debut in February 1980, KOCO ran ''[[Nightline]]'' on a half-hour tape delay from the ABC network feed (at 11:00&nbsp;p.m.) to air syndicated ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'' reruns following its late newscast. In the summer of 1983, station management sought ABC's permission to further delay ''Nightline'' by 90 minutes (to 12:30&nbsp;a.m.), so it could air ''[[Thicke of the Night]]'' after ''M*A*S*H'' once the syndicated late-night talk show premiered that September. ABC vetoed the request and moved ''Nightline'' to then-independent station KOKH-TV, which agreed to carry the program live-to-air; KOCO relented and received permission to resume airing ''Nightline'' on a one-hour delay beginning in April 1984, pushing back the near-cancellation ''Thicke'' by an extra half-hour. (The station eventually shifted ''Nightline'' to its network slot in September 1995.)<ref name=\"oklahoman-newscope\">{{cite news|title=5 changes face of 5 p.m. news|url=http://newsok.com/article/2040678|author=Joe Angus|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=September 25, 1983|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=How an indie used football to find ratings happiness|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/83-OCR/BC-1983-08-22-OCR-Page-0018.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=18|date=August 22, 1983|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Similarly, channel 5 tape-delayed other ABC late night shows that directly followed ''Nightline'' to air additional syndicated programming in [[Dayparting#Day parts on television|late access]]: ''[[Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher]]'' aired on a half-hour delay from its then-recommended 11:05&nbsp;p.m. Central timeslot from its ABC debut in September 1995 until it ended in December 2002; its replacement, ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' (which has preceded ''Nightline'' since the network switched the scheduling order of the two programs in January 2013), aired on a one-hour delay from its January 2003 premiere, in favor of a same-day ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show|Oprah]]'' rebroadcast, until KOCO pushed ''Kimmel'' to the show's network \"live\" slot in September 2011.  Because it signed off during the overnight hours at the time, KOCO also preempted the ABC News program ''World News Now'' from its January 6, 1992 premiere until the station permanently instituted a 24-hour schedule on November 28, 1993.\n\nChannel 5 also preempted portions of ABC's [[Saturday morning cartoon|Saturday morning]] lineup intermittently through September 2006 (as an example, ''[[The Bugs Bunny Show#Final Saturday morning years, 1985\u20132000|The Bugs Bunny and Tweety Show]]'' and ''[[Star Wars: Ewoks|Ewoks]]'' were preempted in favor of the local [[real estate]] program ''Home Showcase'' in 1987).<ref>{{cite web|title=Home Showcase TV Show Premiers/Saves Time For Buyers|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P2-5394803|newspaper=[[The Journal Record]]|publisher=The Journal Record Publishing Company|via=Questia Online Library|date=May 2, 1987}}</ref> The station also preempted all but 90 minutes of the then four-hour-long lineup between April 1992 and September 1996, in order to accommodate a local Saturday morning newscast and other syndicated programming.<ref>{{cite news|title=Too Close for Comfort|url=http://newsok.com/article/2390944|author=Tim Chavez|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=April 12, 1992|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> From September 1996 until December 2007, the ABC children's programs that were recommended to air during the 10:00&nbsp;a.m. hour aired instead on a one-week delay at 7:00&nbsp;a.m.; KOCO aired the remaining two hours in pattern from the ABC off-air feed. The various ''[[Power Rangers]]'' series that aired as part of the [[ABC Kids (United States)|ABC Kids]] block were also aired on a one-week delay from 5:00 to 6:00&nbsp;a.m., instead of the network's \"live\"-fed slot during the 11:00&nbsp;a.m. hour, from September 2003 until September 2006; as Hearst's other ABC stations opted to do with the series, KOCO preempted ''Power Rangers'' thereafter until the series was dropped by the network on August 28, 2010 due to the program's lack of educational content. (For similar reasons, the station tape-delayed ''[[Kim Possible]]'' and ''[[Power Rangers SPD]]'' for broadcast on early Monday mornings before ''World News Now'' during the 2005\u201306 season.)\n\nIt was also among the more than 20 stations that declined to air ABC's November 2004 telecast of ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]'', amid concerns that the intense war violence and strong profanity retained from the 1998 [[World War II]]-set film's theatrical cut would subject stations that aired it to being fined by the FCC, which initiated a crackdown on indecent material following the [[Super Bowl XXXVIII halftime show controversy|wardrobe malfunction incident]] during [[Justin Timberlake]] and [[Janet Jackson]]'s [[Super Bowl XXXVIII]] halftime show performance that February.<ref name=\"postgazette-privateryan\">{{cite news|title=TV Note: WTAE, other ABC affiliates reject 'Private Ryan' telecast|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/ae/tv/tv-note-wtae-other-abc-affiliates-reject-private-ryan-telecast-557996/|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|publisher=[[Block Communications]]|date=November 12, 2004|accessdate=February 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Scaring Private Ryan: 20 ABC Affiliates Nix Movie|url=http://businessjournaldaily.com/scaring-private-ryan-20-abc-affiliates-nix-movie-2004-11-12|periodical=Business Journal Daily|date=November 12, 2004|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109042125/http://businessjournaldaily.com/scaring-private-ryan-20-abc-affiliates-nix-movie-2004-11-12|archivedate=November 9, 2013}}</ref> KOCO, along with the eight other Hearst-owned ABC stations\u2014out of the eleven it owned at the time\u2014that also refused to air ''Saving Private Ryan'', chose to air the 1992 film ''[[Far and Away]]'' in its place. (The FCC eventually determined that, even though content typically prohibited from being shown on broadcast television was not expurgated from the film's network cut, the movie's broadcast did not violate agency regulations.)<ref name=\"postgazette-privateryan\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Some stations shelved 'Private Ryan' amid FCC fears|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2004-11-11-private-ryan_x.htm|author=Ann Oldenburg|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|publisher=Gannett Company|date=November 11, 2004|accessdate=September 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Sports programming===\nSports programming on KOCO-TV is sourced solely through ABC's [[ESPN]]-managed sports programming unit, [[ESPN on ABC]]. Through ABC's television contract with the [[Big 12 Conference]], channel 5 serves as the primary over-the-air rightsholder to college football games involving the [[Oklahoma Sooners football|University of Oklahoma Sooners]] and the [[Oklahoma State Cowboys football|Oklahoma State Cowboys]]. The station's sports department also produces local [[pre-game show|pre-game]] and [[post-game show]]s that air around ABC-televised Sooners and Cowboys games, as well as a regular season preview show covering both teams that airs each August. (Over-the-air regular season Sooners and Cowboys games not shown on KOCO air instead on KOKH-TV by way of [[Fox College Football|Fox]]'s partial broadcast television rights to the Big 12.) In September 1982, after the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit|Tenth Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals]] issued a stay of a district court order that ruled network and cable contracts for college football telecasts reached by the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) to be in violation of antitrust rules, the University of Oklahoma sold KOCO-TV the local television rights to a game between the Sooners and the [[USC Trojans football|USC Trojans]] under arrangement with the Katz Agency sports management firm. The court's delay in acting on the case and time constraints thereof led to the university abandoning its effort to telecast the game on KOCO.<ref>{{cite web|title=The old college try|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/82-OCR/1982-09-27-BC-OCR-Page-0032.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|page=31|date=September 27, 1982|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=The old college try|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/82-OCR/1982-09-27-BC-OCR-Page-0033.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|page=32|date=September 27, 1982|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter NCAA regulations restricting the number of college football games that could be televised live in a single season were [[NCAA v. Board of Regents of the University of Oklahoma|overturned by the U.S. Supreme Court]] in 1984, KOCO acquired the local rights to a Katz Sports-syndicated package of college football games involving [[Big Eight Conference]] teams. (Katz subsequently sold the rights to the college football games and certain other sports events to [[Raycom Sports]] after the 1985 NCAA Division I college football season.) From 1988 to 1991 and again from 1993 to 1995, KOCO also maintained a programming agreement with the Sooners to air various team-related programs during the regular season, including the head coach's weekly analysis program ''Oklahoma Football'', which was co-hosted by then-[[sports director]] [[Dean Blevins]] and Sooners football coach [[Gary Gibbs]]. (Fox affiliate KOKH held the local rights to the Sooners magazine programs for the 1992 season, with KOCO carrying select Oklahoma State Cowboys programs such as analysis program ''The [[Pat Jones (American football)|Pat Jones]] Show'' in the interim.)<ref name=\"oklahoman-koconewsteam\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Tuning In...|url=http://newsok.com/article/2280122|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=September 17, 1989|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Blevins Due on ABC Broadcasts|url=http://newsok.com/article/2440340|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=August 29, 1993|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=High School Football Hits the Air|url=http://newsok.com/article/2405285|author=Dale Saviers|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=September 4, 1992|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1992 to 1994, KOCO carried select basketball games involving the city's now-defunct [[Continental Basketball Association]] (CBA) franchise, the [[Lawton-Fort Sill Cavalry|Oklahoma City Cavalry]], with Blevins also providing color commentary for the telecasts. Since the team's [[Seattle SuperSonics relocation to Oklahoma City|relocation from Seattle]] in [[2008\u201309 NBA season|2008]], under [[NBA on ABC|ABC's share of sister network ESPN's television contract]] with the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA), channel 5 has also carried certain ABC-televised regular season and [[NBA playoffs|playoff]] games featuring the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]]. Notably, in [[2012 NBA Finals|2012]], the station aired the Thunder's first [[NBA Finals]] appearance as an Oklahoma City-based franchise (their fourth overall, counting the pre-relocation [[Seattle SuperSonics]]' previous appearances in [[1978 NBA Finals|1978]], [[1979 NBA Finals|1979]] and [[1996 NBA Finals|1996]]), which saw the [[Miami Heat]] defeat the Thunder to win the championship title four games to one.\n\n==News operation==\n{{As of|September 2017}}, KOCO-TV broadcasts 34 hours of locally produced newscasts each week (with five hours each weekday and 4\u00bd hours each on Saturdays and Sundays); the station also produces an additional 3\u00bd hours of newscasts each week (consisting of a half-hour each on weekdays, Saturdays and Sundays) for its MeTV-affiliated DT2 subchannel. During the fall months, channel 5 regularly preempts its early evening newscasts on Saturdays\u2014the 5:00&nbsp;p.m. edition since August 2009, and the 6:00&nbsp;p.m. edition, which had previously been subject to frequent overrun-related programming delays, since ABC bridged its football coverage upon shifting its [[Saturday Night Football]] telecasts a half-hour earlier in August 2019\u2014to accommodate ABC's college football game coverage. Through a content agreement with [[Community Newspaper Holdings]], KOCO also contributes news content featured in two of the group's Oklahoma newspaper properties, ''[[The Norman Transcript]]'' and the ''Enid News & Eagle''.\n\n===News department history===\nChannel 5's news department began operations when the station signed on as Enid-based KGEO-TV on July 2, 1954, initially consisting of a half-hour, weekday-only 12:30&nbsp;p.m. newscast. By the time the station moved to Oklahoma City in 1958, the re-called KOCO was running a five-minute newscast at 6:25&nbsp;p.m. and a half-hour newscast at 10:00&nbsp;p.m. each weeknight (later evolving into half-hour newscasts at 5:30&nbsp;p.m. weeknights and at 10:00&nbsp;p.m. seven nights a week by 1964). Ernie Schultz (who would later serve as a [[news director]] for WKY-TV and KWTV) served as the original main anchor of the Monday through Friday editions. As part of the condition of the station's license transfer to Oklahoma City that required it to maintain an auxiliary studio in its original city of license, KOCO maintained a news bureau at its original Randolph Street facility in Enid; the bureau would eventually be closed by station management in 1995. From September 1965 until September 1970, the station produced a Sunday evening news and features program, ''Sundayscope'', which also featured a regular viewer mail segment hosted by general manager Ben K. West.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oklahoma City television pioneer Ben K. West dies|url=http://newsok.com/article/3502760|author=Mel Bracht|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=October 9, 2010|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> The weeknight newscasts were reformatted in 1968 as ''The Hickox-Halburnt Report'', anchored by news director Richard Hickox and assistant news director Joe Halburnt Jr.; they were replaced by Dean Swanson in 1971, at which point, the newscasts were retitled ''The News on 5''. In 1974, as the ''[[Eyewitness News]]'' format was growing in popularity in television markets throughout the nation, KOCO-TV renamed its newscasts to ''Channel 5 Eyewitness News''. (It was the second station in the Oklahoma City market to have utilized the format, following a previous run at KWTV between 1966 and 1971; the format was later re-used by KOCO, as ''Eyewitness News 5'', from July 1998 to April 2013). By this time, Swanson and chief meteorologist Fred Norman were joined weeknights by sports director Jerry Park, who would become the station's longest-serving on-air personality, working there for 25 years.<ref name=\"oklahoma-parkretires\">{{cite news|title=KOCO's Park Ends Career Longtime Sportscaster to Retire|url=http://newsok.com/article/2654104|author=Mel Bracht|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=May 20, 1999|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nUnder the helm of news director Tom Kirby (who was later promoted to president and general manager of KOCO, remaining in that role until his resignation to pursue consulting work in 1993), the station made aggressive moves to improve its standing among the market's television news operations by highlighting investigative reporting and extensive coverage of breaking news events\u2014among which, included live and filmed coverage of a July 1973 riot at the [[Oklahoma State Penitentiary]] in [[McAlester, Oklahoma|McAlester]], which was compiled into a one-hour documentary that received a commendation by the [[National Council on Crime and Delinquency]]. The station also acquired a private airplane to transport reporters and camera crews to news stories and pick up edited film reels.<ref>{{cite web|title=An airplane, remote crew added KOCO-TV's new news|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/74-OCR/1974-08-19-BC-OCR-Page-0074.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=74|date=August 19, 1974|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> In 1973, Ben Tipton\u2014a former radio host at KBYE (890 AM, now [[KTLR]])\u2014joined KOCO as the station's first African American on-air personality and the first black news anchor in the Oklahoma City market. Tipton served as a weekend evening anchor and political reporter and also created and hosted ''The Black Review'', a weekly public affairs program focusing on community events and topical discussions focusing on Oklahoma's African-American community that aired on channel 5 under various titles (later as ''Saturday Review'' [alternately titled ''Sunday Review'' whenever ABC Sports telecasts bumped the program from its Saturday midday timeslot] from September 1979 to March 1989 and ''Oklahoma Collage'' thereafter until its cancellation) from January 1976 until November 1993. After Tipton left KOCO in 1977 to become the Ward 7 councilman on the Oklahoma City Council, representing the city's predominately African-American northeast section, Joyce Jackson-Combs\u2014who began at KOCO as a clerical assistant in 1970 and eventually rose the ranks to become an assignment reporter until her departure in 1989\u2014took over as host of the retitled ''Saturday Review'' (remaining in that role until the program was cancelled by KOCO station management) and became the station's public service director.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Council Member Ben Tipton Dies|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/2234427/former-council-member-ben-tipton-dies|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=August 3, 1988|accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A Historical Review of Blacks in Oklahoma Broadcasting|url=https://shareok.org/bitstream/handle/11244/16572/Thesis-1982-L644h.pdf|author=Lester Valentino Lesure|publisher=[[Oklahoma State University|Oklahoma State University Press]]|format=PDF|year=1982|accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter being acquired by Gannett, the company made substantial investments in KOCO's news operations\u2014among them, the acquisition of an [[Eurocopter AS350 \u00c9cureuil|Aerospatiale Astar 350]] (branded as \"Sky 5\"), which was the first helicopter to be used for aerial newsgathering in the Oklahoma City market upon its introduction in February 1978. The format changes during the 1970s ultimately did not reward the station's newscasts with a ratings win, as KOCO remained at a distant third place in the ratings for many years against the then-long-dominant channel 4 and the perennially second-place KWTV. In 1977, KOCO began airing \"Wednesday's Child\", a weekly feature segment on its 10:00&nbsp;p.m. newscast that was presented by Jack Bowen (who served as an anchor/reporter at the station from 1974 to 1987 and again from 1990 to 1995<ref name=\"oklahoman-koconewsteam\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Bowen to Return to KOCO-TV|url=http://newsok.com/bowen-to-return-to-koco-tv/article/2323797|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=July 13, 1990|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>), which profiled children in need of an adoptive family. In June 1979, while on assignment at a [[American Electric Power|Public Service Company of Oklahoma]] (PSO) [[press conference]], KOCO anchor/reporter Ron Stahl and photographer Bill Collard were arrested on a [[trespassing]] complaint after crossing a utility fence to cover a protest against the construction of a nuclear power plant in [[Inola, Oklahoma|Inola]]. Stahl (who contended that he and Collard would have been unable to return for the press conference in time had they chosen to hike more than {{convert|2|mi|km}} over rough terrain to reach a sanctioned area to view the demonstrators' arrests) and nine other reporters who were taken into custody\u2014including Tom Newcomb and Susie Welsh of KTVY, and Vicki Monks of KWTV\u2014were convicted and individually levied a $25 fine in January 1980. The convictions were appealed on [[Freedom of the press in the United States|press freedom]] infringement complaints, but were upheld by the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Oklahoma|U.S. Court of Appeals for the Western District of Oklahoma]]. The [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] declined to review the case upon consideration in January 1984, letting stand the convictions of Stahl and the other reporters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trespass convictions in Oklahoma set up precedential case|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/80-OCR/1980-01-21-BC-OCR-Page-0065.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=65|date=January 21, 1980|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Journalism wins one, loses one in Supreme Court|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/84-OCR/BC-1984-01-23-OCR-Page-0101.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=101|date=January 23, 1984|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> \n\nKOCO's ratings fortunes improved from 1980 to 1982, when its newscasts briefly overtook KWTV for second place following the installment of Jack Bowen and Mary Ruth Carleton as its primary anchor team, alongside Norman and Park. The station's newscasts\u2014then titled ''5 Alive NewsCenter'', eventually being shortened to ''5 Alive News'' in January 1984\u2014even battled longtime powerhouse KTVY for first in the market. On May 31, 1982, the station's early-evening newscast \u2013 which had been airing at 5:30&nbsp;p.m. (instead of the 6:00&nbsp;p.m. timeslot then used exclusively by most network stations, including some ABC affiliates) since September 1972, following ABC's initial 5:00&nbsp;p.m. Central Time feed of the ''ABC Evening News'' \u2013 was shifted to 5:00&nbsp;p.m., where it had previously aired from 1968 to 1972, and retitled ''Live at Five''. (Around this time, ABC had begun requiring affiliates located outside of the [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]] and [[Pacific Time Zone]]s to swap the airtimes of the successor ''[[ABC World News Tonight|World News Tonight]]'' and their local early evening newscasts \u2013 then also aired in that order on ABC's other Oklahoma-based affiliates, KTUL, KTEN and [[KSWO-TV]] in [[Lawton, Oklahoma|Lawton]] \u2013 to allow the former to compete directly with [[NBC Nightly News|NBC]] and [[CBS Evening News|CBS]]'s evening newscasts.) A separate half-hour newscast at 6:00&nbsp;p.m. (originally titled ''Newsplus at 6:00'') subsequently premiered on September 20 of that year. (All three broadcasts ranked the market's most-watched news programs in those time periods during the November 2006 [[Nielsen ratings#Sweeps|sweeps]] period.) In 1984, the station was sued for [[defamation]] by local [[obstetrics and gynaecology|OB-GYN]] William Crittendon, who claimed a report on a [[medical malpractice]] case he was being tried for had misquoted an expert witness who said that a patient had a \"perfectly healthy\" (rather than \"perfectly normal\") [[uterus]]; the [[Oklahoma Supreme Court]] ruled that station management must pay Crittendon $550,000 in damages; an appeal of the ruling, charging [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] violations, gained the support of the [[National Association of Broadcasters]], which contended that the court did not establish negligence or causation.<ref>{{cite web|title=NAB, NCTA lend support to First Amendment cases|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/84-OCR/BC-1984-03-12-OCR-Page-0059.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=59|date=March 12, 1984|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=NAB, NCTA lend support to First Amendment cases|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/84-OCR/BC-1984-03-12-OCR-Page-0060.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=60|date=March 12, 1984|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe station also collaborated with ABC News' ''[[20/20 (American TV program)|20/20]]'' on the 1981 undercover investigative report \"[[Throwaway Kids]]\". Reported locally by then-assignment reporter Pam Henry, the investigative series\u2014which went on to earn [[Peabody Award|Peabody]] and Emmy Awards\u2014looked into abuse, neglect and preventable deaths of children, elderly and [[mental illness|mentally ill]] persons in the care of the [[Oklahoma Department of Human Services]] (OKDHS) that would lead to the resignation of agency director [[Lloyd E. Rader Sr.|Lloyd Rader]]. By 1983, channel 5's newscasts had settled into a solid second place as a series of anchor changes helped propel KWTV from a distant third all the way to first place, displacing KTVY from the #1 ratings position it held for decades. On September 12, 1983, the 5:00&nbsp;p.m. newscast adopted the ''Newscope'' format, a customizable syndicated news concept for local stations that featured local perspectives on major national and international news stories as well as consumer and entertainment news; KOCO reformatted the 5:00 show as a traditional local newscast after ''Newscope'' was discontinued nationally in September 1984.<ref name=\"oklahoman-newscope\"/> A main weakness of KOCO has been the turnover rate of its on-air news department staff. Massive staffing changes took place during 1984 under newly appointed vice president of news operations Gary Long (a former general manager at ex-sister station [[KARK-TV]] in [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]]). Anchors Mary Ruth Carleton and Gan Matthews, farm reporter Gene Wheatley, assignment reporter Jennifer Eve, and sports anchor Tony Sellars (the latter four of which had joined KWTV by the end of 1984) left or had their contracts not be renewed, while longtime weeknight meteorologist Fred Norman was shifted to the weekend evening newscasts, where he would remain until his retirement in 1987. In addition, Gerry Harris (who joined channel 5 from [[WTNH]] in [[Hartford, Connecticut]]) and meteorologist Wayne Shattuck (who had been working as a primary weather anchor at [[KDFW]] in Dallas for four years, following a prior stint at KOCO from 1977 to 1980) were hired to join Bowen and Park on the weeknight newscasts.<ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO's news team changes|url=http://newsok.com/article/2088631|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=November 18, 1984|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Channel 5 fills co-anchor spot|url=http://newsok.com/article/2086403|author=Glen Phillips|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=October 28, 1984|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=TV news staff changes made|url=http://newsok.com/article/2087179|author=Glen Phillips|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=November 4, 1984|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn an effort to improve KOCO's newscast ratings, which had declined to a distant third place over the preceding years as a result of the changes, the station lured away several anchors from rival KTVY, including [[Jane Anne Jayroe|Jane Jayroe]] (who, at the start of her first tenure at KOCO from 1978 to 1980, became the station's first female news anchor) and Jerry Adams (who replaced Bowen after he left channel 5 to replace Roger Cooper as KWTV's main co-anchor), both of whom joined Harris (who had been moved to the noon and 5:00&nbsp;p.m. newscasts, and became a feature reporter for the nightly segment \"Oklahoma Pride\") as the station's primary evening anchors. Brothers [[Butch McCain|Butch]] and [[Ben McCain]] were also hired to anchor the noon newscast as well as a new hour-long weekday news and features program, ''Good Morning Oklahoma'', which debuted on August 3, 1987 and maintained a similar\u2014albeit slightly more news-driven\u2014format as their short-lived KTVY program ''AM Oklahoma''. (The McCains also hosted two [[music video]] programs for KOCO, ''Hot Country Hits'' from May 1992 to May 1994 and ''Chartbusters'' in 1993, as well as the local academic [[quiz show]] ''Challenge [Bowl]'' from September 1988 to September 1994.)<ref>{{cite news|title=TV Anchors Switch Channels|url=http://newsok.com/article/2190592|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=June 27, 1987|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=McCain brothers hosting \"Good Morning, Oklahoma'|url=http://newsok.com/article/2195045|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=August 9, 1987|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=TV Notebook|url=http://newsok.com/article/2252227|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=January 15, 1989|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=McCain Brothers Successful Team|url=http://newsok.com/article/2273588|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=July 23, 1989|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=McCain Brothers Mark 10th Year|url=http://newsok.com/article/2369738|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=September 22, 1991|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> The late 1980s also saw the station's newscasts shift toward a \"softer, entertainment-influenced approach\" that incorporated more [[infotainment]] and special interest segments alongside [[hard news]] content.<ref>{{cite news|title=Competition Drives City TV Newscasts to Play Ratings Game|url=http://newsok.com/article/2250134|author=David Zizzo|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=December 25, 1988|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> In 1988, Dean Blevins was hired as KOCO's sports director, resulting in Jerry Park being relegated to the weekend evening newscasts. (Park\u2014who retired from KOCO in May 1999\u2014was later shifted to the Saturday morning newscast upon its 1992 debut, with Myron Patton replacing him on weekend evenings).<ref name=\"oklahoma-parkretires\"/> On September 2, 1988, the station premiered ''Prep Sports Extra'', a Friday night program that covered [[high school football]] games from around the state during the fall season (which, depending on the year, aired anywhere from 15 to 30 minutes); the program's brief suspension for the fall of 1996\u2014attributed to longtime sports anchor and co-host [[Mick Cornett]]'s promotion to weekday morning news anchor that year\u2014led to such viewer outcry that the station reinstated ''Prep Sports Extra'' (eventually renamed ''High School Playbook'' in September 2012) midway through that year's academic football season.<ref name=\"oklahoman-koconewsteam\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=\"Prep Sports Extra\" Returns|url=http://newsok.com/article/2553766|author=Mel Bracht|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=October 24, 1996|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 14, 1990, KOCO-TV implemented the \"24-Hour News Source\" concept, producing 30-second-long news updates during commercial breaks outside of long-form newscasts near the top of each hour throughout the day as well as weather updates on weekend mornings. It also provided a weekdaily overnight news feed consisting of a simulcast of [[All News Channel]]'s overnight programming and additional content sourced from its then-sister stations WXIA in Atlanta and fellow ABC affiliate [[KUSA-TV]] (now an NBC affiliate) in [[Denver]]. Later that month, KOCO filed a trademark lawsuit against KFOR and its owner at the time, [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]]-based Palmer Communications, seeking $208,000 in damages and an injunction to stop KFOR from promoting itself as the \"24-Hour News <u>and Information Station</u>.\" KOCO representatives claimed that it had been the exclusive owner of the \"24-Hour News Source\" moniker in Oklahoma City since 1980, and KFOR's three-day jump in adopting the format and slogan upon its switch to a 24-hour schedule caused viewer confusion that denied KOCO immediate recognition with its rollout. Oklahoma County District Court Judge Bana Blasdel denied the station's request for an emergency temporary restraining order to prevent KFOR, which contended it was using a slogan that could not be trademarked, from using the term on May 25.<ref name=\"oklahoman-24hourtv\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=FINE TUNING|url=http://newsok.com/article/2342213|author=Tim Chavez|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=December 23, 1990|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO-TV Files Suit Against KFOR-TV In Trademark Case|url=http://newsok.com/article/2318399|author=Tim Chavez|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=May 23, 1990|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Temporary Injunction Denied|url=http://newsok.com/article/2319114|author=Tim Chavez|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=May 30, 1990|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=TV Profits Focus on Newscasts Local Market Revenues Fall|url=http://newsok.com/article/2322567|author=Tim Chavez|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=July 1, 1990|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> The parties would later settle the suit, with KOCO continuing to air round-the-clock news updates until December 27, 1991, when it discontinued the All News Channel block to reinstate an overnight sign-off period. KFOR also continued to use the \"24-Hour News Source\" concept until 1999, but changed its slogan in November 1990 to reference its use of the format obliquely. (KOCO utilized a retooled version of the concept from 1998 to 1999, providing top-of-the-hour weather updates from the newly branded \"24-Hour First Alert Weather\" team.) Channel 5's implementation of the format won it a first place honor for innovation at the Best of Gannett Awards in 1990.<ref>{{cite news|title=City Station Wins Awards|url=http://newsok.com/article/2329919|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=September 2, 1990|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n1990 also saw KOCO become the first television station in the Oklahoma City market to offer [[closed captioning]] of its newscasts for deaf and hearing-impaired viewers. In addition, Tom McNamara (previously with [[KTVK]] in Phoenix, Arizona) joined Jayroe as co-anchor of KOCO's weeknight newscasts; Jerry Adams was reassigned to the weekend evening newscasts, co-anchoring alongside Jennifer Eve in a pairing that saw the weekend broadcasts being tongue-in-cheekly marketed as ''The [[Adam and Eve|Adams & Eve]] Report''. (Adams left the station in 1991, later to be replaced as Eve's weekend co-anchor by assignment reporter Jeff Mirasola.)<ref>{{cite news|title=McNamara Joins KOCO-TV (5) Staff|url=http://newsok.com/article/2306066|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=February 4, 1990|accessdate=October 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"oklahoman-koconewsteam\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=\"Just the Facts, Ma'am\"|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/2381509/just-the-facts-maam|author=Tim Chavez|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=January 12, 1992|accessdate=December 26, 2019}}</ref> On April 18, 1992, KOCO debuted a three-hour-long Saturday morning newscast\u2014the first local newscast in the Oklahoma City market to be offered on weekend mornings\u2014from 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to 12:00&nbsp;p.m., taking over part of the timeslot occupied by ABC's Saturday cartoon lineup. (The newscast\u2014by then, reduced to two hours\u2014would shift to 8:00&nbsp;a.m. on September 9, 1995, and then to 10:00&nbsp;a.m. on September 13, 1997.) Then on September 11, 1995, the noon newscast was expanded to one hour, replacing first-run syndicated shows that had been occupying the 12:30 half-hour locally since the ABC soap opera ''[[Ryan's Hope]]'' ended in December 1988. (The midday newscast would revert to a half-hour on September 7, 1998 to accommodate the ABC soap opera ''Port Charles''.) The weekday morning newscast was expanded into a 90-minute broadcast (starting at 5:30&nbsp;a.m.) on February 2, 1998; it would subsequently expand again to two hours (starting at 5:00) on February 1, 1999. During the early- and mid-1990s, KOCO maintained an investigative unit\u2014known as the \"I-Team\"\u2014led by investigative and assignment reporter Terri Watkins, who worked at channel 5 from 1982 until she retired from broadcasting in 2006. During her tenure at KOCO, Watkins was nominated for and won multiple awards for her various reports including two Peabody Awards, several [[Edward R. Murrow Award (Radio Television Digital News Association)|Edward R. Murrow Awards]], [[Houston International Festival|Houston International Film and Video Festival]], [[New York Film Festival|New York International Film Festival]], [[Associated Press]] and Oklahoma Association of Broadcasters awards, and six Emmy nominations (most notably, for her coverage of the [[Oklahoma City bombing|1995 Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building bombing]] and the trial and execution of bombing co-conspirator [[Timothy McVeigh]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Terri Watkins|url=https://emmyawards.tv/about/silver-circle-nomination-form/silver-circle-inductees/terri-watkins/|website=[[Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO Wins Four Gold Medals at Film Festival|url=http://newsok.com/article/2358159|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=May 26, 1991|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO-TV Honored With Broadcast Awards|url=http://newsok.com/article/2344919|newspaper=The Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=January 20, 1991|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Journalism hall to induct 10|url=http://newsok.com/article/1444291|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=March 13, 2005|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe 1990s saw continued changes to its anchor team that included the move of weekend anchor Jennifer Eve\u2014who rejoined KOCO in 1987, after a reporting stint from 1982 to 1984\u2014replacing the departing Jane Jayroe (in 1992) and Gerry Bonds ([[maiden name|n\u00e9e]] Harris, in 1993) on the weeknight newscasts, a position Eve remained in until she left television news in 2001;<ref>{{cite news|title=Anchorwoman to Leave Channel 5|url=http://newsok.com/article/2394781|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=May 16, 1992|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO-5 changes late news co-anchor|url=http://newsok.com/article/2722653|author=Mel Bracht|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=December 8, 2000|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Eve ready to leave KOCO-5|url=http://newsok.com/article/2743777|author=Mel Bracht|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=June 5, 2001|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Ben and Butch McCain being pulled from ''Good Morning Oklahoma'' in May 1994, after the station decided to switch its morning show to a conventional news format (the McCains would file a [[wrongful termination]] lawsuit against KOCO centering on their firing in September 1996);<ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO Takes McCain Brothers Off the Air|url=http://newsok.com/article/2465566|author=Steve Lackmeyer|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=May 8, 1994|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=No Contract Misrepresentation in McCains' Firing, Station Says|url=https://www.questia.com/newspaper/1P2-5696651/no-contract-misrepresentation-in-mccains-firing|author=Leigh Jones|newspaper=The Journal Record|publisher=The Journal Record Publishing Company|date=September 24, 1996|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> and Jack Bowen departing for Fox affiliate KOKH in November 1995 to become co-anchor of its then soon-to-launch 9:00&nbsp;p.m. newscast.<ref>{{cite news|title=Anchor Jack Bowen to Lead KOKH-TV's Nightly Newscast|url=http://newsok.com/article/2523031|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=December 10, 1995|accessdate=October 2, 2018}}</ref> In September 1991, KOCO premiered ''Hollywood Spotlight'', a movie review and interview program hosted by entertainment reporter Dino Lalli (who joined the station in 1988, after a four-year stint at [[KNBC]] in Los Angeles, and had worked at KTVY beforehand); the program\u2014which usually aired Saturdays, in either an afternoon or early evening slot\u2014ended in August 1997, following Lalli's departure from channel 5.\n\nIn 1998, KOCO rebranded its newscasts to ''Eyewitness News 5'', which remained until April 2013.\n\nIn 1999, then-weekend evening anchor/reporter Cherokee Ballard\u2014who worked at the station from 1989 to 2005, and was the first person of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] descent to anchor a local newscast in the Oklahoma City market\u2014became the focus of a series of reports chronicling her battle with [[non-Hodgkin's lymphoma|non-Hodgkin's large-cell lymphoma]] (for which she had been diagnosed with that June) to educate viewers about the disease. (Ballard's cancer went into remission the following year.)<ref>{{cite news|title=NEWS ANCHOR SHARES PRIVATE BATTLE; Newscaster: Cancer fight educates viewers|url=http://newsok.com/article/2669189|author=Mel Bracht|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=September 28, 1999|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Anchor looks forward to life after KOCO-5|url=http://newsok.com/article/2856739|author=Mel Bracht|newspaper=The Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=June 25, 2004|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> KOCO has increased its commitment to news and weather coverage in recent years, with these efforts helping propel the station's 5:00&nbsp;p.m. newscast to first place in the ratings in 2004, followed by its first-ever outright win at 6:00&nbsp;p.m. in November 2006. In February 2006, the station extended its weekend morning news programming to Sundays, with the addition of a two-hour 7:00&nbsp;a.m. newscast. That same year, the Sunday edition of the 10:00&nbsp;p.m. newscast expanded to a full hour, resulting in ''Sunday Sports Xtra''\u2014a sports wrap-up program that debuted on September 4, 1994 as ''Sports Final'', and was relaunched after a seven-month hiatus as ''Sports Extra'' in August 1997<ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO Shuffles Sports Department|url=http://newsok.com/article/2472438|author=Dale Saviers|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=July 22, 1994|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO Show Back As \"Sports Extra\"|url=http://newsok.com/article/2587310|author=Mel Bracht|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=July 31, 1997|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\u2014converting from a standalone program to a 15-minute tail-end segment within the newscast (the ''Sports Extra'' moniker was used as the umbrella title for its sports segments from 2006 to February 2012).\n\nAfter more than two decades of turnover with its evening anchor team, the station eventually gained stability with its primary anchor team when it paired Jessica Schambach (the longest-serving member of channel 5's current on-air news staff, who joined the station in 2002 as a reporter, and was promoted to the evening newscasts in 2005 as 5:00&nbsp;p.m. co-anchor<ref>{{cite news|title=TV NEWS|url=http://newsok.com/article/2916237|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=October 19, 2005|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>) and Paul Folger (who joined the station from WTEV [now [[WJAX-TV]]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]]) on the weeknight newscasts in 2008. The two were later joined in August 2017 by Abigail Ogle (daughter of KFOR evening anchor [[Kevin Ogle]], and who joined KOCO as a sports reporter in 2012) as co-anchor of the 6:00&nbsp;p.m. newscast. Folger left KOCO in July 2018 to become lead anchor at fellow ABC affiliate [[KSTP-TV]] in [[Minneapolis]]\u2013[[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Oklahoma TV man moving to Minnesota to anchor KSTP-TV news|url=https://bringmethenews.com/minnesota-lifestyle/oklahoma-tv-man-moving-to-minnesota-to-anchor-kstp-tv-news|website=Bring Me The News|date=July 9, 2018|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}</ref> Ogle temporarily served as Schambach's weeknight co-anchor on a full-time basis until March 2019, when Evan Onstot (formerly an evening anchor at [[KSEE]] in [[Fresno, California|Fresno]]) was added as co-anchor, relegating Ogle to 6:00&nbsp;p.m. anchor and 5:00 and 10:00&nbsp;p.m. field reporter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Evan Onstot named weekday evening anchor for KOCO 5 News|url=https://www.koco.com/article/evan-onstot-named-weekday-evening-anchor-for-koco-5-news/26578261|website=KOCO-TV|publisher=Hearst Television|date=February 28, 2019|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=After close to five years in Fresno, Evan Onstot is leaving KSEE 24. Here's his next stop|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article226947474.html|author=Joshua Tehee|newspaper=[[Fresno Bee]]|publisher=[[The McClatchy Company]]|date=February 28, 2019|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> The week of January 2, 2008 saw further changes to its news schedule: the noon newscast was cancelled, the 5:00&nbsp;p.m. newscast was expanded to Saturday evenings, and the Saturday and Sunday morning newscasts were moved to an earlier, uniform timeslot from 5:00 to 7:00&nbsp;a.m. (In lieu of a midday newscast, a 30-second weather update airs before ABC Daytime programming in that timeslot; the Saturday 5:00&nbsp;p.m. newscast is preempted during the fall to accommodate ABC's college football coverage.) In October 2009, KOCO upgraded its severe weather, school closings and news tickers to be overlaid on high definition programming without having to downconvert HD content to [[standard-definition television|standard definition]]. An hour-long extension of the station's weekend morning newscasts debuted on July 31, 2010, airing from 8:00 to 9:00&nbsp;a.m. (The expansion coincided with ABC turning over one hour of its ABC Kids Saturday morning block, which would be replaced by Litton's Weekend Aventure that September, to its owned-and-operated and affiliated stations.)<ref>{{cite web|title=KOCO 5 Expands Weekend Morning News|url=http://www.koco.com/article/koco-5-expands-weekend-morning-news/4281821|website=KOCO-TV|publisher=Hearst Television|date=July 30, 2010|accessdate=October 19, 2017}}</ref> This was followed on September 22, with the expansion of the weekday morning newscast to 4:30&nbsp;a.m., becoming the first television station in Oklahoma to expand its morning newscasts to a pre-5:00&nbsp;a.m. timeslot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koco.com/video/25106303/detail.html|website=KOCO-TV|publisher=Hearst Television|accessdate=October 19, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305202123/http://www.koco.com/video/25106303/detail.html|archivedate=March 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn April 18, 2013, KOCO became the third commercial station in Oklahoma City to begin broadcasting its local newscasts in high definition. (Prior to the move, KOCO utilized a [[pillarboxing|pillarboxed]] presentation for its newscasts from October 5, 2009 to October 11, 2010; the station transmitted in-studio segments in and upconverted field news video to the 16:9 widescreen format thereafter.) With the conversion to HD, KOCO implemented a standardized graphics package (designed by the Hearst graphics hub at [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] sister station [[WESH]]) and music package (\"Strive\" by inthegroovemusic) unveiled in November 2012 on Baltimore sister station WBAL-TV. On April 8, 2016, KOCO launched an hour-long, weekday newscast at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. (which, though not technically an extension of its 4:30\u20137:00&nbsp;a.m. newscast, uses that broadcast's on-air staff), and a nightly, half-hour 9:00&nbsp;p.m. newscast for KOCO-DT2 (which directly competes against a nightly hour-long newscast on KOKH-TV\u2014which debuted in May 1996 as Oklahoma City's first local prime time newscast, and is subject to overrun-caused delays by prime time [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]] game telecasts\u2014and a KFOR-produced half-hour newscast on KAUT-TV, which has aired only on weeknights since its June 2006 launch). (The latter program was part of an effort by Hearst around this timeframe to launch prime time newscasts on the MeTV subchannels of its non-duopoly stations.)<ref>{{cite web|title=KOCO Launching 9 A.M. And 9 P.M. Newscasts|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/93466/koco-launching-9-am-and-9-pm-newcasts|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media|date=March 28, 2016|accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO-5 to expand morning news by one hour with 9 a.m. newscast|url=http://newsok.com/article/5488788|newspaper=The Oklahoman|publisher=The Anschutz Corporation|date=March 31, 2016|accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> On April 4, 2016, beginning with a special into the investigation and arrest of convicted former Oklahoma City police officer [[Daniel Holtzclaw]] (who was convicted in December 2015 of multiple counts\u2014including rape, sexual battery and forcible oral sodomy\u2014committed against eight African American women in traffic stops he conducted in the majority-Black northeast Oklahoma City), the station premiered ''KOCO 5 Chronicle'', a recurring series of hour-long prime time specials focusing on state and community issues. (The program is titled after ''[[Chronicle (American TV program)|Chronicle]]'', a half-hour weeknightly newsmagazine that debuted on Boston sister station WCVB-TV in January 1982, which has also loaned its title for use by other Hearst stations for daily or recurring newsmagazine programs that debuted during the second half of the 2010s.)\n\n===Weather coverage===\nAlthough not as well known as its two principal competitors in this arena, KOCO-TV has made continual efforts over the years to improve its coverage of severe weather affecting Oklahoma. The station's Doppler weather radar system, branded on-air as \"KOCO 5 First Alert Dual-Pol Doppler\", utilizes data from a radar site at the station's Britton Road studios as well as live [[Volumetric Imaging and Processing of Integrated Radar|VIPIR]] data from radars operated by regional [[National Weather Service]] forecast offices. KOCO's ''First Alert Weather'' meteorologists provide local weather updates and, in the event of significant severe weather situations (such as a [[tornado warning]]) affecting Central Oklahoma, audio simulcasts of long-form severe weather coverage for [[University of Oklahoma]]-owned [[NPR]] member station [[KGOU]] (106.3 FM) and Champlin Broadcasting-owned country radio station [[KNAH]] (99.7 FM). In addition, through a content agreement with Community Newspaper Holdings, KOCO also provides forecast data for the weather page inserts in the ''Enid News & Eagle'' and ''The Norman Transcript''. (Both newspapers erroneously continue to use the station's 1998\u20132013 news logo under the ''Eyewitness News 5'' brand in their forecast pages.)\n\nWhen Fred Norman was hired as the station's chief meteorologist in 1972, he became known among viewers for his quirky colloquialisms and lively on-air delivery, but also sought to improve channel 5's weather coverage. During the mid-to-late 1970s, the station offered \"Weather Watch\", a nightly post-sign-off feature consisting mainly of live imagery of the station's weather radar, along with any cut-ins from the station's meteorologists in the event that the National Weather Service issued severe weather alerts for the KOCO viewing area during the overnight sign-off period. Following the 1989 promotion of [[Mike Morgan (meteorologist)|Mike Morgan]] to chief meteorologist, following the departure of Wayne Shattuck (who was also succeeded in that capacity by Morgan at KFOR in 1993),<ref>{{cite news|title=Changes Announced|url=http://newsok.com/article/2298132|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=December 10, 1989|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> KOCO's weather department invested the development of new technology to relay warnings and footage of inclement weather from the field. In July 1990, \"5 Alive WeatherTrack\" (later known as \"WeatherPhone 5\" until it was discontinued in 2004), a toll phone service providing local and worldwide weather information, was launched.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tuning In...|url=http://newsok.com/article/2320343|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=July 1, 1990|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, the station developed First Alert, the first automated weather warning system for television use (which was based on the manual-input [[First Warning]] system developed by KWTV around that time); it also assembled crews of storm chasing units, the \"First Alert Storm Teams\" (or \"F.A.S.T. units\"), which utilized custom vehicles equipped with video cameras and pioneering technology that enabled still photographs to be transmitted over cellular telephone using a dash-mounted computer combined with [[Data compression|photo compression]] codecs. Developed in conjunction with station engineers, chief photographer Chris Lee (who joined KOCO in 1977) and [[Cellular One]], \"First Pix\" was unveiled on April 9, 1992 to transmit photographs of a tornado. (\"First Pix\" as well as \"First Alert\" would earn the station a Regional News [[Emmy Award]] in 1991.) Morgan\u2014who was later sued for [[breach of contract]] and accusations of taking storm-related videotapes, computer programs and forecasting equipment without the station's permission\u2014left KOCO to become chief meteorologist at KFOR-TV in August 1992, and was later briefly replaced by former [[The Weather Channel|Weather Channel]] severe weather expert Vince Miller.<ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO-TV Sues Ex-weatherman|url=http://newsok.com/article/2408142|author=Judy Kuhlman|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=October 2, 1992|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Weather Expert Returns to State As KOCO's Chief Meteorologist|url=http://newsok.com/article/2416692|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=December 27, 1992|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> During Miller's brief tenure, in April 1993, the station became the first in the United States to disseminate live storm footage utilizing [[Night vision#Night vision technologies|night vision technology]]. (This concept was later revived in 2015 as a feature of the \"First Alert Storm Command,\" a mobile storm tracking unit that contains a roof-mounted 360\u00b0 camera and a large monitor that is occasionally used to provide real-time radar data from the field.)\n\nAfter Rick Mitchell took over as chief meteorologist in 1994, it would become the first station to utilize a mobile Doppler radar system, to send video over cellular telephone (earning the station a Regional Emmy nomination) and to distribute full-screen video over cell phones. KOCO's coverage of an [[1999 Bridge Creek\u2013Moore tornado|F5 tornado]] that killed 36 people in several of Oklahoma City's southern suburbs on May 3, 1999 earned the station a special recognition award from [[Governor of Oklahoma|Governor]] [[Frank Keating]]. Mitchell remained with KOCO until July 2012, when he became an evening meteorologist at [[KXAS-TV]] in Dallas\u2013Fort Worth.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rick Mitchell leaving KOCO after 18 years|url=http://www.koco.com/article/rick-mitchell-leaving-koco-after-18-years/3775043|website=KOCO-TV|publisher=Hearst Television|date=July 20, 2012|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Meteorologist Rick Mitchell Set to Join KXAS|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvspy/meteorologist-rick-mitchell-set-to-join-kxas/55669|author=Merrill Knox|website=[[AdWeek|TVSpy]]|publisher=[[Mecklermedia|Mediabistro Holdings]]|date=July 17, 2012|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=KXAS Hires Meteorologist Rick Mitchell|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/60807/kxas-hires-meteorologist-rick-mitchell|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media|date=July 16, 2012|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> In March 2000, the station unveiled the \"Neighborhood Network,\" a network of sensors that relayed real-time weather observations from sites throughout central Oklahoma, and \"Predictor,\" which compiles computer model data to display hour-by-hour forecasts up to 48 hours in advance.<ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO-5 settles with former reporter|url=http://newsok.com/article/2692273|author=Mel Bracht|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=April 3, 2000|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> In October 2012, Mitchell was succeeded by Damon Lane (who had been with the station since 2009 as a weekday morning meteorologist), who just eight months later on May 20, 2013, covered an [[2013 Moore tornado|EF5 tornado]] that killed 24 people in [[Moore, Oklahoma|Moore]], narrowly missing the home he lived in with wife Melissa Newton (formerly a reporter at KOCO from 2004 to 2006). The station's coverage of that tornado earned KOCO a Regional Emmy nomination, and chronicled in part by Lane in a 2016 episode of the ABC docu-series ''[[20/20: In an Instant|In an Instant]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Damon Lane named KOCO chief meteorologist|url=http://www.koco.com/article/damon-lane-named-koco-chief-meteorologist/4290476|website=KOCO-TV|publisher=Hearst Television|date=October 18, 2012|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Damon Lane Named Chief Meteorologist at KOCO|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvspy/damon-lane-named-chief-meteorologist-at-koco/67257|author=Merrill Knox|website=TVSpy|publisher=Mediabistro Holdings|date=October 19, 2012|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=ABC's 'In an Instant' looks at 2013 Moore tornado|url=http://newsok.com/article/5504318|newspaper=The Oklahoman|publisher=The Anschutz Corporation|date=June 17, 2016|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===On-air staff===\n====Notable former on-air staff====\n* [[Ed Birchall]] (a.k.a. \"Ho Ho the Clown\") \u2013 children's television personality (1959\u20131988; deceased)\n* [[Dean Blevins]] \u2013 sports director (1988\u20131994; now at KWTV in same position)\n* [[Mick Cornett]] \u2013 sports anchor/morning news anchor/reporter (1981\u20131999; later [[Mayor of Oklahoma City]] from 2004 to 2018 and Oklahoma Republican gubernatorial candidate in 2018)\n* [[Bill Geddie]] \u2013 news photographer (1978\u20131991; later co-creator/executive producer of ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'')\n* [[Jane Jayroe]] \u2013 anchor/reporter (1977\u20131980 and 1987\u20131992; former [[Miss America]] 1967)\n* [[Ben McCain]] \u2013 weekday morning anchor (1987\u20131994; now actor and producer/host/reporter at [[Spectrum (cable service)|Spectrum]] in Los Angeles)\n* [[Butch McCain]] \u2013 weekday morning meteorologist (1987\u20131994; now actor/weather anchor at [[KKCO]] in [[Grand Junction, Colorado]])\n* [[Rick Mitchell (meteorologist)|Rick Mitchell]] \u2013 chief meteorologist (1994\u20132012; now at [[KXAS-TV]] in [[Dallas]]\u2013[[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]])\n* [[Mike Morgan (meteorologist)|Mike Morgan]] \u2013 chief meteorologist (1989\u20131992; now at KFOR-TV in same position)\n* [[Chad Myers]] \u2013 weekend evening meteorologist (1990\u20131992; now at [[CNN]])\n* [[Milissa Rehberger]] \u2013 weekday morning and noon anchor/reporter (1996\u20132002; now at [[MSNBC]])\n* [[Cameron Sanders]] (aka Ron Sanders) \u2013 reporter (1982\u20131983; later correspondent for CNN and host of [[American Public Media]]'s ''Marketplace'')\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.koco.com/ koco.com] - KOCO-TV official website\n* [http://www.metv.com/ metvoklahomacity.com] - KOCO-DT2 (\"MeTV Oklahoma City\") official website\n* {{TVQ|KOCO-TV}}\n* {{TVQ|K18HX-D}}\n* {{TVQ|K21IT-D}}\n* {{TVQ|K22MA-D}}\n* {{TVQ|K24MD-D}}\n* {{TVQ|K25PG-D}}\n* {{BIA|KOCO|TV|TV}}\n\n{{Oklahoma City TV}}\n{{Oklahoma TV}}\n{{Hearst-Argyle}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koco-Tv}}\n[[Category:Television stations in Oklahoma City|OCO-TV]]\n[[Category:ABC network affiliates]]\n[[Category:MeTV affiliates]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1954]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award winners]]\n[[Category:Hearst Television]]\n[[Category:1954 establishments in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Former Gannett subsidiaries]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|ABC affiliate in Oklahoma City}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = KOCO-TV\n| city                     = \n| station_logo             = [[File:KOCO-TV_Logo.png|center|240px|center]]\n----\n[[File:Me-TV KOCO-DT2.png|center|150px|center]]\n| station_branding         = {{ubl|KOCO 5 (general; call letters are pronounced individually)|''KOCO 5 News'' (newscasts)|MeTV Oklahoma City (DT2)}}\n| station_slogan           = {{ubl|''Live. Local. Latebreaking.'' (primary)|''We'll Bring You the First Alert'' (weather)}}\n| digital                  = 7 ([[Very high frequency|VHF]])\n| virtual                  = 5 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| other_chs                = [[#Repeater stations|See below]]\n| affiliations             = {{ubl|'''5.1:''' [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (since 1954)|'''5.2:''' [[MeTV]] (since 2012)}}\n| owner                    = [[Hearst Television]]\n| licensee                 = Ohio/Oklahoma Hearst Television Inc.\n| location                 = [[Oklahoma City|Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]]\n| country                  = United States\n| airdate                  = {{ubl|{{Start date and age|1954|7|2|p=y}}<ref>KOCO states July 15 as its sign-on date, while the [[Oklahoma Historical Society]] [http://digital.library.okstate.edu/encyclopedia/entries/t/te005.html states it] as July 18.</ref>|(in [[Enid, Oklahoma]]; license moved to Oklahoma City in 1963)}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = '''O'''klahoma '''C'''ity, '''O'''klahoma\n| sister_stations          = \n| former_callsigns         = KGEO-TV (1954\u20131958)\n| former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br>5 (VHF, 1954\u20132009)\n| former_affiliations      = {{ubl|'''Secondary:'''|[[NTA Film Network|NTA Film]] (1956\u20131961)|'''DT2:'''|[[The Local AccuWeather Channel|Local AccuWX]] (2008\u20132011)|[[This TV]] (2011\u20132012)}}\n| effective_radiated_power = 65.7 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|451|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| facility_id              = 12508\n| coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|35|33|45.0|N|97|29|24.0|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=inline, title}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{URL|https://www.koco.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''KOCO-TV''', [[virtual channel]] 5 ([[Very high frequency|VHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 7), is an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]-[[network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Oklahoma City|Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]], United States. The station is owned by the [[Hearst Television]] subsidiary of [[Hearst Communications]]. KOCO-TV's studios and transmitter are located on East Britton Road ([[U.S. Route 66 in Oklahoma|Historic Route 66]])\u2014between North Kelley and North Eastern Avenues\u2014in the McCourry Heights neighborhood of northeast Oklahoma City, within {{convert|2|mi|km|spell=in}} of the facilities of competing [[duopoly (broadcasting)|station duopolies]] ([[NBC]] affiliate [[KFOR-TV]] [channel 4] and [[Independent station (North America)|independent station]] [[KAUT-TV]] [channel 43] to its immediate west, [[CBS]] affiliate [[KWTV-DT]] [channel 9] and [[MyNetworkTV]] affiliate [[KSBI]] [channel 52] to its southwest, and [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate [[KOKH-TV]] [channel 25] and [[The CW|CW]] affiliate [[KOCB]] [channel 34] to its southeast).\n\nOn [[cable television|cable]], KOCO is available on [[Cox Communications]] channel 8 ([[standard-definition television|standard definition]]) and [[digital cable|digital]] channel 705 ([[high-definition television|high definition]]) and [[AT&T U-verse]] channels 5 (standard definition) and 1005 (high definition) in the [[Oklahoma City metropolitan area]], and on channel 5 on most cable systems elsewhere within the Oklahoma City [[media market|DMA]] as well as on [[satellite television|satellite]] providers [[DirecTV]] and [[Dish Network]] throughout the market.\n\n==History==\n===Early history in Enid===\nThe [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) originally assigned the VHF channel 5 allocation in the Oklahoma City [[media market|market]] to [[Enid, Oklahoma|Enid]]. The initial application to broadcast over the frequency was filed in July 1952\u2014shortly after the FCC had lifted a [[Federal Communications Commission#Freeze of 1948|four-year moratorium on new television station license applications]]\u2014when the Enid Radiophone Company, a subsidiary of ''[[Enid News & Eagle]]'' parent Enid Publishing Company and owner of radio station [[KCRC (AM)|KCRC]] (1390 AM), applied with the FCC to obtain a [[Planning permission#Broadcasting|construction permit]] and [[broadcast license|license]] to operate a television station on VHF channel 5.<ref>{{cite web|title=Television Applications Filed at FCC|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/52-OCR/BC-1952-07-14-OCR-Page-0081.pdf|periodical=[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=[[PDF]]|page=81|date=July 14, 1952|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Enid businessman George Streets, owner of local electronics manufacturer Streets Electronics Inc., filed a separate license application for channel 5 in November of that year.<ref>{{cite web|title=TV Grants and Applications|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/52-OCR/BC-1952-11-17-OCR-Page-0101.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=101|date=November 17, 1952|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=FCC Readies Flexible Priority List on TV Hearing Speed-Up|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/53-OCR/BC-1953-08-24-OCR-Page-0046.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=46|date=December 28, 1953|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=New Grantees' Commencement Target Dates|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/53-OCR/BC-1953-12-28-OCR-Page-0097.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=97|date=December 28, 1953|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> When the FCC awarded the license and permit for channel 5 to Streets (who would serve as its original [[general manager]]), and his ownership group (which included local building contractor Philip R. Banta, who served as the station's president, and stockholder L.D. Banta, both of whom\u2014like Streets\u2014held similar 21.3% interests in the station) on February 11, 1954, he requested and received approval to assign '''KGEO-TV''' (for \"<u>G</u>reater <u>E</u>nid, <u>O</u>klahoma\") as the call letters for his television station. As consolation for losing the application grant to Streets Electronics, the Streets group gave Enid Radiophone an option to acquire a 20% stake in the station.<ref>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/54-OCR/1954-02-15-BC-OCR-Page-0104.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=104|date=February 15, 1954|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=St. Louis, Nashville & Enid, Okla.|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-TV-Digest-IDX/IDX/50s/Television-Digest-1954-07-OCR-Page-0018.pdf|periodical=Television Digest|publisher=Radio News Bureau|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=18|date=July 10, 1954|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe station began [[test pattern|test broadcasts]] on July 6, 1954; KGEO\u2014which originally intended to debut on June 15, three weeks before test telecasts commenced\u2014officially signed on the air nine days later on July 15.<ref>{{cite web|title=Six Plan TV Start Within Fortnight|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/54-OCR/1954-05-03-BC-OCR-Page-0084.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=84|date=May 3, 1954|accessdate=August 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=KWK-TV Begins; Six Others Ready|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/54-OCR/1954-07-12-BC-OCR-Page-0068.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=68|date=July 12, 1954|accessdate=August 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=KDRO-TV, KGEO-TV Begin Programming|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/54-OCR/1954-07-19-BC-OCR-Page-0056.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=56|date=July 19, 1954|accessdate=August 5, 2019}}</ref> Channel 5 was the fifth television station to sign on in the Oklahoma City market\u2014behind WKY-TV (channel 4, now [[KFOR-TV]]), which signed on the air on June 6, 1949; [[KTVQ (Oklahoma City)|KTVQ]] (channel 25, allocation now occupied by [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate [[KOKH-TV]]), which signed on October 28, 1953; KLPR-TV (channel 19, allocation now occupied by [[Cornerstone Television]] affiliate [[KUOT-CD]]), which signed on November 8, 1953; and [[KWTV-DT|KWTV]] (channel 9), which signed on December 20, 1953\u2014the seventh television station to sign on in the state of Oklahoma, the first within the Oklahoma City market's present designated boundaries to be [[city of license|licensed]] outside of Oklahoma City proper, and the only full-power VHF station to have operated in northern Oklahoma. The station originally maintained studio facilities located at East Randolph Avenue and North 2nd Street in northeastern Enid, adjacent to a Streets-owned appliance store; KGEO based its {{convert|816|ft|m|adj=on}} transmission tower adjacent to the property.<ref>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/54-OCR/1954-04-19-BC-OCR-Page-0109.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=109|date=April 19, 1954|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO-TV On the Road|url=http://www.enidnews.com/news/local_news/koco-tv-on-the-road/article_d32b52de-fc1e-55b1-a9cf-5103b40354d7.html|author=Robert Barron|newspaper=[[Enid News & Eagle]]|publisher=[[Community Newspaper Holdings]]|date=July 14, 2005|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nInitially broadcasting nine hours of programming per day from 2:30 to 11:30&nbsp;p.m., Channel 5 has operated as an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate since its debut,<ref>{{cite web|title=New Affiliates Raise ABC-TV Total to 196|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/54-OCR/1954-05-17-BC-OCR-Page-0117.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=113|date=May 17, 1954|accessdate=August 5, 2019}}</ref> In addition to carrying ABC programming, KGEO-TV also maintained a secondary affiliation with the [[NTA Film Network]] from October 15, 1956 until the programming service ceased operations in November 1961. The film [[anthology series]] ''NTA Film Spectacular'' was the service's only program to be cleared by KGEO/KOCO, as the majority of NTA's offerings were carried by either WKY-TV (which cleared several of NTA's drama, interview and variety series) or KWTV (which had carried most of the service's scripted programs). KGEO management charged that some provisions of [[National Telefilm Associates]] (NTA)'s contracts with NTA Film affiliates\u2014particularly, a compulsory 11-hour \"option\" for affiliates to carry network programming\u2014violated FCC rules for chain broadcasters; these accusations were rebutted in an FCC hearing on October 5, 1956, when NTA representatives claimed that the company did not abdicate license control over programs and that affiliation contracts, among other allowances, permitted stations to decline clearance of certain programs. Channel 5 became an exclusive ABC affiliate in November 1961, when National Telefilm Associates discontinued the NTA Film Network service.<ref name=\"Boxoffice7\">{{citation|title=Require Prime Evening Time for NTA Films|url=https://issuu.com/boxoffice/docs/boxoffice_111056-1|journal=[[Boxoffice (magazine)|Boxoffice]]|page=13|date=November 10, 1956}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=104 Sign Up for NTA Film Network, Due to Begin Operations on Oct. 15|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/56-OCR/1956-09-17-BC-OCR-Page-0056.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=56|date=September 17, 1956|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/56-OCR/1956-09-17-BC-OCR-Page-0058.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=58|date=September 17, 1956|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NTA Readying Answers On Film Network Questions|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/56-OCR/1956-10-15-BC-OCR-Page-0009.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=9|date=October 15, 1956|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Transfer to Oklahoma City===\nBeginning under the stewardship of the Streets group, the station's ownership made a concerted effort to migrate channel 5 into the larger Oklahoma City metropolitan area. On January 11, 1955, Streets Electronics filed a construction permit application to build a new {{convert|1,386|ft|m|0|adj=on}}-tall tower in a rural area {{convert|6|mi|km|spell=in}} west-northwest of [[Crescent, Oklahoma|Crescent]] ({{convert|31|mi|km|disp=sqbr}} south-southeast of Enid).<ref>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/55-OCR/1955-01-17-BC-OCR-Page-0105.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=105|date=January 17, 1955|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> The move came shortly before the FCC proposed rules to limit television transmission antennas from being located more than {{convert|5|mi|km|spell=in}} from the outskirts of a station's principal city of license. The KGEO transmitter proposal as well as a proposal by KSWS-TV (now NBC affiliate [[KOBR]]) in [[Roswell, New Mexico]] to build a {{convert|1,610|ft|m|adj=on}} transmission tower drew opposition from the [[United States Air Force]] and the [[United States Department of Defense|U.S. Department of Defense]] (DoD), which were concerned that broadcast towers standing at heights above {{convert|1,000|ft|m|0}} would create safety hazards for military and civil aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|title=At deadline: Air Force Wants Low Towers|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/55-OCR/1955-04-18-BC-OCR-Page-0009.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=9|date=April 18, 1955|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> On August 5, FCC Hearing Examiner Hugh B. Hutchison issued a recommendation for approval of the move of the KGEO transmitter to the Crescent site, citing that the existing tower near Enid (located within a {{convert|12|mi|km|disp=sqbr|adj=on}} proximity to [[Vance Air Force Base]] and [[Enid Woodring Regional Airport|Woodring Airport]]) was more of a hazard to airplanes than the proposed tower would have been, that the proposed tower would substantially place 678,439 residents within KGEO-TV's signal contour. Hutchinson also stated that KGEO was not guilty of charges made by KTVQ owner Republic Television and Radio Company that channel 5 wanted to \"straddle\" its transmitter between Enid and Oklahoma City to serve both cities, as between 75% and 85% of television set owners in the Enid area had oriented their home antennas to receive signals from Oklahoma City and the new tower would provide improved reception in Enid by allowing the signal to propagate into the area at the same direction that these home antennas were aimed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Examiner Approves Second Tall Tower|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/55-OCR/1955-08-08-BC-OCR-Page-0084.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=80|date=August 8, 1955|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn December 15, the Commission denied motions by Republic Television and Radio (which was concerned that KGEO's move to the Crescent site would create unfair competition that would result in the shutdown of the bankrupt station) to set aside the recommendation to grant of the transmitter application as well as a petition to reopen the record and call attention to the issues the move would cause.<ref>{{cite web|title=Okla. Move Opposed|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/55-OCR/1955-09-19-BC-OCR-Page-0180.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=202|date=September 19, 1955|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=FCC Hears Oral Argument On KGEO-TV Tower Changes|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/55-OCR/1955-12-26-BC-OCR-Page-0061.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=61|date=December 26, 1955|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=Fox the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/55-OCR/1955-12-26-BC-OCR-Page-0072.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=72|date=December 26, 1955|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> The FCC granted the permit change application by Streets Electronics in a 6-1 vote on May 4, 1956, subject to the group ensuring that the tower include sufficient lighting and hazard markings; the agency subsequently denied DoD petitions to deny KGEO's permit as well as one filed by WSLA (channel 8, now [[WAKA]]) in [[Selma, Alabama]] to increase its tower height from {{convert|387|ft|m}} to {{convert|1,993|ft|m}} based on the issues previously addressed.<ref>{{cite web|title=At Deadline: Tall Tower, Site Move Approved for KGEO-TV Enid|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/56-OCR/1956-05-07-BC-OCR-Page-0009.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=9|date=May 7, 1956|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/56-OCR/1956-05-14-BC-OCR-Page-0116.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=116|date=May 14, 1956|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=FCC Denies Defense Petitions Involving TV Towers' Height|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/56-OCR/1956-10-08-BC-OCR-Page-0074.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=74|date=October 8, 1956|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> On October 9, 1956, the Enid broadcast tower collapsed as construction crews prepared to relocate the station's transmitter antenna to the newly built Crescent tower, causing an estimated $140,000 in damage. The crane boom and [[gin pole]] that was hoisting the antenna off its platform buckled along with the tower, and the antenna dug a furrow into the ground, folding into four large sections during the collapse. KGEO-TV's analog signal was briefly knocked off the air until it set up temporary transmitter facilities from an auxiliary tower in downtown Enid, where it continued to transmit until the new tower became operational.<ref>{{cite web|title=KGEO-TV Antenna, Tower Collapse, Crash to Ground|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/56-OCR/1956-10-15-BC-OCR-Page-0074.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=74|date=October 15, 1956|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=KGEO-TV Antenna, Tower Collapse, Crash to Ground|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/56-OCR/1956-10-15-BC-OCR-Page-0078.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Telecasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=78|date=October 15, 1956|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn October 11, 1957, Streets Electronics sold KGEO-TV to the Caster-Robison Television Corporation (owned by broadcasting executives Louis E. Caster and Ashley Robison) for $950,000 plus the assumption of approximately $500,000 in debt; the sale to the Caster-Robison group received FCC approval two months later on December 11, with the then-recently deceased Caster's interest subsequently being transferred to his estate on March 5, 1958. On March 1, 1958, the station's call letters were changed to '''KOCO-TV''' (for \"<u>O</u>klahoma <u>C</u>ity, <u>O</u>klahoma\"), to reflect its new secondary city of service.<ref>{{cite web|title=At Deadline: Caster, Robison Pay $2 Million For Ch. 5 KGEO-TV Enid, Okla.|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/57-OCR/1957-10-14-BC-OCR-Page-0009.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=9|date=October 14, 1957|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/58-OCR/1958-03-03-BC-OCR-Page-0091.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=91|date=March 3, 1958|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Although it nominally remained an Enid station, KOCO had moved its studio operations to Oklahoma City, setting up temporary facilities inside a converted former Kimberling's [[grocery store]] on Britton Road. In October of that year, the station's operations moved to a permanent studio facility on a {{convert|5|acre|ha|spell=in|adj=on}} plot of land near Northwest 63rd Street and Portland Avenue, which included a terrace overlooking [[Lake Hefner]] for use during local programs produced outdoors within the studio grounds.<ref>{{cite web|title=New KOCO-TV Building Going Up|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/58-OCR/1958-07-07-BC-OCR-Page-0070.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=70|date=July 7, 1958|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> The station later requested a waiver of FCC [[station identification]] rules to identify as an Enid\u2013Oklahoma City station on-air and in license documents; however, the Commission denied the petition in May 1961.<ref>{{cite web|title=The FCC last week...|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/61-OCR/1961-05-22-BC-OCR-Page-0065.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=65|date=May 22, 1961|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/61-OCR/1961-05-22-BC-OCR-Page-0080.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=80|date=May 22, 1961|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Following Caster's death on May 15, 1960 due to a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Fates & Fortunes|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/60-OCR/BC-1960-05-23-OCR-Page-0098.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=98|date=May 23, 1960|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Ashley Robison and the inheritors of Caster's estate sought offers to sell off KOCO.\n\nIn May 1961, Caster-Robison Television sold KOCO to the Cimarron Television Corporation\u2014a subsidiary of Oklahoma City-based Capital City Investment Corporation that included among its investors, oilmen Dean A. McGee and John E. Kirkpatrick, Grayce Kerr (wife of state senator [[Robert S. Kerr]], who also was a minority owner of KVOO-TV [now [[KJRH-TV]]] in Tulsa with McGee at the time) as well as longtime KOCO stockholders Philip and L. D. Banta\u2014for $3 million. The sale received FCC approval on September 27 of that year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Changing Hands|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/61-OCR/1961-05-29-BC-OCR-Page-0036.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=38|date=May 29, 1961|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/61-OCR/1961-07-03-BC-OCR-Page-0082.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=82|date=July 3, 1961|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/61-OCR/1961-10-09-BC-OCR-Page-0104.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=104|date=October 9, 1961|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> As that transaction was taking place, the FCC issued a Notice of Proposed Rulemaking to add a third commercial VHF allocation, under reduced mileage separation requirements, in eight U.S. markets. Under the plan, per an earlier filing by the Caster-Robison group, KGEO and its channel 5 allocation would be moved to Oklahoma City, but with its signal radiation suppressed to alleviate co-channel interference with KFSA-TV (now [[KFSM-TV]]) in [[Fort Smith, Arkansas|Fort Smith]] (located {{convert|180|mi|km|disp=sqbr}} east of Oklahoma City, at a distance below the FCC's {{convert|190|mi|km|adj=on|disp=sqbr}} threshold for separation of adjacent broadcast signals transmitting on the same channel).<ref>{{cite web|title=New V for 11 markets, 8 will lose|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/61-OCR/1961-07-31-BC-OCR-Page-0048.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=48|date=July 31, 1961|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Where Third VHF Would Go|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/61-OCR/1961-08-07-BC-OCR-Page-0054.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=56|date=August 7, 1961|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/62-OCR/1962-02-26-BC-OCR-Page-0137.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=137|date=February 26, 1962|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Despite the full proposal receiving backing from ABC, the FCC voted twice against relocating short-spaced VHF channels into seven of the eight proposed markets during the spring of 1963, but granted permission for KOCO's channel allocation to be shifted to Oklahoma City both times, albeit with requirements that it observe standard mileage separation requirements to limit interference with KFSA-TV and that it maintain an auxiliary studio in Enid. The FCC granted KOCO a waiver of the mileage requirement in a 5-1 vote on July 25 of that year, after station representatives convinced the Commission that KOCO's would signal be impaired within Oklahoma City at a distance sufficient under the requirements, and that, if it were to comply with standard spacing rules and [[Civil Aeronautics Board]] tower height limitations, it would be difficult for the transmitter to provide a signal that would allow it to adequately serve both the state capital and Enid. (KOCO was the second Oklahoma television station to transfer its license and operations to a larger, nearby city: fellow ABC affiliate KTVX [now [[KTUL]]] had moved from [[Muskogee, Oklahoma|Muskogee]] to Tulsa in August 1957.)<ref>{{cite web|title=ABC Not Giving Up on Drop-ins|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/63-OCR/1963-03-18-BC-OCR-Page-0058.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=58|date=March 18, 1963|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Drop-ins end up in short-spaced grave|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/63-OCR/1963-06-03-BC-OCR-Page-0044.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=44|date=June 3, 1963|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/63-OCR/1963-06-10-BC-OCR-Page-0103.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=103|date=June 10, 1963|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Closed Circuit|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/63-OCR/1963-07-29-BC-OCR-Page-0005.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=5|date=July 29, 1963|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/63-OCR/1963-08-05-BC-OCR-Page-0097.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=97|date=August 5, 1963|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Closed Circuit|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/63-OCR/1963-08-12-BC-OCR-Page-0005.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=5|date=August 12, 1963|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1964, channel 5 moved its transmitter facilities to a {{convert|1,563|ft|m|adj=on}} tower on East Britton Road in northeast Oklahoma City, at an antenna farm housing the transmission towers of other local television and radio stations; the tower was dedicated with two days of ceremonies that included such notable guests as [[ABC News]] anchor [[Howard K. Smith]] and the husband-and-wife comedy team of [[Phil Ford (comedian)|Phil Ford]] and [[Mimi Hines]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Nabbed' by the posse|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/64-OCR/1964-03-09-BC-OCR-Page-0088.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=88|date=March 9, 1964|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> KOCO's formal transfer to Oklahoma City made it the third station in the state's capital city to have been affiliated with ABC: WKY-TV had aired select ABC shows under a secondary basic affiliation from its sign-on in June 1949 until August 1956 and fledgling UHF outlet KTVQ maintained a full-time primary affiliation from its sign-on in November 1953 until that station ceased operations in December 1955, with WKY-TV continuing to carry some of the network's programs while KTVQ was operating. (Like other UHF stations of the period, television viewers were required to purchase a standalone UHF tuner in order to receive KTVQ's signal.)\n\nOne of channel 5's most popular local programs was a show aimed at younger audiences; [[Ed Birchall]] hosted a local [[children's television series|children's program]] on the station for 29 years from March 1959 until shortly before his death after a brief bout with advanced-stage cancer in July 1988. Originally debuting as ''Lunch With HoHo'' and airing under various titles (including ''HoHo's Cartoon Circus'', ''Good Morning HoHo'' and ''HoHo's Showplace''), Birchall\u2014who donned a colored patchwork jacket and suspender pants, a small brown [[top hat]] and oversized tie in his portrayal of HoHo the [[Clown]]\u2014starred alongside a [[sock puppet]] named Pokey (played by longtime KOCO [[stage manager]] Bill Howard), and presented various segments from educational content to light-hearted newspaper stories to [[animated cartoon|cartoon]] shorts. A memorial service (the first of three held for Birchall) had to be moved to St. Charles Borromeo Catholic Church, one of Oklahoma City's largest churches, to accommodate a live KOCO broadcast (which was also carried by KTVY, KWTV and KOKH-TV) as well as a crowd of mourners that included an [[guard of honour|honor guard]] of professional clowns.<ref>{{cite news|title='Ho Ho,' the Hobo Clown, Shows the Good Side of Life to Young TV Viewers|url=http://newsok.com/article/2091899|author=Nancy P. Condit|newspaper=[[The Oklahoman|The Daily Oklahoman]]|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=December 18, 1984|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ho Ho: State's Friend Dies After Short Illness|url=http://newsok.com/article/2231226|author=Julie Ellsworth|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=July 4, 1988|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Memories of Ho-Ho the Clown|url=http://www.405magazine.com/June-2016/Memories-of-Ho-Ho-the-Clown/|author=Mark Beutler|periodical=405 Magazine|date=June 1, 2016|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ho Ho Gets Last Tribute From Friends|url=http://newsok.com/article/2231565|author=Mick Hinton|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=July 8, 1988|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Beloved KOCO television personality dies|url=http://www.koco.com/article/beloved-koco-television-personality-dies/4291517|website=KOCO-TV|publisher=[[Hearst Television]]|date=January 9, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Howard, Oklahoma City TV personality best known for Pokey the Puppet, dies|url=http://newsok.com/article/3832149|author=Brandy McDonnell|newspaper=The Oklahoman|publisher=[[The Anschutz Corporation]]|date=January 9, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Other notable past local programs produced by KGEO/KOCO included entertainment/lifestyle/fashion talk program ''The Ida B. Show'' (originally titled ''At Home with Ida B.'' and then ''Dateline Hollywood''), whose host, Ida Blackburn, had previously hosted a local version of ''[[Romper Room]]'' for the station from 1958 to 1960;<ref>{{cite news|title=Oklahoma TV personality 'Ida B.' dies at 87|url=http://newsok.com/article/5530617|newspaper=The Oklahoman|publisher=The Anschutz Corporation|date=December 13, 2016|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=IDA BLACKBURN|url=http://legacy.newsok.com/obituaries/oklahoman/obituary.aspx?pid=183120704|newspaper=The Oklahoman|publisher=The Anschutz Corporation|date=December 18, 2016|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO legend Ida Blackburn dies|url=http://www.koco.com/article/koco-legend-ida-blackburn-dies/8489117|website=KOCO-TV|publisher=Hearst Television|date=December 12, 2016|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> and ''Captain Tom's [[Popeye the Sailor (animated cartoons)|Popeye]] Theatre'', hosted by Tom Gilmore as the titular character, who read storybooks on the program, alongside the puppet version of the Alfred Lee Whittle character he developed for radio in 1948.<ref>{{cite news|title=State mourns passing of pioneer newsman|url=http://newsok.com/article/1929064|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=May 14, 2003|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> and a local version of the ''[[Dialing for Dollars]]'' movie/trivia franchise.\n\n===Combined Communications ownership===\nIn November 1969, Cimarron Television announced that it would sell KOCO-TV to [[Phoenix, Arizona]]-based Combined Communications Corporation (CCC) for $6.5 million. It was the first broadcast property ever acquired by CCC, which was formed earlier that year through the merger of the KTAR Broadcasting Company (owner of company flagships [[KTAR (AM)|KTAR-AM]]-[[KPNX|TV]] in Phoenix) and Eller Outdoor Advertising (a company founded by CCC president [[Karl Eller]]). The sale received FCC approval on July 17, 1970.<ref>{{cite web|title=CCC begins expansion moves|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/69-OCR/1969-11-17-BC-OCR-Page-0064.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=64|date=November 17, 1969|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=KOCO-TV joins group in $6.5 million sale|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/70-OCR/1970-07-27-BC-OCR-Page-0047.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=49|date=July 27, 1970|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=KOCO-TV joins group in $6.5 million sale|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/70-OCR/1970-07-27-BC-OCR-Page-0048.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=50|date=July 27, 1970|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=For the Record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/70-OCR/1970-07-27-BC-OCR-Page-0076.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=76|date=July 27, 1970|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> In February 1977, KOCO adopted \"5 Alive\" as its on-air branding, as part of Combined Communications' rollout of the \"Alive\" branding concept\u2014which Peters Productions initially developed for [[Tribune Broadcasting]]-owned [[Independent station (North America)|independent station]] [[WPIX]] (now a [[The CW|CW]] affiliate) in [[New York City]] in early 1976\u2014on most of the group's television stations. It was accompanied by a logo similar to that used at the time by [[Atlanta]] sister station [[WXIA-TV]], when it began identifying as \"11 Alive\" in September 1976 ({{as of|2017|lc=y}}, WXIA is the only station out of the four former CCC outlets that continues to use the \"Alive\" moniker, which had also been utilized by sister station [[WLKY]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]] and former sister [[WPTA]] in [[Fort Wayne, Indiana]]).\n\nOn March 31, 1977, [[Allbritton Communications|Washington Star Communications]] announced that it would sell its [[Washington, D.C.]] flagship station WMAL-TV (now [[WJLA-TV]]) to Combined Communications, in exchange for KOCO-TV and approximately $65 million of nonvoting preferred stock in CCC. The deal, which was considered to be the largest purchase price for a single television station up to that time, was done to comply with an FCC rulemaking to diversify print and broadcast media ownership, under which the agency required Star Communications to divest itself of all but one of its D.C.-area media properties by January 1979. The proceeds from the sale, as well as a total of $65 million that Star Communications would have received within 20 years through the repurchase of Combined stock, were to be used to offset the continuing monetary losses of ''[[The Washington Star]]'' newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|title=WMAL-TV fetches $100 million, trading record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/77-OCR/BC-1977-04-04-OCR-Page-0028.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=28|date=April 4, 1977|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=WMAL-TV fetches $100 million, trading record|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/77-OCR/BC-1977-04-04-OCR-Page-0029.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=29|date=April 4, 1977|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tricks of the trade in CCC-WSCI swap|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/77-OCR/BC-1977-04-11-OCR-Page-0030.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=30|date=April 11, 1977|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Allbritton Plans Trade of WMAL-TV In Effort to Save Star|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1977/04/01/allbritton-plans-trade-of-wmal-tv-in-effort-to-save-star/be312264-4d7e-444c-828e-09fa8b9772c6/|author=Stephen J. Lynton|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[Graham Media Group|The Washington Post Company]]|date=April 1, 1977|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Although the sale initially received approval from the FCC in January 1978, it was never finalized: on February 3, 1978, three weeks before the sale contract with CCC was set to expire, Star Communications sold ''The Washington Star'' to [[Time Inc.]] for $20 million plus the assumption of $8 million in debt. The FCC subsequently rescinded its approval of the transfer pending an inquiry into Time's purchase of the ''Star'', given the basis of the trade on ensuring the newspaper's financial stability.<ref>{{cite web|title=WJLA-TV swap for KOCO-TV approved by FCC|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/78-OCR/1978-01-16-BC-OCR-Page-0028.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=28|date=January 16, 1978|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=WJLA-TV swap for KOCO-TV approved by FCC|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/78-OCR/1978-01-16-BC-OCR-Page-0029.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=29|date=January 16, 1978|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Wheeling and dealing in Washington|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/78-OCR/1978-02-06-BC-OCR-Page-0031.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=31|date=February 6, 1978|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=More shoals ahead on WJLA-TV deal|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/78-OCR/1978-02-13-BC-OCR-Page-0029.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=29|date=February 13, 1978|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=FCC wants another look at WJLA swap|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/78-OCR/1978-02-20-BC-OCR-Page-0029.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=29|date=February 20, 1978|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=FCC wants another look at WJLA swap|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/78-OCR/1978-02-20-BC-OCR-Page-0030.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=30|date=February 20, 1978|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> In a meeting to reconsider its approval of the WJLA-KOCO trade in early March (which was rescheduled from its original February 24 hearing date), the FCC once again granted approval of the station trade after the commission determined that Star Communications president [[Joe Allbritton]] had not committed himself to retaining the ''Star'' and that reevaluating the approval order turned up no reason to overturn the original decision.<ref>{{cite web|title=Allbritton deal twists slowly in the wind|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/78-OCR/1978-02-27-BC-OCR-Page-0028.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=28|date=February 27, 1978|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=Allbritton deal twists slowly in the wind|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/78-OCR/1978-02-27-BC-OCR-Page-0029.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=29|date=February 27, 1978|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Allbritton deal again clears FCC; court appeal is still a hang-up|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/78-OCR/1978-03-13-BC-OCR-Page-0024.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=24|date=March 13, 1978|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Despite this, on March 24, Star Communications\u2014which had twice extended its sale contract with CCC to accommodate the FCC's hearing docket following delays in the hearing date\u2014terminated the sale, citing a court appeal filed by the Adams Morgan Organization, the District of Columbia chapter of the [[National Organization for Women]], the D.C. Media Task Force and the National Black Media Coalition that accused Star Communications on reneging on efforts to help minority-owned groups obtain financing to acquire the company's broadcast properties.<ref>{{cite web|title=Allbritton backs out of WJLA-TV deal|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/78-OCR/1978-03-27-BC-OCR-Page-0027.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=27|date=March 27, 1978|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=WSCI insists Allbritton didn't renege on promises to citizen groups when it sold Washington stations|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/77-OCR/BC-1977-09-19-OCR-Page-0089.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=119|date=September 19, 1977|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=WSCI insists Allbritton didn't renege on promises to citizen groups when it sold Washington stations|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/77-OCR/BC-1977-09-19-OCR-Page-0120.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=120|date=September 19, 1977|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Gannett ownership===\nOn May 9, 1978, the then-[[Rochester, New York]]-based [[Gannett|Gannett Company]] announced that it would purchase Combined Communications\u2014which, at the time, had owned seven television and thirteen radio stations, two newspapers (''[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]'' and the ''[[Oakland Tribune]]''), and an outdoor advertising unit\u2014in an all-stock transaction worth $370 million, which was the largest transaction involving an American print and broadcast media company up to that point. The sale\u2014which was contingent on Gannett selling its Rochester station, [[WHEC-TV]] (which it later sold for $27 million to BENI Broadcasting), to comply with FCC rules that restricted media companies from owning more than seven VHF television stations nationwide\u2014both received FCC approval and was consummated by the boards of Gannett and Combined on June 7, 1979.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gannett Plans to Buy Combined Communications|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/business/1978/05/09/gannett-plans-to-buy-combined-communications/0e005aaa-35ee-4696-8a26-e756cdb5ac65/|author=William H. Jones|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[Graham Media Group|The Washington Post Company]]|date=May 9, 1978|accessdate=October 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Combined Communications Agrees To a $370 Million Gannett Merger|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1978/05/09/archives/combined-communications-agrees-to-a-370-million-gannett-merger.html?mcubz=3|author=N. R. Kleinfeld|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=May 9, 1978|accessdate=October 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gannett Holders Approve Merger|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/02/28/archives/gannett-holders-approve-merger.html?mcubz=3|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=February 28, 1979|accessdate=October 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=FCC clears biggest deal ever|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/79-OCR/BC-1979-06-11-OCR-Page-0019.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=19|date=June 11, 1979|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}<br>{{cite web|title=FCC clears biggest deal ever|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/79-OCR/BC-1979-06-11-OCR-Page-0020.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=20|date=June 11, 1979|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Gannett (which would eventually spin off its broadcast holdings into [[Tegna Inc.]] in June 2015) made major investments in the former Combined stations, aiming to improve the local news presence at KOCO and the four sister stations included in the purchase. In the fall of 1980, the station's operations were relocated into a newly constructed, state-of-the-art studio facility located near the station's Britton Road transmitter site ({{convert|0.5|mi|km|disp=sqbr}} east of the studios of rival KTVY); the former studio facilities on Northeast 63rd Street were subsequently purchased by the [[Trinity Broadcasting Network]] for use as the office and production facilities for TBN [[owned-and-operated station]] [[KTBO-TV]] (channel 14). The new $2.4-million facility (designed by Oklahoma City-based architect Frank Rees) housed two production studios, offices and an expanded newsroom, and was designed to provide passive [[solar energy]] and included overhangs to shield the building's interior from sunrays to keep the building cool during the summer months.<ref>{{cite web|title=In Sync: Starting from scratch|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/79-OCR/BC-1979-07-23-OCR-Page-0048.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=48|date=July 23, 1979|accessdate=October 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile KOCO remained under Gannett ownership for 18 years, its position in the company's portfolio was placed in limbo several times. On September 25, 1982, Gannett announced that it would sell KOCO to the [[San Francisco]]-based [[Chronicle Publishing Company]] for $100 million, in exchange for Chronicle's NBC-affiliated [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]] flagship station, [[KRON-TV]] (now a [[MyNetworkTV]] affiliate), which Chronicle had built and signed on in 1949. The transaction was contingent on Gannett selling its [[Oakland, California|Oakland]]-based newspaper, ''East Bay Today'' (which served as the prototype for ''[[USA Today]]''), to comply with cross-ownership restrictions that prohibit the common ownership of newspapers and full-power television stations in the same market, and was part of an attempt by the company to concentrate its television station holdings to major markets. On September 28, 1983, Chronicle and Gannett \"mutually agreed\" to terminate the sale agreement, after Chronicle management decided to retain ownership of KRON.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gannett Trades KOCO-TV|url=http://newsok.com/article/1996998|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=September 25, 1982|accessdate=October 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ownership Change Set for KOCO-TV|url=http://newsok.com/article/1997083|author=Gypsy Hogan|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=September 26, 1982|accessdate=October 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gannett to swap KOCO-TV plus $100 million for Chronicle's KRON-TV|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/82-OCR/1982-10-04-BC-OCR-Page-0030.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=30|date=October 4, 1982|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gannett Won't Buy Television Station|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/103326550/|periodical=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|page=52|date=September 29, 1983|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Under Gannett, KOCO became heavily involved in community outreach initiatives; from 1981 to 1997, the station held the \"5 Who Care Awards,\" an annual awards telecast recognizing outstanding public service contributions by local volunteers, businesses and [[non-profit organization]]s and was expanded in 1989 to offer the \"Kids Who Care Awards\" to honor volunteerism by Oklahoma youth.<ref>{{cite news|title=Station to Salute Outstanding Volunteers|url=http://newsok.com/article/2142636|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=March 30, 1986|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=5 Who Care' Awards to Air Monday|url=http://newsok.com/article/2263745|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=April 23, 1989|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> The station expanded upon these initiatives in 1989, with the creation of the \"Project Challenge\" campaign, which included the \"Oklahoma's Best\" honors for academic excellence and dedication to the teaching profession.<ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO-TV to Honor Teachers|url=http://newsok.com/article/2382240|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=January 19, 1992|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn September 5, 1985, Gannett announced that it would purchase the [[Detroit News|Evening News Association]] for $717 million. However, the purchase created an ownership conflict between KOCO-TV and NBC-affiliated rival KTVY, as FCC rules in effect at the time had prohibited a single company from [[Duopoly (broadcasting)|owning two commercial television stations in the same market]]. (Even today, that combination would have been forbidden as their respective total-day viewership falls among the agency's threshold prohibiting co-ownership of any of the four highest-rated television stations within a single media market.)<ref>{{cite web|title=Gannett's magic touch wins Evening News|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/85-OCR/BC-1985-09-02-OCR-Page-0031.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=31|date=September 2, 1985}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gannett's magic touch wins Evening News|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/85-OCR/BC-1985-09-02-OCR-Page-0032.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=32|date=September 2, 1985|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=OK, Gannett, your move!|url=http://newsok.com/article/2120412|author=Glen Phillips|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=September 8, 1985|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gannett May Bid For ENA Control|url=http://newsok.com/article/2119336|author=Mary Jo Nelson|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=August 28, 1985|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Gannett ultimately chose to keep KOCO on November 15, 1985, when it sold KTVY, along with fellow NBC affiliate [[WALA-TV]] (now a Fox affiliate) in [[Mobile, Alabama]] and CBS affiliate [[KOLD-TV]] in [[Tucson, Arizona]] to [[Miami|Miami, Florida]]-based [[Knight Ridder|Knight Ridder Broadcasting]] for $160 million. However, Gannett was allowed to jointly own KOCO and KTVY under a temporary waiver until the Knight-Ridder transaction was completed in February 1986, one month after the KTVY sale was finalized.<ref>{{cite web|title=Closed Circuit|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/85-OCR/BC-1985-09-09-OCR-Page-0007.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=7|date=September 9, 1985|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gannett discloses what it wants to keep|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/85-OCR/BC-1985-10-07-OCR-Page-0030.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=30|date=October 7, 1985|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=In Brief|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/85-OCR/BC-1985-11-18-OCR-Page-0126.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=126|date=November 18, 1985|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gannett Sells KTVY To Knight-Ridder|url=http://newsok.com/article/2128026|author=Mary Jo Nelson|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=November 16, 1985|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Knight-Ridder Newspaper Inc. purchases from Gannett Company Inc. three TV stations in Oklahoma City, Mobile, and Tucson|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-4140148.html|agency=[[PR Newswire]]|publisher=[[Knight Ridder]]|via=[[HighBeam Research]]|date=February 19, 1986|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> On May 14, 1990, three days after KFOR-TV adopted a similar schedule, channel 5 began maintaining a 24-hour-a-day programming schedule, adding a mix of syndicated programming and infomercials as well as hourly local news updates to fill overnight timeslots. (KOCO resumed daily overnight sign-offs on December 27, 1991; it permanently instituted a 24-hour schedule on November 28, 1993, offering ABC's overnight newscast ''[[World News Now]]'' and an all-night classic film block on Fridays and Saturdays, the latter of which had previously been offered by KOCO from September 1981 until it resumed signing off on weekends in September 1987.)<ref name=\"oklahoman-24hourtv\">{{cite news|title=24-Hour TV Programming Announced|url=http://newsok.com/article/2317104|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=May 12, 1990|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> After having phased out the name from its news branding the previous September, when it began identifying its newscasts as ''5 News'', KOCO dropped the \"5 Alive\" moniker from general promotional use in May 1994, in conjunction with the debut of a new logo (which was inspired by the [[Paul Rand]]-designed [[circle 7 logo]], and was replaced with the current \"circle 5\" logo following a subsequent rebranding in February 1995) and on-air graphics for its newscasts and station promotions; prior to that time, KOCO and WXIA (which briefly retired the \"11 Alive\" brand in 1993, only to begin restoring it upon viewer demand) were the only Gannett stations that had continued to use the \"Alive\" moniker.\n\nOn July 24, 1995, the Gannett Company announced that it had entered into an agreement to acquire [[Multimedia (media company)|Multimedia Inc.]] for $1.7 billion, plus $539 million in long-term debt. When the FCC approved the merger in late November 1995, the agency's Broadcast Bureau stipulated that Gannett would have to sell KOCO and NBC-affiliated sister station [[WLWT]] in [[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, Ohio]] to comply with cross-ownership regulations. (Gannett was also required to sell CBS affiliate [[WMAZ-TV]] and sister radio stations WMAZ [now [[WMAC]]] and [[WAYS (AM)|WAYS]] in [[Macon, Georgia]]; however, the company was ultimately able to retain WMAZ-TV after the FCC modified its national ownership cap to allow broadcasters to own any number of television stations with a combined reach of up to 35% of all U.S. households.) However, since it could not legally own both a broadcast television station and a cable provider in the same market under FCC rules of the time period, Gannett was granted a waiver that gave the company until December 1996 to divest itself of either Multimedia Cablevision\u2014which, at the time, was the major cable provider for most of Oklahoma City's suburban communities (except for [[Forest Park, Oklahoma|Forest Park]], which has historically had its public utilities aligned with Oklahoma City and, therefore, was the only area suburb that was part of [[Cox Communications]]'s Oklahoma City service area at the time)\u2014or KOCO-TV; the sale was finalized on December 4, 1995.<ref>{{cite news|title=THE MEDIA BUSINESS; Expanding in TV, Gannett Agrees to Buy Multimedia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/25/business/the-media-business-expanding-in-tv-gannett-agrees-to-buy-multimedia.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=July 25, 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Gannett, Multimedia announce merger agreement|url=http://www.gannett.com/article/99999999/PRESSRELEASES17/100721008/Gannett--Multimedia-announce-merger-agreement|publisher=Gannett Company|date=December 4, 1995|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130107024621/http://www.gannett.com/article/99999999/PRESSRELEASES17/100721008/Gannett--Multimedia-announce-merger-agreement|archivedate=January 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sale Due For KOCO In Merger|url=http://newsok.com/article/2522179|author=Jim Stafford|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=December 2, 1995|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gannett Deal Yields Ownership Conflict|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P2-5690127|newspaper=[[The Journal Record]]|publisher=The Journal Record Publishing Company|via=Questia Online Library|date=July 26, 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gannett/Multimedia gets FCC green light|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/95-OCR/BC-1995-12-04-OCR-Page-0020.pdf|author=Chris McConnell|periodical=Broadcasting & Cable|publisher=[[Reed Business Information|Cahners Business Information]]|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=18|date=April 7, 1997|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hearst Television ownership===\n{{multiple image\n | direction = vertical\n | align = right\n | width   = 190\n | image1  = KOCO.svg\n | caption1 = Former KOCO logo, used from August 1998 until April 18, 2013.\n | image2  = Koco 2008.png\n | caption2 = Former alternate logo for KOCO's newscasts under the \"''Eyewitness News 5''\" brand.\n}}\nOn November 20, 1996, Gannett announced that it would sell KOCO-TV and WLWT to [[San Antonio]]-based Argyle Television Holdings II (the successor company to the original Argyle Television, which sold most of its television stations to [[New World Pictures#New World Communications (1993\u20131997)|New World Communications]] in May 1994) for $20 million, in exchange for fellow ABC affiliate [[WZZM]] in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]] and NBC affiliate [[WGRZ]] in [[Buffalo, New York]]. The sale \u2013 which required Gannett to sell the [[Niagara Falls, New York]]-based ''[[Niagara Gazette]]'' to alleviate a cross-ownership conflict with WGRZ \u2013 was approved by the FCC on January 27, 1997, and finalized on January 31.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Gannett Announces Agreement with Argyle Television Inc.|url=http://www.tegna.com/gannett-announces-agreement-with-argyle-television-inc/|publisher=Gannett Company|via=[[Tegna, Inc.]]|date=November 20, 1996|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Texas chain buys WLWT|url=http://www.enquirer.com/editions/1996/11/21/loc_wlwt.html|author=Jeff Harrington|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|publisher=Gannett Company|date=November 21, 1996|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Argyle Television to swap television stations in Grand Rapids, Mich. and Buffalo, N.Y. to Gannett for television stations in Cincinnati and Oklahoma City|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-18871796.html|agency=[[Business Wire]]|publisher=Gannett Company|via=[[HighBeam Research]]|date=November 20, 1996}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Gannett Completes Agreement with Argyle Television Inc.|url=http://www.tegna.com/gannett-completes-agreement-with-argyle-television-inc/|publisher=Gannett Company|via=[[Tegna, Inc.]]|date=January 31, 1997|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gannett, Argyle swapping TVs|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/96-OCR/BC-1996-11-25-OCR-Page-0038.pdf|author=Elizabeth A. Rathbun|periodical=Broadcasting & Cable|publisher=Cahners Business Information|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=42|date=November 25, 1996|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> Subsequently, on March 27, 1997, the [[Hearst Corporation]] announced that it would purchase five of the seven Argyle Television stations\u2014KOCO-TV, WLWT, ABC affiliates [[KHBS]] in Fort Smith (and its [[Fayetteville, Arkansas|Fayetteville]] satellite KHOG-TV), [[KITV]] in [[Honolulu]] (and its satellites KHVO in [[Hilo, Hawaii|Hilo]] and KMAU in [[Wailuku, Hawaii]]), and [[WAPT]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]], and the non-license assets of Fox affiliate [[WNAC-TV]] in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]\u2014for $525 million. The merger was approved by the FCC on June 2, 1997, and finalized in August of that year; the combined group of Hearst's six existing television stations and the five it acquired from Argyle became known as Hearst-Argyle Television (renamed [[Hearst Television]] in May 2009).<ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO-TV Among 12 Stations in Company|url=http://newsok.com/article/2572645|author=Jon Denton|newspaper=The Daily Oklahoman|publisher=Oklahoma Publishing Company|date=March 27, 1997|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hearst to Buy Argyle TV In a Rare Public Venture|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/03/27/business/hearst-to-buy-argyle-tv-in-a-rare-public-venture.html|author=Kenneth N. Gilpin|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=March 27, 1997|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hearst stocks up on ArgyIes|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/97-OCR/BC-1997-01-20-OCR-Page-1015.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting & Cable|publisher=Cahners Business Information|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=6|date=January 20, 1997|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Changing Hands|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/97-OCR/BC-1997-04-07-OCR-Page-0070.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting & Cable|publisher=Cahners Business Information|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=70|date=April 7, 1997|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> The acquisition marked Hearst's return to the Oklahoma City market; the company owned radio station KOMA (1520 AM, now [[KOKC (AM)|KOKC]]) from 1932 until 1938, when Hearst sold that station to John T. Griffin (who founded KWTV in 1953).<ref>{{cite web|title=Griffin Contracts To Acquire KOMA|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/38-OCR/1938-11-01-BC-OCR-Page-0026.pdf|periodical=Broadcasting-Broadcast Advertising|publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc.|via=American Radio History|format=PDF|page=26|date=November 1, 1938|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn June 13, 1998, [[rear flank downdraft]] winds approaching {{convert|105|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}} struck the station's Britton Road studio, causing minor damage that included a toppled backyard fence and a large dent to the dome of its [[weather radar]]. The event was broadcast live as the station was providing wall-to-wall coverage of the accompanying [[Thunderstorm#Supercells|supercell thunderstorm]], which [[Tornado outbreak of June 13, 1998#Oklahoma|spawned seven tornadoes]] across [[Canadian County, Oklahoma|Canadian]] and northern [[Oklahoma County, Oklahoma|Oklahoma]] counties, while a KOCO photojournalist positioned in the studio's garage was shooting video of the storm as it approached the Britton Road facility. Believing a tornado had touched down because of the apparent cloud-based mesocyclone rotation, Mike LaPoint (who was the station's weekend evening meteorologist from 1997 to 2001) yelled to then-chief meteorologist Rick Mitchell, \"Rick, it's on the ground!\" as the three men ran to take shelter inside the building. Electricity was knocked out to the studio and transmitter facilities, taking the KOCO broadcast signal off-the-air for almost 24 hours; the station remained available to Cox Communications and Multimedia Cablevision subscribers via a direct auxiliary feed transmitted by [[Optical fiber|fiber optic]] to the cable providers.<ref>{{cite web|title=June 13, 1998|url=https://kocoweatherblog.wordpress.com/2008/06/13/june-13-1998/|website=KOCO-TV|publisher=Hearst-Argyle Television|date=June 13, 2008|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=June 13, 1998: A Look Back|id=IJ_hlWT9l3g|date=|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A selection from a decade of visits to tower and studio sites in the Northeast and beyond|url=http://www.fybush.com/sites/2004/site-040129.html|author=Scott Fybush|website=Fybush.com|date=April 1, 2004|accessdate=March 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1998, when [[KTEN]]\u2014which had been affiliated with ABC on a part-time basis since its sign-on in June 1954\u2014disaffiliated from the network, KOCO-TV began serving as a default ABC station for areas on the Oklahoma side of the adjacent [[Sherman, Texas|Sherman]]\u2013[[Ada, Oklahoma|Ada]] market (including the cities of Ada, [[Pauls Valley, Oklahoma|Pauls Valley]] and [[Sulphur, Oklahoma|Sulphur]]) through its existing availability on most cable providers in the region ([[WFAA]] in [[Dallas]]\u2013[[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]] served as the primary default affiliate for counties in far southern Oklahoma and extreme [[North Texas|north-central Texas]] within the DMA). However, residents in southern Oklahoma could view most ABC programs that were preempted by KTEN via KOCO for several years beforehand, particularly after the former switched to a primary NBC affiliation in 1986 (resulting in the steady reduction of ABC-provided content on KTEN's schedule to select daytime and prime time programs by 1994, when it added an additional primary affiliation with Fox). The Sherman-Ada market would regain an ABC station of its own when KTEN launched a [[KTEN-DT3|digital subchannel]] affiliated with the network on May 1, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=ABC-TV Gets New Affil In Sherman-Ada|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/41244/abctv-gets-new-affil-in-shermanada|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media|date=April 6, 2010|accessdate=February 10, 2015}}</ref> Despite this, KOCO remains available on cable and [[direct-broadcast satellite television|satellite]] providers within that market. Through this former default status, it was the only Oklahoma City television station to provide extensive live coverage of an [[Tornado outbreak of February 10\u201311, 2009|EF4 tornado]] that killed eight people in [[Lone Grove, Oklahoma|Lone Grove]] on February 10, 2009.\n\nDue partly to its strong syndicated programming lineup, KOCO has grown to become one of ABC's strongest affiliates in recent years; it ranked as one of the network's highest-rated affiliates from 2009 to 2012, according to [[Nielsen Media Research]], sharing this distinction with two of its Hearst-owned sister stations, [[WISN-TV]] in [[Milwaukee]] and [[KMBC-TV]] in [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]]; the station had also made the claim of ranking as the highest-rated ABC affiliate overall from 2007 to 2009. In December 2010, KOCO became the second television station in the Oklahoma City market (after KWTV-DT) and the sixth station in Oklahoma to carry syndicated programming in [[high-definition television|high definition]].\n\n==Subchannel history==\n===KOCO-DT2===\n'''KOCO-DT2''', branded as '''\"MeTV Oklahoma City\"''', is the [[MeTV]]-affiliated second [[digital subchannel]] of KOCO-TV. [[Terrestrial television|Over the air]], it broadcasts in standard definition on VHF digital channel 7.2 (or virtual channel 5.2 via [[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]]). On cable, KOCO-DT2 is available on Cox Communications digital channel 222 in the Oklahoma City area, and on [[Suddenlink Communications]] systems throughout western Oklahoma. In addition to carrying MeTV programming, KOCO-DT2 is also designated as an alternate ABC affiliate, and carries network (and occasionally, syndicated) programs that KOCO must preempt to carry extended [[breaking news]] or [[severe weather]] coverage or special event programming on its main channel.\n\nKOCO launched a digital subchannel on virtual channel 5.2 in 2005, which originally carried a live feed of the station's Doppler radar\u2014then known as \"Advantage Doppler HD\" (now branded as \"First Alert Dual-Pol Doppler\")\u2014accompanied by an audio simulcast of [[NOAA Weather Radio]] station [[WXK85]]. In April 2008, the subchannel became an affiliate of [[The Local AccuWeather Channel]], under the brand \"First Alert Weather 24/7\". Alongside carrying regional and national forecast segments provided by the [[AccuWeather]]-operated network, KOCO also produced pre-recorded local forecast segments presented by meteorologists from the station's \"First Alert Weather\" team\u2014which were updated two to three times per day\u2014for the subchannel (the radar imagery and NOAA Weather Radio feed continued to be shown after the local forecast segments, along with serving as a transition segment between its AccuWeather and E/I programming).<ref>{{cite web|title=KOCO, AccuWeather to offer 24-hour weather in Oklahoma City|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/21660/koco-accuweather-to-offer-24hour-weather-in-oklahoma-city|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media|date=April 16, 2008|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=KOCO-TV Partners with Local AccuWeather Channel to Offer 24-Hour Weather in Oklahoma City Market|url=https://www.accuweather.com/en/press/35227|website=[[AccuWeather]]|date=April 16, 2008|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> In addition, KOCO-DT2 carried a half-hour block of syndicated children's programs compliant with FCC [[E/I|educational programming]] guidelines on Monday through Saturday afternoons, and was occasionally used to air special weather coverage from its sister stations during tropical weather events (in particular, in September 2008, it simulcast coverage of [[Hurricane Gustav]] from NBC-affiliated sister station [[WDSU]] in [[New Orleans]] to provide information on the storm for [[Louisiana]] residents who evacuated inland to Oklahoma City).\n\nOn January 24, 2011, KOCO-DT2 became an affiliate of [[This TV]], through an affiliation agreement between Hearst Television and network co-parent [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], which handled affiliate distribution for the movie-focused network on behalf of original managing partner [[Weigel Broadcasting]] (as [[DHX Media|Cookie Jar Group]] programmed a daily [[Cookie Jar Toons|block of educational and entertainment-focused children's programs]] for This TV at the time, KOCO dropped the syndicated E/I programming that Hearst acquired for its stations' DT2 feeds to comply with educational content regulations for multicast services).\n\nOn July 24, 2012, Hearst Television and Weigel Broadcasting announced that Hearst had renewed affiliation agreements with MeTV for eight of the group's affiliates through 2015, and agreed to add the classic television network on digital subchannels of KOCO-TV and its sister stations in [[WCVB-TV|Boston]], [[WBAL-TV|Baltimore]], [[KCRA-TV|Sacramento]] and [[WXII-TV|Greensboro]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Me-TV Adds Five More Hearst Stations|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/60965/metv-adds-five-more-hearst-stations|website=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheck Media|date=July 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Where to Watch Me-TV: KOCO|url=http://metvnetwork.com/wherewatch.php?marketID=211|website=[[MeTV]]|publisher=[[Weigel Broadcasting]]|accessdate=October 1, 2012}}</ref> The This TV affiliation rights for the Oklahoma City affiliation were subsequently acquired by Family Broadcasting Group, then-owner of independent station [[KSBI]] (channel 52, now a MyNetworkTV affiliate); however, because KOCO's MeTV contract did not commence for another two weeks, KSBI was forced to share the This TV affiliation with KOCO-DT2 after KSBI-DT2 began carrying the latter network on September 17, 2012. KOCO-DT2 affiliated with MeTV on October 1, 2012, at which time, KSBI became the market's exclusive This TV affiliate.<ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO-TV announces debut of Me-TV Oklahoma City|url=http://www.koco.com/article/koco-tv-announces-debut-of-me-tv-oklahoma-city/4290247|website=KOCO-TV|publisher=Hearst Television|date=October 2, 2012|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> On August 28, 2017, KOCO-DT2 switched to a 16:9 [[widescreen]] standard definition format; prior to the upgrade, ABC and syndicated programs presented in widescreen were transmitted on KOCO-DT2 in a horizontally compressed format to fit the subchannel's 4:3 aspect frame.\n\n==Digital television==\n===Digital channels===\nThe station's digital signal is [[Multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref>{{cite web|title=RabbitEars TV Query for KOCO|url=http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=KOCO#station|website=[[RabbitEars]]|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 5.1 || [[1080i]] || rowspan=\"2\"|[[16:9]] || KOCO-HD || Main KOCO-TV programming / [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n|-\n| 5.2 || rowspan=\"2\"|[[480i]] || KOCO-ME || [[MeTV]]\n|-\n|}\n\nKOCO-TV is one of several ABC-affiliated stations owned by Hearst (including, among others, WCVB-TV in [[Boston]], [[WMUR-TV]] in [[Manchester, New Hampshire]], [[WTAE-TV]] in [[Pittsburgh]], [[KETV]] in [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]] and KMBC-TV in Kansas City) that transmit the primary feed of its digital signal and all high definition programming it carries in the [[1080i]] HD format, instead of ABC's preferred [[720p]] format.\n\n===Analog-to-digital conversion===\nKOCO-TV began transmitting a [[digital terrestrial television|digital television]] signal on [[Very high frequency|VHF]] channel 7 on November 1, 2002. The station discontinued regular programming on its analog signal, over VHF channel 5, on June 12, 2009, as part of the [[Digital television transition in the United States|federally mandated transitioned from analog to digital television]].<ref name=\"Analog to Digital\">{{cite web|title=DTV Tentative Channel Designations for the First and the Second Rounds|url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf|publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]]|accessdate=June 28, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf|archivedate=August 29, 2013}}</ref> The station's digital signal remained on its pre-transition VHF channel 7, using PSIP to display KOCO-TV's [[virtual channel]] as 5 (corresponding to its analog channel) on digital television receivers. After the switchover, the marginal reductions to the broadcast radius of KOCO's digital signal created some reception gaps in parts of southern and north-central Oklahoma that previously, at best, received [[Broadcast range|Grade B]] coverage from its analog signal. In May 2010, the station installed a new digital transmitter antenna and dish on the Britton Road tower to help extend KOCO's signal reception to the affected areas.<ref>{{cite news|title=KOCO Step Closer To New Antenna|url=http://www.koco.com/news/23633190/detail.html|website=KOCO-TV|publisher=Hearst Television|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305202325/http://www.koco.com/news/23633190/detail.html|archivedate=March 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Repeater stations==\nTo reach viewers throughout the 34 counties comprising the Oklahoma City Designated Market Area, KOCO-TV extends its over-the-air coverage area through a network of five [[Low-power broadcasting|low-power]] [[Broadcast relay station#Broadcast translators|digital translator stations]] \u2013 all of which transmit using PSIP virtual channel 5 \u2013 encompassing much of [[Western Oklahoma]] that distribute its programming beyond the {{convert|75|mi|km|adj=mid|-wide}} range of its broadcast signal.\n\n===Digital low-power translator stations===\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = List of KOCO-TV translators\n}}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"white-space: nowrap; font-size: 80%; height: 1em\"\n|-\n| '''Station'''\n| '''[[City of license]]'''\n| '''Channels<br>''(Digital)'''''\n| '''Owner'''\n| '''First air date'''<br>{{specify|date=September 2019}}\n| '''Former<br>callsigns'''\n| '''Former channel<br>number(s)'''\n| '''ERP<br>''(Digital)'''''\n| '''HAAT<br>''(Digital)'''''\n| '''Facility ID'''\n| '''Transmitter<br>coordinates'''\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''K22MA-D'''\n| [[Elk City, Oklahoma|Elk City]]\n| 22 (UHF)\n| Oklahoma Community Television, LLC\n| {{Start date and age|2007|p=y}}\n| K43KT-D (2007\u20132010)\n| '''Digital:''' 43 (UHF; 2007\u20132018)\n| 0.46&nbsp;kW\n| {{convert|403|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 168300\n| {{coord|35|21|25|N|99|16|9|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=K22MA-D}}\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''K18HX-D'''\n| [[Hollis, Oklahoma|Hollis]]\n| 18 (UHF)\n| Oklahoma Community Television, LLC\n| {{Start date and age|2007|p=y}}\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| 0.95&nbsp;kW\n| {{convert|397|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 168325\n| {{coord|34|44|30.2|N|99|48|31.4|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=K18HX-D}}\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''K24MD-D'''\n| [[Sayre, Oklahoma|Sayre]]\n| 24 (UHF)\n| Oklahoma Community Television, LLC\n| {{Start date and age|2007|p=y}}\n| K42IB-D (2007\u20132018)\n| '''Digital:''' 42 (UHF; 2007\u20132018)\n| 0.39&nbsp;kW\n| {{convert|518|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 168310\n| {{coord|35|9|5|N|99|42|51|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=K24MD-D}}\